WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
[Amit Varma]: Here's a fundamental value of mine that shapes the way I look at the world. I believe that

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:14.360
[Amit Varma]: two consenting adults should be able to interact with each other in any way they want as long

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:18.800
[Amit Varma]: as they're not infringing on the rights of anyone else. As long as there is consent and

00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:23.360
[Amit Varma]: it's not harming anyone, it's morally wrong to get in their way. Now this holds true in

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:28.320
[Amit Varma]: any context. This interaction could be in the bedroom or in the marketplace. And yet

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:32.880
[Amit Varma]: you will find people of different ideologies that will oppose such freedom in one domain

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:37.880
[Amit Varma]: or the other. Some want to clamp down on personal freedoms, invoking shady notions of collective

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:43.060
[Amit Varma]: morality. Some want to clamp down on economic freedoms. All of these restrictions are morally

00:00:43.060 --> 00:00:48.340
[Amit Varma]: wrong. And not only are they morally wrong, they lead to terrible consequences. Societies

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:54.480
[Amit Varma]: grow and prosper through the free exchange of ideas. Equally, societies grow and prosper

00:00:54.480 --> 00:01:01.080
[Amit Varma]: through the free exchange of goods and services. That is why voluntary interaction is so amazing.

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:04.920
[Amit Varma]: It leaves both people better off. I like to invoke a phrase coined by the writer John

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:09.560
[Amit Varma]: Stossel for this, the double thank you moment. Let's say you go to a cafe to buy a cup of

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:13.920
[Amit Varma]: coffee. When you hand over the money, the cashier says thank you. When you receive your

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:18.960
[Amit Varma]: coffee, you say thank you. You value the coffee more than the money. It's the other way around

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:24.800
[Amit Varma]: for the cafe. Both of you are better off. This is magic. This is the secret of economic

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:29.440
[Amit Varma]: growth. Across the world, societies became prosperous when people started interacting

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:34.460
[Amit Varma]: in such positive some ways. There's a direct correlation between the degree of economic

00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:40.240
[Amit Varma]: freedom and the rate of growth anywhere. This is why after millennia of not much happening,

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:45.520
[Amit Varma]: millennia of pretty much everybody being poor, the last two centuries have lifted our standards

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:51.720
[Amit Varma]: of living so much. Globalization, trade, consenting adults. Despite this, markets often get a

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:57.160
[Amit Varma]: bad rap. Here are a few reasons for this. One, it is intuitive for us to think of the

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:02.080
[Amit Varma]: world in zero-sum ways. If someone is getting richer, we assume it has to be at the expense

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:07.980
[Amit Varma]: of someone else. But this is not true. All voluntary interaction is a win-win game. Two,

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:12.340
[Amit Varma]: we confuse cronyism for free markets, while they are opposite things. In a free market,

00:02:12.340 --> 00:02:16.460
[Amit Varma]: the state looks after the rule of law and there are no barriers to entry. Competition

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:21.960
[Amit Varma]: benefits everyone. But big companies often lobby the state, even purchase the state,

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:28.040
[Amit Varma]: to get coercive laws made that restrict competition, protect their own incompetence and harm consumers

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:33.240
[Amit Varma]: and citizens. This creates the opposite of a free market. But people often mistake this

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:38.440
[Amit Varma]: for markets themselves. Three, through history, including our own history in India, we have

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:43.440
[Amit Varma]: seen rapacious companies get together with a coercive state that has a monopoly on violence

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:48.840
[Amit Varma]: to exploit the people. This is exactly what the East India Company did and it causes an

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:54.280
[Amit Varma]: irrational distrust of markets, while it should really cause a rational skepticism of state

00:02:54.280 --> 00:03:00.520
[Amit Varma]: power. Four, some of us are entranced by an engineering mindset, the notion that we are

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:04.600
[Amit Varma]: smart enough to design the world from the top down. This is what Frederick Hayek called

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:10.320
[Amit Varma]: the fatal conceit. And it is, of course, a fallacy. Five, there are ideologies that build

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:15.400
[Amit Varma]: a narrative of compassion around themselves and rely on using state power to suppress

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:20.200
[Amit Varma]: individual rights, whether in the bedroom or the marketplace. And these are often couched

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:25.000
[Amit Varma]: in good intentions. These good intentions are seen. The terrible consequences of the

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.600
[Amit Varma]: coercion they involve are unseen. So we need to be clear-eyed about this. At both a moral

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:38.120
[Amit Varma]: and consequential level, freedom is good in every domain. And that is why India's liberalisation

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:44.400
[Amit Varma]: of 1991 was such a big deal. It increased our economic freedom, empowered individuals

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:52.840
[Amit Varma]: and lifted millions of people out of poverty. It was a humanitarian miracle.

