00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:14.240
[Amit Varma]: enterprise, which brought over a quarter of a billion people out of poverty. But the reforms

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:20.080
[Amit Varma]: could have gone further, and the momentum eventually ended. Between 1991 and 2011, we

00:04:20.080 --> 00:04:25.360
[Amit Varma]: had a golden period. Since then, we are on a downward trajectory. What makes it worse

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:31.160
[Amit Varma]: is that over 60% of India is born after that liberalisation. So though they reap the benefits

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:36.260
[Amit Varma]: of those reforms, they don't realise what a big deal they were. They don't have a memory

00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:40.920
[Amit Varma]: of the times before those reforms. In some cases, they even idealise the ideologies that

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:46.840
[Amit Varma]: kept us poor for decades and caused so much suffering. They look only at the intentions

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:51.560
[Amit Varma]: and not the outcomes. In an attempt to correct that, the Mercator Centre at George Mason

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:56.680
[Amit Varma]: University, led by my friend and frequent guest Shruti Rajgopalan, have started something

00:04:56.680 --> 00:05:02.320
