[Amit Varma]: up rather by 80s, I'm just thinking of my own childhood, but your life kind of growing

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:13.920
[Amit Varma]: up because the fulcrum of this episode in a sense is the 91 reform. So obviously, it's

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:17.280
[Amit Varma]: not as if everything happened at that fixed point in time, something's happened before

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:21.560
[Amit Varma]: something's happened later. But I find that today, you know, given that more than 60%

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:27.760
[Amit Varma]: of India is born after 91 doesn't really have a sense of what life was like before that.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:33.880
[Amit Varma]: And often have this really idealized view of, you know, what India was like before that.

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:38.680
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I'll chip in as well with what little memories I have, though I was, you

00:08:38.680 --> 00:08:43.000
[Amit Varma]: know, relatively incredibly privileged in those times. But Shruti, why don't we start

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.200
[Amit Varma]: with you? Because in your wonderful essay on the part of the 91 project, one of the

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:52.400
[Amit Varma]: things I liked about that essay was that you brought the personal in also, where you speak

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:56.480
[Amit Varma]: about what life was like in the 70s and 80s, and what your grandmother would do differently

00:08:56.480 --> 00:09:00.720
[Amit Varma]: and what your mother would do differently today and all of that. So give me a sense

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:03.640
[Amit Varma]: of what life was like back then.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:11.000
[Guest 1]: So you know, I was incredibly young when the reform moment happened. But for most of us,

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.880
[Guest 1]: like anyone's childhood memories, you only know what you see around you. So it's not

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:21.640
[Guest 1]: like when I was a kid, and I was growing up in like, you know, mostly socialism, very

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:27.040
[Guest 1]: few goods and, you know, variety in goods in terms of consumer goods, right. So, you

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:32.120
[Guest 1]: know, very much grew up in the two brands of chocolate, two kinds of cola drinks sort

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:37.000
[Guest 1]: of world, right. And it wasn't unusual, simply because we didn't know better. It wasn't like

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.480
[Guest 1]: we were privy to this whole other world out there, where there were these amazing things

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:47.640
[Guest 1]: that were available. So for me, two things happened simultaneously. Somewhere around

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:54.520
[Guest 1]: 1991-92, my parents had to go abroad for a stint. And they were real troopers, they took

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:58.840
[Guest 1]: me and my sister, they kind of like more than troopers, I think they were a little bit crazy.

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:04.120
[Guest 1]: They just yanked me and my sister out of school. And they said that you learn more traveling

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:09.080
[Guest 1]: across Europe. So you know, just come along with us. So we basically didn't go to school

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:14.920
[Guest 1]: for more than half a year. And my mother's a musician. So we sort of traveled with her.

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:21.800
[Guest 1]: And it was really the first brush with markets, right? And the idea was all the myths that

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:27.200
[Guest 1]: we read in our textbook was India is poor, India is overpopulated. There are too many

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:32.040
[Guest 1]: people trying to go for too few goods and things like that. But one of the stark things

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:36.320
[Guest 1]: you realize when you're in Europe is that the places you enjoy the most are the places

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:41.440
[Guest 1]: that are crowded, right? And the places that are not crowded that have too few people,

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:46.000
[Guest 1]: they are rich, they have things, but the stores close at four in the evening, right? Nothing

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:50.800
[Guest 1]: is that easily available. Even the streets are sometimes not lit in some of these, you

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:55.720
[Guest 1]: know, Dutch villages and things like that kind of feels pretty off. And the really big

00:10:55.720 --> 00:11:00.840
[Guest 1]: cities which are noisy and polluted. And you know, when you go to London or you go to Vienna,

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:04.320
[Guest 1]: those are the incredible places. So you know, one thing became very clear that there's something

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:08.600
[Guest 1]: about this overpopulation thing, which is very off that I, you know, kind of viscerally

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:14.880
[Guest 1]: figured out that I seem to like these places. The other was just that there are possibilities

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:19.560
[Guest 1]: of things that are available when you go to a store, right? You just go to the supermarket

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:25.280
[Guest 1]: and it's no longer two types of things. My mother spent our entire childhood, my sister

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:31.320
[Guest 1]: and I have identical clothes because my mother bought cloth, took it to the tailor and got

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:35.080
[Guest 1]: it stitched. And when you're very young, there's too much leftover cloths. You're basically

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:40.760
[Guest 1]: making, you know, both kids wear identical clothes. Our childhood pictures are ridiculous

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:47.120
[Guest 1]: and will never be revealed. So those are sort of the biggest memories. Now I have a very

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:50.920
[Guest 1]: different point of view when I look back at my childhood, because now I'm a professional

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:55.560
[Guest 1]: economist, right? So now when I look back at my childhood, I'm not just looking at it

00:11:55.560 --> 00:12:00.200
[Guest 1]: from the point of view of what my mom did or my grandmother did. I have an analytical

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:05.120
[Guest 1]: framework I can impose and now understand why this was happening. So for instance, my

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:10.200
[Guest 1]: grandmother used to spend pretty much every day in the afternoon, like post lunch and

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:16.400
[Guest 1]: before dinner, she would go through all the rice, dal, wheat, and, you know, kind of separate

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:22.320
[Guest 1]: the kankad. You know, there's a kankad and pathar. That's how many there would be, right?

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:28.240
[Guest 1]: Another instance is we would not buy atta in a packet. Okay. We would actually get the

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:32.520
[Guest 1]: wheat. My grandmother would do the separation thing and we would take it to the chakki.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:36.960
[Guest 1]: Okay. And we would be allowed inside the chakki where they would watch and make sure that

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:42.440
[Guest 1]: nothing is adulterated, right? Nothing is mixed into the atta and it's really pure.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:47.000
[Guest 1]: These are very strange things to do. Okay. If you think about it, it means you basically

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.680
[Guest 1]: don't trust branding, right? You don't trust the reputation of any good. There is too much

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:58.360
[Guest 1]: adulteration in the market, right? And now when I look back, I'm like, oh, I understand why there

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:03.240
[Guest 1]: was so much rampant adulteration in the market. It's because prices are controlled because

00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:06.880
[Guest 1]: of the Essential Commodities Act and, you know, everything that follows. And now you

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:12.280
[Guest 1]: get everything at a very specific control price at the ration shop. So there are two

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:16.960
[Guest 1]: ways of doing this. Either the ration shop people just, you know, kind of escape and

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:22.660
[Guest 1]: they just siphon off all the wheat to the black market and they try to make a killing.

00:13:22.660 --> 00:13:26.400
[Guest 1]: But still, there are going to be people standing outside the ration shop and protest, right?

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:32.120
[Guest 1]: So you've got to give them something. So what is a way to both siphon off some of the wheat

00:13:32.120 --> 00:13:39.400
[Guest 1]: and rice and dal while also serving the poor notionally? It's just you mix it with, you

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:45.120
[Guest 1]: know, all this other pathar and kankar until it reaches a weight where the market price

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:49.480
[Guest 1]: will compensate whatever the control price is, right? Because now you've mixed it in

00:13:49.480 --> 00:13:53.200
[Guest 1]: and the weight has increased. So these were the sorts of things that were going on. Of

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:57.680
[Guest 1]: course, as a 7-8 year old, I have no idea that, you know, there's this entire socialist

00:13:57.680 --> 00:14:03.120
[Guest 1]: political economy at play. It was more that this is just how life is. The sort of like

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:11.000
[Guest 1]: aha moment really came, I think, maybe starting 1992-93. You get this big shift in consumer

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:17.240
[Guest 1]: goods, you know, and some of it is pre-1991. Like, you know, Pepsi, drinking Pepsi was

00:14:17.240 --> 00:14:22.000
[Guest 1]: like a major thing in our life. My sister loved Michael Jackson. Michael Jackson drinks

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:26.660
[Guest 1]: Pepsi. Pepsi must be amazing because Michael Jackson is amazing and all the other things

00:14:26.660 --> 00:14:31.760
[Guest 1]: that follow. But Pepsi actually came to India a few years before because of various, you

00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:36.440
[Guest 1]: know, deals that the government was literally trying to woo the company to come back and

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:42.520
[Guest 1]: set up plant and things like that. So some of this was already in motion. But by 1992-93,

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:50.240
[Guest 1]: you suddenly started seeing a lot more things. The second was you could finally import stuff,

00:14:50.240 --> 00:14:56.640
[Guest 1]: right? So you could get like a like a VHS recorder fairly easily or a CD player fairly

00:14:56.640 --> 00:15:01.680
[Guest 1]: easily, even if you couldn't get like CDs easily from a library. Those sorts of things

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:07.840
[Guest 1]: started becoming very common quickly in my childhood. And I remember that, you know,

00:15:07.840 --> 00:15:12.800
[Guest 1]: that moment being quite stark because we had just seen all these amazing, you know, variety

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:17.080
[Guest 1]: of goods. When we went abroad, we came back to India. And within a matter of three, four

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:21.240
[Guest 1]: years, you started getting the same things. And of course, you know, all the usual stuff.

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:27.200
[Guest 1]: I think we already managed to get a gas connection and a phone connection pre-liberalization.

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:31.720
[Guest 1]: But I remember it taking a long time. Right. So when the cell phone revolution happened

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:36.360
[Guest 1]: much later, when I was in college, that was sort of like a like an incredible thing. So

00:15:36.360 --> 00:15:43.000
[Guest 1]: some of this is like lived experience. Some of it is just when I look at childhood pictures

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.120
[Guest 1]: and I try and understand what the hell is going on in my household, I look at it as

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:52.560
[Guest 1]: a grown economist. And that's the way I make sense of my my childhood. So my memory can

00:15:52.560 --> 00:15:57.040
[Amit Varma]: be a little bit faulty on this. Yeah, I can I can imagine you asking your mother that,

00:15:57.040 --> 00:16:00.400
[Amit Varma]: hey, why did me and my sister always wear the same clothes? And she's like, you are

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:04.480
[Amit Varma]: an economist, you figure it out. And I'm really glad you brought up that overpopulation point

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:08.480
[Amit Varma]: because that's still a bogey that is being banded around. You know, we were taught in

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:13.520
[Amit Varma]: our textbooks that India's problem is too many people. I mean, India's problem is really

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:17.960
[Amit Varma]: bad governance, not too many people. You know, too many people is a great thing. People are

00:16:17.960 --> 00:16:22.800
[Amit Varma]: brains, not stomachs, their resources. And that's why in all of human history, what you

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:28.720
[Amit Varma]: see is a migration from places with less population density to places with more population density.

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:33.680
[Amit Varma]: That is why we go to cities. However much we may idealize village life, I don't think

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:39.520
[Amit Varma]: most of the listeners of this episode for that matter, are you know, living in say villages

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:44.360
[Amit Varma]: or whatever population is great, people are great. And every time a politician tells you

00:16:44.360 --> 00:16:48.160
[Amit Varma]: population is a problem, the politician is telling you you are the problem. That's again

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:52.640
[Amit Varma]: kind of resonant because with me in the 80s, because I was of course, a son of an IAS officer.

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:56.800
[Amit Varma]: So things like you know, I didn't have a scarcity of a telephone at home. But you know, as you

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:01.680
[Amit Varma]: were speaking, I just remembered an interesting incident when I was in the 11th standard,

00:17:01.680 --> 00:17:06.120
[Amit Varma]: which would be in the late 1980s. A girl who was my classmate in college just rang the

00:17:06.120 --> 00:17:11.200
[Amit Varma]: bell outside and I opened the door and she said, Hi, I was just passing by and I need

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:15.240
[Amit Varma]: to make an urgent phone call. Can I use your phone, please? I know you have a phone. So

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:20.200
[Amit Varma]: I said, Okay, so she came in, she made a phone call, and then she went off. And of course,

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:23.960
[Amit Varma]: I was pretty clueless and perhaps still am. So it took me many years to figure out that

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:29.040
[Amit Varma]: the purpose of her visit wasn't necessarily the phone call. But that's how scarcities

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:34.160
[Amit Varma]: were. It would take you five years, 10 years on a waiting list to get a phone. You know,

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:38.640
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode with Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley, who writes that fantastic newsletter with

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:43.500
[Amit Varma]: Pranay Kutasane. And the episode was titled Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley's father's scooter.

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:48.160
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned scooters in your essay where you point out that a second hand scooter actually

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:52.600
[Amit Varma]: cost more than a new scooter because a new scooter would take 10 years to come and I

00:17:52.600 --> 00:17:57.080
[Amit Varma]: want to read out this lovely para from your piece where you write quote, is this the first

00:17:57.080 --> 00:18:02.220
[Amit Varma]: time I'm quoting you at yourself in the show? Well, okay, it's very freaky, probably. Yeah.

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:06.720
[Amit Varma]: So you're right, quote, it got so bad that when a girl child was born, well wishers would

00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:11.100
[Amit Varma]: only half in jest, suggest to the parents that they should immediately book a scooter,

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:15.120
[Amit Varma]: so it would arrive in time for the wedding. This was reminiscent of the old Soviet Union

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:19.480
[Amit Varma]: joke about a man paying for an automobile. The clerk tells him it will be delivered in

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:24.920
[Amit Varma]: 10 years. The man asked morning or afternoon, what difference does it make response a clerk?

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:29.160
[Amit Varma]: Well, the plumber is coming in the morning, stop good. And it was kind of the same with

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:32.320
[Amit Varma]: everything, not just phones. Like, you know, another thing I remember was that back in

00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:37.040
[Amit Varma]: those days, it was a very, very big deal if someone went abroad to study, right? It was

00:18:37.040 --> 00:18:41.800
[Amit Varma]: a huge deal. You know, you had to be the elite among the elite for that to happen. While

00:18:41.800 --> 00:18:48.000
[Amit Varma]: today that is so commonplace. The opportunities are just insane. You know, an airline flight,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.400
[Amit Varma]: even for a privileged kid like me was such a big deal. flights were so expensive. And

00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:57.080
[Amit Varma]: like I remember looking at the prices 15 years later and realizing that they are the same,

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:00.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, and obviously inflation had happened. And in real terms, they were way, way cheaper.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:05.400
[Amit Varma]: And when that opened up like today, you know, smartphones even are so affordable, so many

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:11.020
[Amit Varma]: more people can fly. And again, I remember what a struggle it was to get the books you

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:14.720
[Amit Varma]: wanted the movies you wanted. I remember in fact, when satellite television came something

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:20.080
[Amit Varma]: that you mentioned, just watching star movies or whatever the equivalent was in freaking

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:25.360
[Amit Varma]: bewilderment that they are showing movies all day. I don't have to wait for that once

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:30.320
[Amit Varma]: a week when Doordarshan will show something all day. I can watch seven movies a day. It

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:34.640
[Amit Varma]: was mind blowing. But before I kind of forget, yeah, go ahead.

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:39.600
[Guest 1]: I want to add something to the to the Bajaj thing. You know, the actually the Soviet Union

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:45.200
[Guest 1]: joke Alex told me Alex Davrok told me that joke and I have appropriated it. So you know,

00:19:45.200 --> 00:19:50.560
[Guest 1]: the Bajaj thing, there are like, I just want to unpeel that because it's a good example

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:54.920
[Guest 1]: of what was going on and why it was happening. Right. So on the one hand, you're like, oh,

00:19:54.920 --> 00:19:59.280
[Guest 1]: you had to wait a long time to get a Bajaj scooter. Right. Now, that seems a little bit

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:03.400
[Guest 1]: like what's happening right now during the pandemic. I just moved homes. I ordered some

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:07.600
[Guest 1]: furniture and because of all the supply chain, you know, complications, it's going to take

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:13.000
[Guest 1]: like six weeks for some very basic furniture to show up. But that's not the reason that

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:18.720
[Guest 1]: it was delayed. It wasn't like a pandemic or something like that. It was more endemic

00:20:18.720 --> 00:20:25.360
[Guest 1]: than that. And the reason is that the original command and control system, they thought that

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:30.760
[Guest 1]: all the means of production, right, all your typical iron, steel, these sorts of things,

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:35.400
[Guest 1]: they're very scarce. Right. We need to make sure that these things are used well and not

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:40.480
[Guest 1]: wasted. And the way we ensure that it's used well in a closed economy where people can't

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:47.120
[Guest 1]: just go to global markets to just buy as much steel as they want is to ensure that the government

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:52.960
[Guest 1]: allows people based on priority on what they can and cannot produce. Right. So there's

00:20:52.960 --> 00:21:00.440
[Guest 1]: an order of priority list on who can use what kind of steel. Now, once you make this kind

00:21:00.440 --> 00:21:04.480
[Guest 1]: of five year plan document, which we can talk about in detail, and it's fairly complicated

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:08.080
[Guest 1]: to make this and you still get it terribly, terribly wrong, it can't be done. But let's

00:21:08.080 --> 00:21:12.840
[Guest 1]: say that you attempt this kind of five year plan document. You still need to figure out

00:21:12.840 --> 00:21:17.160
[Guest 1]: that, hey, I have X tons of steel that we're producing in the country. And now what are

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:21.520
[Guest 1]: the priority sectors? OK, so they'll have an order of priority. You know, some of it

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:26.040
[Guest 1]: has to go to heavy machinery, blah, blah, blah. Now, scooters and Vespas is somewhere

00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:31.040
[Guest 1]: in the list of priority, right? Godrej, Almera is somewhere in that list of priorities. So

00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:37.600
[Guest 1]: you keep going down bicycles, spectacles, whatever. The thing is, they realize somewhere

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:42.600
[Guest 1]: down the line that people actually want more scooters than you think they should want.

00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:48.760
[Guest 1]: Right. That's what's really going on. Right. So all these young men who are now, you know,

00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:54.080
[Guest 1]: in the 70s with like an explosion in population growth, these young men, why do they want

00:21:54.080 --> 00:21:59.640
[Guest 1]: these scooters? So now Bajaj says, but they want them. So what do we do? And, you know,

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:03.220
[Guest 1]: Rahul Bajaj just talked about this. He keeps going back to the Ministry of Commerce and

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:07.720
[Guest 1]: industry and saying, I want an expansion permit because lots of people want scooters. Now,

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:12.200
[Guest 1]: what normally happens when you limit the number of scooters that can be produced, but more

00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:17.120
[Guest 1]: people want it. Right. The price of scooters will go up. But when you're in a socialist

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:23.040
[Guest 1]: economy, you cannot allow Rahul Bajaj to profit from the system you put in place in the first

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:27.920
[Guest 1]: place. Right. To make sure that resources are used appropriately and they're not wasted

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:33.960
[Guest 1]: and so on and so forth, which means now not only will Rahul Bajaj have a limit or a restriction

00:22:33.960 --> 00:22:38.560
[Guest 1]: on where he can set up his firm, how much he can produce, how much steel input he can

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:44.660
[Guest 1]: use, how many workers he is allowed to have on the factory floor versus in the sales department.

00:22:44.660 --> 00:22:48.360
[Guest 1]: These are times where if you had to shift someone from the sales office to the front

00:22:48.360 --> 00:22:51.700
[Guest 1]: office or the factory floor, you needed to go back to the government, get permission

00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:55.880
[Guest 1]: and come back and make the switch. Right. These kinds of times. So not only do we have

00:22:55.880 --> 00:23:01.280
[Guest 1]: to do that, now we also have to control the consumer end. Right. People want this too

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:04.740
[Guest 1]: much and they're going to drive the price up because they're stupid. They want these

00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:09.340
[Guest 1]: Vespa Bajaj Vespas. They shouldn't want them. So now how do we control the price? We put

00:23:09.340 --> 00:23:15.060
[Guest 1]: in price controls. So now an automatic consequence of price controls and not being allowed to

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:21.480
[Guest 1]: expand supply because you have these expansion permits which are required is you're going

00:23:21.480 --> 00:23:26.400
[Guest 1]: to have quantity demanded far exceeds quantity supplied. There's a very classic shortage.

00:23:26.400 --> 00:23:32.360
[Guest 1]: You can have long lines. Right. Sometimes. And in this instance, the long lines is replaced

00:23:32.360 --> 00:23:36.680
[Guest 1]: by other things. So one of them is just time preference. Right. So the point that you were

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:41.200
[Guest 1]: talking about, which is a second hand scooter today is more valuable than a first hand scooter

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:45.960
[Guest 1]: 10 years from today, because now I can have it today. But it also pops up in this marriage

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:50.320
[Guest 1]: example because if you talk, I'm too young for this. So maybe I'm going to anytime I

00:23:50.320 --> 00:23:56.360
[Guest 1]: want to make like old people jokes, I'm just going to dump it on you guys. But Godrej Almera's

00:23:56.360 --> 00:24:03.320
[Guest 1]: right Bajaj scooters are all number one dowry demands. Right. Because that is a moment when

00:24:03.320 --> 00:24:08.780
[Guest 1]: you really know someone will go a very long way to skip the line. Right. So Bajaj scooters

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:12.900
[Guest 1]: are not mostly being driven by men, not so many by women, but it's always the bride's

00:24:12.900 --> 00:24:18.200
[Guest 1]: father who's like struggling to get these things. So there are about six kinds of socialist

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:25.040
[Guest 1]: command and control problems going on for this joke to become so endemic to Indian life.

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:30.460
[Guest 1]: Right. So it's not just any shortage, because Indians also face all sorts of shortages.

00:24:30.460 --> 00:24:34.680
[Guest 1]: Sometimes you have to wait in a long line to get an iPhone. This is not that kind of

00:24:34.680 --> 00:24:38.720
[Guest 1]: shortage. I just want to make that clear, because I don't think this is the sort of

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:43.760
[Guest 1]: shortage that most Indians modern day in modern day life have experienced.

00:24:43.760 --> 00:24:48.960
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely. So, Ajay, you've been silent all this while, though not silent all these years.

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:54.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me what was life like for you kind of growing up in India, I'm guessing that

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:58.800
[Amit Varma]: there were a lot of things which were normalized, which felt normal. And over a period of time,

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:02.640
[Amit Varma]: you actually start as you know, as you become an economist, you apply your frame to it and

00:25:02.640 --> 00:25:06.840
[Amit Varma]: you kind of figure out, you begin to break it down and understand exactly what was going

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:12.040
[Amit Varma]: on. But, you know, give me a glimpse of sort of what it was like for you in the 70s and

00:25:12.040 --> 00:25:13.040
[Guest 2]: 80s.

00:25:13.040 --> 00:25:18.680
[Guest 2]: So I grew up in the 70s. And some of my more interesting memories from that period are

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:26.120
[Guest 2]: my sisters and I would venture out in the morning to stand in line for the rationed

00:25:26.120 --> 00:25:33.160
[Guest 2]: access to milk and bread and butter and cheese. There were long queues. And so it was efficient

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:38.560
[Guest 2]: for parents to have multiple children because you could parallel process on those queues.

00:25:38.560 --> 00:25:45.760
[Guest 2]: And it just seems unbelievable that there should be shortages of milk, of bread, of

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:52.280
[Guest 2]: butter and of cheese. But that's the way it was. These things were just not available.

00:25:52.280 --> 00:25:59.280
[Guest 2]: I remember pervasive lack of access to books and music and so on. So getting books was

00:25:59.280 --> 00:26:04.400
[Guest 2]: a big deal. I mean, I grew up in a house with 6000 books, but each of those books was a

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:08.560
[Guest 2]: treasure and it was like a sustained long range project that we're going to get this

00:26:08.560 --> 00:26:13.760
[Guest 2]: book and it would be like a big task before we would get this book.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:21.840
[Guest 2]: I was at the Hostel 3 at IIT Bombay in 1983 and we had an LP of The Dark Side of the Moon

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:27.920
[Guest 2]: by Pink Floyd and nothing else. Why? Because that was the only LP that was released by

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:33.600
[Guest 2]: HMV in India. There was no other Pink Floyd content. So Susan Thomas got Wish You Were

00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:39.640
[Guest 2]: Here from Kuwait and that was like our first precious LP which could play Wish You Were

00:26:39.640 --> 00:26:45.840
[Guest 2]: Here. So it was a strange world. It was a funny experience growing up through all that.

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:51.960
[Guest 2]: My father was an economist and, for example, we got to read Milton Friedman's Free to

00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:57.880
[Guest 2]: Choose in 1976. So we were very much aware of that intellectual discussion around how

00:26:57.880 --> 00:27:03.920
[Guest 2]: this whole thing is broken. So we could rage against an incomprehensibly stupid system,

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:12.000
[Guest 2]: but we also lived in it. I also remember, I first went abroad to do my PhD. This was

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:18.600
[Guest 2]: in 1987. And I vividly remember that in Los Angeles in 1987, for the first time in my

00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:23.640
[Guest 2]: life, I saw a highway. For the first time in my life, I saw a CD player. For the first

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:28.920
[Guest 2]: time in my life, I heard a CD. These were things that didn't exist in India.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:34.520
[Amit Varma]: Magnificent. You know, before we talk about 91, I really do want to talk about 1947 as

00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:40.320
[Amit Varma]: well. You know, it seems necessary. It wasn't that, you know, you had a bunch of policies

00:27:40.320 --> 00:27:45.400
[Amit Varma]: put in place by one person. And, you know, and it was an accident and historical accident

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:48.820
[Amit Varma]: and we suffered for that reason. And then eventually we overturned some of the policies

00:27:48.820 --> 00:27:53.360
[Amit Varma]: and things get better. It was much more than that. There was a certain way of thinking

00:27:53.360 --> 00:27:58.440
[Amit Varma]: that was pervasive in those times. And before we actually get down to talking about the

00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:02.720
[Amit Varma]: ways of thinking, especially of, you know, Nehru and his influences and so on, a sort

00:28:02.720 --> 00:28:06.640
[Amit Varma]: of a counterfactual question, because if you look at the leaders of that time, you actually

00:28:06.640 --> 00:28:11.760
[Amit Varma]: see different ideologies. It is not necessarily the case that it is inevitable that India

00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:16.720
[Amit Varma]: would have set upon this path. You know, you had people like Raj Gopalachari and Patel

00:28:16.720 --> 00:28:22.200
[Amit Varma]: who were of a more liberal bent as far as markets were concerned. And you also had people

00:28:22.200 --> 00:28:28.720
[Amit Varma]: who were far more to the left than, say, Nehru himself was. So on one hand, it is a popular

00:28:28.720 --> 00:28:33.040
[Amit Varma]: and largely correct notion that Nehru was a creature of his times. This was the temper

00:28:33.040 --> 00:28:37.920
[Amit Varma]: of the times. Nobody at that time knew the reality of the Soviet Union. It was natural

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:43.040
[Amit Varma]: to kind of admire them for what they did. And Friedman hadn't written his books. Hayek

00:28:43.040 --> 00:28:46.940
[Amit Varma]: was an obscure economist somewhere. But on the other hand, it's also kind of true that

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:52.160
[Amit Varma]: there were other directions we could have taken. And this is not just in terms of economics.

00:28:52.160 --> 00:28:56.640
[Amit Varma]: It's also just in terms of so much else, the direction our politics took, the constitution

00:28:56.640 --> 00:29:01.920
[Amit Varma]: that we came up with, all of that. So when you look back on that period in history, is

00:29:01.920 --> 00:29:06.240
[Amit Varma]: there a sense of perhaps an opportunity lost? Is there a sense that, hey, it could have

00:29:06.240 --> 00:29:10.840
[Amit Varma]: been worse? Like one point so many people make is that the fact that India stayed together,

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:16.640
[Amit Varma]: that the center held, is itself a kind of a miracle because many such previous experiments

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:24.760
[Amit Varma]: just fell apart after colonialism was defeated. So what's kind of your sense of that, Ajay?

00:29:24.760 --> 00:29:30.140
[Guest 2]: I'm closer to the position that if you and I had been co-pilots with Nehru standing in

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:34.840
[Guest 2]: the 20s and 30s and 40s, we would have been closer to those positions. So let's look at

00:29:34.840 --> 00:29:39.840
[Guest 2]: that world. At that time, the argument would be made that, look, the Great Depression showed

00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:45.560
[Guest 2]: that the simple application of free markets doesn't work so well. Folks like John Maynard

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:52.960
[Guest 2]: Keynes were very keen to protect some basic decency and liberal democracy because as they

00:29:52.960 --> 00:30:00.680
[Guest 2]: saw it, the alternative was to collapse into national socialism in Germany or communism

00:30:00.680 --> 00:30:07.000
[Guest 2]: in Russia. So the idea was that the only way to stave off the barbarians was to give up

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:12.440
[Guest 2]: some of our economic freedom. Then when you look from the viewpoint of people in India,

00:30:12.440 --> 00:30:21.720
[Guest 2]: of the dreamers for India, there is no question that there was a remarkable economic development

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:28.520
[Guest 2]: project which took place in Japan after the Meiji Restoration and in Soviet Russia after

00:30:28.520 --> 00:30:34.400
[Guest 2]: the Russian Revolution. So people like Nehru dreamed that we don't have to take 400 years

00:30:34.400 --> 00:30:40.080
[Guest 2]: to do this. Can we do this in 40 years? And Nehru often talked about this tension that

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:45.160
[Guest 2]: you wanted the decency of British liberal democracy, but at the same time, you want

00:30:45.160 --> 00:30:52.360
[Guest 2]: to match British quality prosperity within 40 years, within 50 years, within 60 years.

00:30:52.360 --> 00:31:00.160
[Guest 2]: So they felt that state mobilization and the quaint term used by development economics,

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:04.600
[Guest 2]: which is a developmental state, was the way to do it. One more piece I want to add to

00:31:04.600 --> 00:31:10.160
[Guest 2]: that is the Second World War. During the Second World War, all over the world, governments

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:14.840
[Guest 2]: commandeered the economy. They normalized oppression because all parts of the economy

00:31:14.840 --> 00:31:19.880
[Guest 2]: were taken over by the government. I want to say in passing, there is a bit of that

00:31:19.880 --> 00:31:27.520
[Guest 2]: going on with COVID-19. War powers is a huge problem because it normalizes state control.

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:33.680
[Guest 2]: I have increasingly grown to think that by default, we tend to sink into oppression.

00:31:33.680 --> 00:31:40.280
[Guest 2]: It takes a tremendous effort by a people, by an intelligentsia, to claw back freedom.

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:44.680
[Guest 2]: That state oppression is the norm and freedom is the exception. And around the time of the

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:49.200
[Guest 2]: Second World War, all over the world, state domination was the norm and not the exception.

00:31:49.200 --> 00:31:54.600
[Guest 2]: Look at the UK, look at the US. They had price controls all the way to the 70s. If you read

00:31:54.600 --> 00:32:01.280
[Guest 2]: about Australia all the way to the early 80s, it sounds like the stupidity of Indian public

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:08.880
[Guest 2]: policy. So it took many years for the world to wake up and say, no, that's not the story

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:14.960
[Guest 2]: that makes sense. So I'm reasonably sympathetic to the kind of arguments and the debates that

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:20.280
[Guest 2]: took place in that period that led to a certain outcome. I envy a country like Taiwan, a country

00:32:20.280 --> 00:32:24.800
[Guest 2]: like South Korea that chose to walk a different path. I admire the people who did that, who

00:32:24.800 --> 00:32:32.600
[Guest 2]: led that. My reading of that period is that that was an exception and I fear that if the

00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:38.520
[Guest 2]: three of us were put in that place, in that time, in that consciousness, with that sense

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:43.680
[Guest 2]: of the dream for India, that we can do this rapidly. I'm much more of a conservative today

00:32:43.680 --> 00:32:48.400
[Guest 2]: in the sense that you let the world evolve organically. At that time, it was much more

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:54.960
[Guest 2]: fashionable to think that a developmentalist state will take a country by the scruff of

00:32:54.960 --> 00:33:00.480
[Guest 2]: the neck, will remake a country, will make a new man. There was all this dreaming about

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:06.800
[Guest 2]: the power of a state to reshape a society. So I'm sympathetic to what those guys did

00:33:06.800 --> 00:33:12.320
[Guest 2]: while recognizing in hindsight that those decisions were awful for the country.

00:33:12.320 --> 00:33:17.200
[Guest 1]: I would add a couple of things to this and go even a little farther back in history than

00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:22.960
[Guest 1]: what Ajay just said. You know, when you started Amit, you asked if this was like a foregone

00:33:22.960 --> 00:33:27.640
[Guest 1]: conclusion, right? If India was just predestined to do this. So some of it is, of course, there

00:33:27.640 --> 00:33:31.880
[Guest 1]: is an entire structure of war controls in place. You know, Nehru becomes the successor

00:33:31.880 --> 00:33:37.200
[Guest 1]: and he's very enamored by socialists and there's that going on. But I think if you go back

00:33:37.200 --> 00:33:44.880
[Guest 1]: maybe 50 years, 60 years before Nehru, you start seeing the big change happening, right?

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:49.120
[Guest 1]: So if you look at the Indian intellectuals of that time, you see the old guard, which

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:54.920
[Guest 1]: is, you know, Nauroji and you see Hume and you see, you know, Feroz Shah Mehta, right?

00:33:54.920 --> 00:34:01.240
[Guest 1]: All Gokhale, right? All these people, they are liberals somewhere influenced somewhere

00:34:01.240 --> 00:34:05.960
[Guest 1]: between, you know, Scottish enlightenment and like sort of Burkean conservatism, right?

00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:11.360
[Guest 1]: That's kind of where they are. But their experience, and this I have learned from studying, especially

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:19.440
[Guest 1]: Nauroji, is number one, that the British government, while they might pretend to be laissez-faire,

00:34:19.440 --> 00:34:24.000
[Guest 1]: it's really a mercantilist economy. It's not really functioning like a laissez-faire economy.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:29.320
[Guest 1]: And second, when it comes to India, it is acting as an extractive state, right? It's

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:34.600
[Guest 1]: a predatory state. So they're literally just, you know, stealing resources from India. They

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:40.240
[Guest 1]: are burdening, they are taxing. It's not like India is, you know, gloriful free trade internal

00:34:40.240 --> 00:34:47.560
[Guest 1]: network at that time. When they start lecturing on these things, the only allies that Nauroji

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:52.240
[Guest 1]: finds is the Fabians, right? So when he goes abroad, though he's standing for elections

00:34:52.240 --> 00:34:56.880
[Guest 1]: in the Liberal Party, and this is William Gladstone's Liberal Party, it's not any willy-nilly,

00:34:56.880 --> 00:35:02.520
[Guest 1]: you know, aaj ka Liberal Party. But the people who support Nauroji to even win the seat is

00:35:02.520 --> 00:35:06.560
[Guest 1]: the Social Democratic Federation, right? Like George Bernard Shaw says, I'm so glad the

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:11.600
[Guest 1]: SDF went Fabian and supported the Fabian candidate, who, by the way, is Dadavai Nauroji, right?

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:18.080
[Guest 1]: So the Fabian connection to Indian nationalist movement goes back about 50 years before Nehru.

00:35:18.080 --> 00:35:22.480
[Guest 1]: Nehru is a consequence of that. It's not that Lasky and George Bernard Shaw just whispered

00:35:22.480 --> 00:35:26.840
[Guest 1]: something in Nehru's ear and wow, he became Fabian, right? Some of this is, you know,

00:35:26.840 --> 00:35:31.680
[Guest 1]: by then, John Maynard Keynes has already written the obituary of laissez-faire. It's called

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:35.480
[Guest 1]: the end of laissez-faire, right? His essay. And you can see there's the shift going on,

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:41.200
[Guest 1]: right? So there is progressivism in the US, there is fascism, Nazism in Europe, there

00:35:41.200 --> 00:35:46.560
[Guest 1]: is full-blown, you know, command and control socialism happening in the Soviet. So, I mean,

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:50.840
[Guest 1]: the whole world is going in a particular direction. So that's part one. And there are very few

00:35:50.840 --> 00:35:56.760
[Guest 1]: naysayers, okay? Hayek is not obscure at that time. Just FYI. Okay, he's already written

00:35:56.760 --> 00:36:01.280
[Guest 1]: his, done his work on capital theory. He's taken on John Maynard Keynes. He's like the

00:36:01.280 --> 00:36:06.480
[Amit Varma]: world's most famous economist. I think for non-economists, he's kind of obscure. Actually,

00:36:06.480 --> 00:36:10.640
[Guest 1]: for non-economists of that time, he's not. I'll tell you why. Because when he writes

00:36:10.640 --> 00:36:16.400
[Guest 1]: The Road to Serfdom. That's 1945 or something, right? 44, yeah. Yeah, it's, but you know,

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:21.280
[Guest 1]: I mean, the Reader's Digest does a miniature version of it, like which, you know, major

00:36:21.280 --> 00:36:27.480
[Guest 1]: economist writing major books today is appearing the next day in Times of India or Stardust

00:36:27.480 --> 00:36:32.520
[Guest 1]: or, you know what I mean? So what I mean is that they had more connection to the intellectuals

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:38.680
[Guest 1]: than we imagine now. But leaving that aside, so, you know, B.K. Nehru says that all the

00:36:38.680 --> 00:36:44.160
[Guest 1]: people who were interested in the Indian nationalist movement went to LSE because LSE supported,

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:48.160
[Guest 1]: you know, Indian freedom. Why did LSE support it? Because the Fabians were so close to British

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:53.160
[Guest 1]: Labour Party. The Labour Party was more pro-Indian independence versus the Tories. So there is

00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:59.080
[Guest 1]: like a deep linkage here, which is at the time India got independence, given that it

00:36:59.080 --> 00:37:02.280
[Guest 1]: was the Labour Party in power. Right. And given that there were war controls and it's

00:37:02.280 --> 00:37:07.520
[Guest 1]: actually Nehru who succeeded, you know, it's almost predestined we're going to be Fabian.

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:13.720
[Guest 1]: But the second part is because this was going on, all the Indian intellectuals who actually

00:37:13.720 --> 00:37:20.400
[Guest 1]: went abroad to originally appear for the civil services were also exposed to this. Right.

00:37:20.400 --> 00:37:24.800
[Guest 1]: So for me, it's not interesting that Nehru was influenced by Lasky. For me, what is interesting

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:30.320
[Guest 1]: is Trilok Singh and P. N. Haksar are Lasky students. Right. P. N. Haksar is the most

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:34.800
[Guest 1]: important advisor to Indira Gandhi and Trilok Singh is like, you know, sort of the first

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:39.160
[Guest 1]: de facto writer of, you know, the first five year plan and things like that. So I think

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:42.800
[Guest 1]: that is the more interesting thing. You know, when Ajay said that if the three of us were

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:48.040
[Guest 1]: advising them, you know, maybe we would have gone with the vein of what things were or

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:52.880
[Guest 1]: we would have advised them differently. But that's the point. The army of people advising

00:37:52.880 --> 00:37:58.280
[Guest 1]: Nehru other than a very small minority, the people in the civil services, the people who

00:37:58.280 --> 00:38:04.240
[Guest 1]: are actually executing these war controls, they have largely wholesale bought into this

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:08.880
[Guest 1]: idea that development can be led by the state. They are very far from the Scottish Enlightenment

00:38:08.880 --> 00:38:15.640
[Guest 1]: view. And second, even post-World War, when the world is now saying, hey, we need to once

00:38:15.640 --> 00:38:21.960
[Guest 1]: again embrace liberalism and trade, the global consensus among elite economists says that's

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:27.080
[Guest 1]: the prescription for developed countries. Developing countries still need industrial

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:32.360
[Guest 1]: policy and import substitutions because they need to be protected. And, you know, it takes

00:38:32.360 --> 00:38:38.400
[Guest 1]: the South Korean and Taiwanese miracle in some sense for that view to change and like

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:42.720
[Guest 1]: Anne Kruger and Bhagwati and all to come along and say, hang on a second, I don't think this

00:38:42.720 --> 00:38:47.000
[Guest 1]: is a good prescription for developing countries. Developing countries are doing great without,

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:50.920
[Guest 1]: you know, industrial policy and import substitution. In fact, they're getting impoverished because

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:58.560
[Guest 1]: of this. So there is a scaffolding of ideas which is being held up by people in positions

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:03.240
[Guest 1]: of power within the bureaucracy in politics, which we have now forgotten because we don't

00:39:03.240 --> 00:39:08.000
[Guest 1]: read all this in history. But I think that is the critical part as opposed to Nehru did

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:12.800
[Guest 1]: this and, you know, Manmohan Singh did that. Manmohan Singh happens to be an academic economist.

00:39:12.800 --> 00:39:17.120
[Guest 1]: So we put him in a different category, but like Nehru did this or Bajpai did that or,

00:39:17.120 --> 00:39:23.680
[Guest 1]: you know, Narsimha Rao did this. I think that's a little bit reductive version, both in 91

00:39:23.680 --> 00:39:24.680
[Guest 1]: and in 47.

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:29.480
[Amit Varma]: Right. Fascinating. And, you know, on the note of what you were saying about, you know,

00:39:29.480 --> 00:39:34.280
[Amit Varma]: the economic temper of the times and how the world was generally evolving, just a point

00:39:34.280 --> 00:39:38.040
[Amit Varma]: and a recommendation. And the point is that at one point, and this might confuse some

00:39:38.040 --> 00:39:42.120
[Amit Varma]: listeners, that you said that you spoke about the move away from Scottish enlightenment

00:39:42.120 --> 00:39:47.080
[Amit Varma]: ideals of individual freedom and personal liberty and all of that happening with progressivism

00:39:47.080 --> 00:39:51.320
[Amit Varma]: and Nazism and command and control. And the listener might wonder, but these are all different

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:56.520
[Amit Varma]: things. But the ways in which they are moved away from enlightenment ideals is that they

00:39:56.520 --> 00:40:01.960
[Amit Varma]: all focus on the collective over the individual on group identities instead of individual

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:07.480
[Amit Varma]: identities. And they are all flawed in different ways and to different extents. But in that

00:40:07.480 --> 00:40:11.640
[Amit Varma]: sense, that's kind of what you meant. And the recommendation I have is that a book I

00:40:11.640 --> 00:40:16.400
[Amit Varma]: read recently, The Clash of Economic Ideas by our mutual friend Lawrence H. White, where

00:40:16.400 --> 00:40:23.480
[Amit Varma]: he kind of talks about this evolution of economic thinking and ideology through those decades,

00:40:23.480 --> 00:40:28.440
[Amit Varma]: including an excellent chapter on India as well, which is a book I'd heartily recommend.

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:35.080
[Amit Varma]: So I have a much broader question, which might seem like a bit of a ramble. So please indulge

00:40:35.080 --> 00:40:40.560
[Amit Varma]: me while I go on it, which actually goes back to one of my pet themes of how do we form

00:40:40.560 --> 00:40:45.920
[Amit Varma]: ideas? How do we form our view of the world? For example, one way in which we do that is

00:40:45.920 --> 00:40:49.680
[Amit Varma]: through personal experience. Like there's an anecdote I wrote about in a column of mine

00:40:49.680 --> 00:40:54.240
[Amit Varma]: and which I talk about sometimes to talk about the importance of reading is something that

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:59.000
[Amit Varma]: a friend of Narendra Modi once told me that, you know, she knew him a decade ago. And when

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:02.840
[Amit Varma]: he was Gujarati and she was hanging out at his place with a bunch of friends, there were

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:07.640
[Amit Varma]: six or seven of them. And at one point, Mr. Modi started telling a story about how his

00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:12.320
[Amit Varma]: mother was ill when he was a kid, and she was feeling very hot. And he went to open

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:16.800
[Amit Varma]: the fan, and he found there was no electricity. And as Mr. Modi told the story, apparently

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:21.800
[Amit Varma]: he started crying. And my friend's point in telling me the story was that his view of

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:26.400
[Amit Varma]: the world is very experiential, that anything he can experience, he gets it. Otherwise,

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:32.360
[Amit Varma]: he doesn't. So for example, when he becomes CM, he tries hard to electrify every village

00:41:32.360 --> 00:41:36.480
[Amit Varma]: of Gujarat. He cares about roads because he can see them, he can walk on them, he has

00:41:36.480 --> 00:41:41.320
[Amit Varma]: experienced them. But there are other things which you can't experience things like how

00:41:41.320 --> 00:41:46.360
[Amit Varma]: markets work, how spontaneous order works, a positive sumness of things. And therefore,

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:50.440
[Amit Varma]: those are where he is deficient. And you know, and my point in the column was that people

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:55.160
[Amit Varma]: should read a lot more. So that's how we gather dots and, you know, paint more high definition

00:41:55.160 --> 00:41:59.960
[Amit Varma]: pictures. But in the case of someone who hasn't been lucky enough to read a lot, my suggestion

00:41:59.960 --> 00:42:04.440
[Amit Varma]: was that have a lot of humility, always talk to experts, which is something he didn't do.

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:09.800
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of the massive blunders of, you know, his time as Prime Minister from you

00:42:09.800 --> 00:42:14.840
[Amit Varma]: know, demonetization and so on, are really in a sense due to his being this kind of an

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:18.880
[Amit Varma]: akho dekhi Prime Minister and not being humble enough to correct for that. The other way

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:23.640
[Amit Varma]: that we arrive at views of the world is actually through the opposite of this, like in this

00:42:23.640 --> 00:42:28.040
[Amit Varma]: case is perhaps a lack of education, but we also arrive at wrong views of the world through

00:42:28.040 --> 00:42:33.040
[Amit Varma]: education itself, you know, which can depend on where you go to university, where you go

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:37.960
[Amit Varma]: to college and so on. Now, it seems to me that in Nehru's case, it's a bit of both.

00:42:37.960 --> 00:42:42.440
[Amit Varma]: For example, in his autobiography, he has this interesting line where he writes, I have

00:42:42.440 --> 00:42:46.760
[Amit Varma]: long been drawn to socialism and communism and Russia has appealed to me, I realize more

00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:51.880
[Amit Varma]: and more how the very basis and foundation of our acquisitive society and property was

00:42:51.880 --> 00:42:56.920
[Amit Varma]: violence, stop quote. So he's got a negative notion of private property, because the aspect

00:42:56.920 --> 00:43:02.680
[Amit Varma]: of which that he has seen is the violent aspect of it. Similarly, he would have a negative

00:43:02.680 --> 00:43:07.920
[Amit Varma]: notion of markets, because he would associate it with you know, his akho dekhi experience

00:43:07.920 --> 00:43:12.480
[Amit Varma]: of the British state, which of course came from the East India Company, which was exploitative,

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:18.200
[Amit Varma]: which was, you know, all of those things that people sometimes caricature markets as today.

00:43:18.200 --> 00:43:22.760
[Amit Varma]: And equally, when it comes to sort of getting his ideology, again, Time magazine once wrote

00:43:22.760 --> 00:43:27.480
[Amit Varma]: about him in a 1951 piece, quote, Beatrice and Sidney Webb, the godparents of Fabian

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:32.800
[Amit Varma]: socialism are in a truer sense, his creators in Vishnu and Shiva, stop quote. And at a

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:36.600
[Amit Varma]: later point in time, you know, John Kenneth Galbraith wrote, quote, the center of Nehru's

00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:41.840
[Amit Varma]: sinking was Lasky, stop quote. And Ram Guha once quoted an unnamed person saying, quote,

00:43:41.840 --> 00:43:45.440
[Amit Varma]: in every meeting of the Indian cabinet, there is a chair reserved for the ghost of Professor

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Harald Lasky, stop quote. So my sort of larger kind of question, which I wonder about is

00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:54.680
[Amit Varma]: that on the one hand, you get your view of the world from the things that you see around

00:43:54.680 --> 00:43:59.560
[Amit Varma]: you. And you perhaps make simplistic causal inferences from there. On the other hand,

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:03.800
[Amit Varma]: you can do it through education or just through exposure to different worldviews. Because

00:44:03.800 --> 00:44:08.120
[Amit Varma]: when we are young, we are searching for ways to make sense of the world. The first simplistic

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:12.200
[Amit Varma]: ideology that seems to explain everything that is coherent, it could be untrue, but

00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:17.600
[Amit Varma]: it could be coherent, just appeals to us. And sometimes sadly, we become wedded to that.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:24.240
[Amit Varma]: So that's one view of how, you know, a person's view of the world can be formed. But the counterpoint

00:44:24.240 --> 00:44:28.840
[Amit Varma]: to that is that there is something more happening here that the aankho dekhi element doesn't

00:44:28.840 --> 00:44:34.120
[Amit Varma]: really matter so much because what we see in today's times in modern politics is that

00:44:34.120 --> 00:44:39.720
[Amit Varma]: narratives are more important than reality, which is why you have so many young people,

00:44:39.720 --> 00:44:43.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, born after the fall of the Soviet Union and the Berlin Wall and all of that,

00:44:43.920 --> 00:44:47.960
[Amit Varma]: who haven't, you know, experienced any of the horrors of communism or socialism gone

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:55.080
[Amit Varma]: wrong in the 20th century, suddenly drawn to those ideologies based on coercion, which

00:44:55.080 --> 00:45:01.320
[Amit Varma]: then kind of makes me wonder that are we all slaves to these ideologies and you know, a

00:45:01.320 --> 00:45:05.680
[Amit Varma]: bit of a ramble, but so I'm not, you know, framing a question here, but what are sort

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:07.800
[Guest 2]: of your thoughts on this?

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:16.080
[Guest 2]: You're absolutely right in thinking and asking the question, how do we learn? And how do

00:45:16.080 --> 00:45:22.920
[Guest 2]: many people develop their worldview? And when you try to apply that to Nehru, you have to

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:27.920
[Guest 2]: be in that special corner of the general theory of how people learn, which is that he was

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:31.680
[Guest 2]: one of the most powerful intellectuals of the 20th century. He was no ordinary person.

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:38.080
[Guest 2]: He was a deeply well-read person. He got FaceTime with the smartest people in the world. He,

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:45.160
[Guest 2]: there was no brilliant person of that age that Nehru did not get intensive weekend long

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:53.160
[Guest 2]: conversations with. So there are no simple flaws in what he was thinking. He's the author

00:45:53.160 --> 00:45:57.880
[Guest 2]: of the Discovery of India, one of the greatest books ever written. And arguably, if you ever

00:45:57.880 --> 00:46:02.080
[Guest 2]: want to step away from Churchill's claim that India is just a geographical expression, that

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:06.840
[Guest 2]: idea was invented in the Discovery of India. It's like the first coherent statement of

00:46:06.840 --> 00:46:12.200
[Guest 2]: what is India and you know, what all of us one way or the other define as our concept

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:18.520
[Guest 2]: of India is really, you know, from the Discovery of India. So I will again, take you back to

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:24.560
[Guest 2]: the formative years, the formative years of the INC and of every dreamer for India. Look

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:29.680
[Guest 2]: around the world. Okay. There is racism in the world. That is a very powerful preconception

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:35.600
[Guest 2]: that white people are better. It takes guts. It takes nerve to even rise to the point of

00:46:35.600 --> 00:46:40.400
[Guest 2]: saying, no, I'm every bit as good as you. It seems easy for us to say that today. Okay.

00:46:40.400 --> 00:46:44.560
[Guest 2]: But think of how many people in India today will think an NRI is better than us. Okay.

00:46:44.560 --> 00:46:51.840
[Guest 2]: So racism runs deep and the colonialism in our minds is not merely about evicting the

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:57.160
[Guest 2]: colonial ruler. It's in our minds. It's an enormous act of courage to step out of that

00:46:57.160 --> 00:47:01.520
[Guest 2]: and say, I dream that I will be as good as you, if not better. And then when you start

00:47:01.520 --> 00:47:07.000
[Guest 2]: looking around in world history, there's just no running away. It's Japan, the Meiji Restoration

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:14.560
[Guest 2]: from 1868 to 1905. In 1905, for the first time in world history, an Asian country, Japan,

00:47:14.560 --> 00:47:20.640
[Guest 2]: won a war against a half European country, Soviet Russia, sorry, Czarist Russia. Okay.

00:47:20.640 --> 00:47:26.560
[Guest 2]: And that was done in a short time with really a state-led model. It was government leadership.

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:29.680
[Guest 2]: It was the government that planned, we're going to have a steel factory. We're going

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:36.160
[Guest 2]: to build warships. We're going to get kids to learn how radar works and so on. So it

00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:45.200
[Guest 2]: is really hard to play the game of rapid industrialization in India and a rapid catch up with the global

00:47:45.200 --> 00:47:52.120
[Guest 2]: frontier, which was the UK, without trying to think in ways that were reminiscent of

00:47:52.120 --> 00:47:58.840
[Guest 2]: Japan and Soviet Russia. We're different today because we know that those rapid catch-ups

00:47:58.840 --> 00:48:03.360
[Guest 2]: really don't happen. And it's a long, slow process. And that's what buys space for a

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:09.000
[Guest 2]: self-organizing system. So things will evolve slowly. We are not saying to ourselves that

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:19.000
[Guest 2]: I want to do this on the time horizons, like 1917 to 1942 or 1943, where you go from the

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:22.760
[Guest 2]: Russian revolution to winning the battle of Stalingrad and becoming the world's greatest

00:48:22.760 --> 00:48:29.920
[Guest 2]: land army, or on the time horizon from the Meiji restoration to 1905. We don't worry

00:48:29.920 --> 00:48:33.560
[Guest 2]: about those things today, partly because we don't think that even a centrally planned

00:48:33.560 --> 00:48:38.720
[Guest 2]: system can particularly do that. Essential to the conception of a self-organizing system

00:48:38.720 --> 00:48:42.920
[Guest 2]: is to take a little more time, but it will be done right. And it will be a decent, fair

00:48:42.920 --> 00:48:48.160
[Guest 2]: outcome. You have to also notice how Nehru constantly says to himself and to everybody

00:48:48.160 --> 00:48:52.080
[Guest 2]: that we want to do all the great things of Soviet Russia without the concentration camps

00:48:52.080 --> 00:48:55.880
[Guest 2]: and without the purges and without the massacres. So he was searching for that middle road,

00:48:55.880 --> 00:49:00.560
[Guest 2]: that how do you achieve the decency of the UK? How do you achieve civil liberties and

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:06.760
[Guest 2]: constitutionalism and the lack of violence against your own people while achieving a

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:10.480
[Guest 2]: Soviet style catch up to the global frontier?

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:14.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, having said that, you know, you look at the Soviet Union and you say, okay,

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:19.120
[Amit Varma]: we want to do, you know, ABC, but we don't want to do X, Y, Z, we'd rather be like Britain.

00:49:19.120 --> 00:49:24.440
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, he's looking at a particular aspect of Britain. You know, Britain was also

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:28.520
[Amit Varma]: in many ways, much more laissez-faire, for example, than they are today. Like at one

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:33.520
[Amit Varma]: point, you know, there is this famous quote from this Time Magazine 1951 piece on Nehru,

00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:37.920
[Amit Varma]: where they wrote, quote, he shares all the socialist emotional tenets about the capitalist

00:49:37.920 --> 00:49:42.560
[Amit Varma]: order. In consequence, he has a socialist undisguised contempt for capitalism, reinforced

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:47.280
[Amit Varma]: by the aristocratic Brahmin's contempt for the Baniya caste. He speaks of the quote Baniya

00:49:47.280 --> 00:49:52.000
[Amit Varma]: civilization of the capitalist West, stop quote, of the West cutthroat civilization.

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:57.120
[Amit Varma]: Utterly unlike Gandhi, he admires modern production methods and wants to bring them to India.

00:49:57.120 --> 00:50:01.840
[Amit Varma]: But as a socialist, he believes that capitalism after his prodigies of production is bound

00:50:01.840 --> 00:50:06.600
[Amit Varma]: to make a bloody and cruel mess of distribution. This view is based on the standard British

00:50:06.600 --> 00:50:11.360
[Amit Varma]: socialist reading of 19th century economic history. His understanding of 20th century

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:16.760
[Amit Varma]: American capitalism is negligible, stop quote. And so it's a particular strand of thinking,

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:21.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, which was in England that he's really focusing on. He's not focusing on all the

00:50:21.640 --> 00:50:24.360
[Amit Varma]: other things that are happening there.

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:29.300
[Guest 2]: If you want a simple model, he was trying to do, you know, X percent of the UK and one

00:50:29.300 --> 00:50:34.400
[Guest 2]: minus X of the USSR. So it's going to be pretty bad.

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:39.640
[Amit Varma]: And is there also then a certain intellectual arrogance and therefore simple mindedness

00:50:39.640 --> 00:50:46.240
[Amit Varma]: in people who are drawn towards these kind of command and control models of thinking

00:50:46.240 --> 00:50:47.240
[Amit Varma]: about the world?

00:50:47.240 --> 00:50:53.120
[Guest 2]: Once again, in defense of those people, I just want to say that we each of us struggle

00:50:53.120 --> 00:50:57.080
[Guest 2]: to decide for the world. And if you and I were in those times, we would think differently.

00:50:57.080 --> 00:51:03.200
[Guest 2]: So, my father started out as a card carrying member of the Communist Party. And he changed

00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:07.320
[Guest 2]: his mind completely over the years. But the point is that in that age, when you looked

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:08.320
[Guest 2]: at the world, it looked different.

00:51:08.320 --> 00:51:12.920
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm not talking about the specific people. My question, I would say even applies today

00:51:12.920 --> 00:51:17.200
[Amit Varma]: that are certain kinds of people applied and I'm thinking aloud here completely. So I might

00:51:17.200 --> 00:51:22.920
[Amit Varma]: find this a silly question when I listen back on it. But are certain kinds of people drawn

00:51:22.920 --> 00:51:24.720
[Amit Varma]: to certain kinds of ideology?

00:51:24.720 --> 00:51:30.800
[Guest 1]: Well, I think there are two things going on. One is the characteristic of the individual,

00:51:30.800 --> 00:51:35.200
[Guest 1]: you know, which can change whether it's Nehru or Indira Gandhi or whoever. And the second

00:51:35.200 --> 00:51:41.160
[Guest 1]: is the ecosystem that they inhabit, right? Now, I'm a product of a very particular ecosystem,

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:47.080
[Guest 1]: right? I mean, it's not like I sprung out of the soil as an economist or as a, you know,

00:51:47.080 --> 00:51:52.120
[Guest 1]: free market leaning economist or anything like that. I was as socialist as anyone else

00:51:52.120 --> 00:51:57.880
[Guest 1]: reading about overpopulation, five-year plans, punch-shield agreements in our civics textbooks,

00:51:57.880 --> 00:52:03.920
[Guest 1]: right? Emergency and your trains ran on time. But I was very fortunate and privileged. I

00:52:03.920 --> 00:52:08.760
[Guest 1]: had an exceptional economics professor, principles of microeconomics, you know, the basics of

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:13.520
[Guest 1]: trade, all this, you know, the basics I was telling you, the shortages and, you know,

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:17.480
[Guest 1]: excess demand, excess supply, all this, like the basic stuff, he just explained it so well

00:52:17.480 --> 00:52:22.800
[Guest 1]: to me, it was hard to unsee the world after that. Now, if I think about my own intellectual

00:52:22.800 --> 00:52:28.640
[Guest 1]: trajectory post undergraduate economics, once I understood that, I gravitated more towards

00:52:28.640 --> 00:52:34.120
[Guest 1]: books that would help explain that better. I gravitated towards people who explained

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:38.640
[Guest 1]: to me that, you know, why is everyone disagreeing with me? Why do I see markets as a good thing

00:52:38.640 --> 00:52:43.720
[Guest 1]: and everyone else seems to think I'm bananas, right? So you start getting together with

00:52:43.720 --> 00:52:48.520
[Guest 1]: the Amit Vermas and the Ajay Shahs of the world, and they are able to explain a little

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:53.120
[Guest 1]: bit better to you that, hey, this is happening because of this, right? So this is the analytical

00:52:53.120 --> 00:52:56.800
[Guest 1]: framework you're using, you're right, other people are wrong, not because they're stupid

00:52:56.800 --> 00:53:02.360
[Guest 1]: or malicious or malevolent, it is because there's a fundamental misunderstanding in their mind

00:53:02.360 --> 00:53:06.760
[Guest 1]: about how this particular thing works, or when they say socialism, they mean something

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:11.320
[Guest 1]: else or when they say markets, they mean something else. And then I've been incubated in that

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:16.560
[Guest 1]: ecosystem for a really long time, I eventually got a PhD, I happened to get a PhD from George

00:53:16.560 --> 00:53:22.520
[Guest 1]: Mason, which, you know, is a leader in Austrian economics. And, you know, a lot of my own

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:27.200
[Guest 1]: professors worked on the socialist calculation problems, all the things we're talking about

00:53:27.200 --> 00:53:30.480
[Guest 1]: today, you mentioned Larry White, he was on my dissertation committee, all this is not

00:53:30.480 --> 00:53:35.800
[Guest 1]: by accident, right, that I have turned out the way that I have turned out. So there is

00:53:35.800 --> 00:53:42.080
[Guest 1]: something about the ecosystem that is incubating you. So even in that time, right, for every

00:53:42.080 --> 00:53:48.680
[Guest 1]: Nehru, you have a Chenoi, okay, Chenoi happens to be one of the people who went to the, you

00:53:48.680 --> 00:53:53.520
[Guest 1]: know, went to the UK. And incidentally, he's at the LSE at the same time as all these other

00:53:53.520 --> 00:53:58.760
[Guest 1]: guys. But he's more attracted to Karl Popper, and he's more attracted to Frederick Hayek,

00:53:58.760 --> 00:54:03.440
[Guest 1]: and he's not so attracted to Lasky, right. But if you talk to BK Nehru, if you talk to

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:09.280
[Guest 1]: Mino Masani, right, same people, similar generation, they go the completely other way. Mino Masani

00:54:09.280 --> 00:54:14.320
[Guest 1]: was like card carrying socialist, went on the 10th anniversary of the Bolshevik Revolution

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:19.000
[Guest 1]: and saw what was the celebrations in Moscow firsthand and things like that, and then changed

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:24.400
[Guest 1]: much later because of a Gandhian view of why Stalinism was bad. So there's an ecosystem

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:28.720
[Guest 1]: that incubates these people. So now Nehru is, of course, exceptional on multiple margins.

00:54:28.720 --> 00:54:34.280
[Guest 1]: He's an exceptional mind. He has access to an exceptional ecosystem. Now, did he meet

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:40.280
[Guest 1]: every possible individual that he could have met and took in every possible view? No, but

00:54:40.280 --> 00:54:46.880
[Guest 1]: that's fine. He took as many elite views into question of that time as he possibly could.

00:54:46.880 --> 00:54:51.780
[Guest 1]: And you know, now talking about this aankhon dekhi business, he's also got results like

00:54:51.780 --> 00:54:57.120
[Guest 1]: India was growing at maybe 1, 1.2% in colonial India, especially by the time the war came

00:54:57.120 --> 00:55:02.400
[Guest 1]: along. By the time 15 years of Nehru was done, we're roughly growing at, you know, three

00:55:02.400 --> 00:55:08.080
[Guest 1]: and a half to four and a half percent. That's a pretty big jump. So not only is Nehru's

00:55:08.080 --> 00:55:14.200
[Guest 1]: model working, it's working far better than anything that he inherited from the colonial

00:55:14.200 --> 00:55:18.920
[Guest 1]: masters right now. Everything goes to hell right after that. But at the time, it's not

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:24.680
[Guest 1]: just that he's not willing to look at the world or not willing to look at evidence.

00:55:24.680 --> 00:55:30.000
[Guest 1]: The evidence is in his corner, right? The elites are kind of supporting what he's saying.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:34.440
[Guest 1]: There are very few people who are disagreeing with him. Most of the people he trusts who

00:55:34.440 --> 00:55:40.280
[Guest 1]: are trained by, you know, other people at top universities are, you know, going along

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:47.960
[Guest 1]: the same way as he is. It would be very surprising if he went a different way, to be very honest,

00:55:47.960 --> 00:55:53.920
[Guest 1]: right? Everyone else who went a different way did so for various other reasons in different

00:55:53.920 --> 00:55:59.840
[Guest 1]: coalitions at a different point in time. So a Tantra party, which, you know, to me is

00:55:59.840 --> 00:56:04.080
[Guest 1]: probably politically most aligned to the way of thinking for, you know, not just me, perhaps

00:56:04.080 --> 00:56:09.720
[Guest 1]: all three of us. They are conservative on many social issues, right? They're very conservative

00:56:09.720 --> 00:56:15.560
[Guest 1]: on things like caste in a way that Nehru and Ambedkar are not, for instance, right? They

00:56:15.560 --> 00:56:22.640
[Guest 1]: are explicitly allies with the aristocracy of India, which is all the Maharajas who in

00:56:22.640 --> 00:56:28.400
[Guest 1]: a sense are, you know, your Maharajas and Zamindars are the feudal lords. Now, I'm not

00:56:28.400 --> 00:56:32.040
[Guest 1]: saying anything about the character of these people like Gayatri Devi and all the people

00:56:32.040 --> 00:56:38.840
[Guest 1]: they allied with, but it's a very odd group of people to make your allies in post-colonial

00:56:38.840 --> 00:56:42.600
[Guest 1]: India when you have a different vision for India, which is, you know, India needs to

00:56:42.600 --> 00:56:46.840
[Guest 1]: not just be economically prosperous, but also needs to be politically free and equal and

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:51.280
[Guest 1]: caste needs to go away and feudalism needs to go away. So with every group of people,

00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:55.800
[Guest 1]: I'm sure if we had a deep enough discussion, we would find something terribly, terribly

00:56:55.800 --> 00:57:01.480
[Guest 1]: wrong with the ecosystem that they inhabited and the kinds of, you know, ideas that, that

00:57:01.480 --> 00:57:08.960
[Guest 1]: they borrowed. Having said that, I think there is also a really big problem in any of us

00:57:08.960 --> 00:57:15.560
[Guest 1]: viewing that we have the right idea or the right model of the world. It is scientism

00:57:15.560 --> 00:57:21.600
[Guest 1]: at its worst, right? So when people say we have, even when free market economists say,

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:26.640
[Guest 1]: hey, we figured this out, to me, that's, that's the worst thing I can hear from anyone. It

00:57:26.640 --> 00:57:31.760
[Guest 1]: immediately terrifies me. Have we really figured it out? Yes, we know certain things for sure.

00:57:31.760 --> 00:57:36.160
[Guest 1]: We know that resources are scarce. We know that there are unintended consequences when

00:57:36.160 --> 00:57:41.760
[Guest 1]: you try and command and control these things. We know there are very early limits to human

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:46.880
[Guest 1]: ability to process decentralized knowledge and therefore control the economy. But having

00:57:46.880 --> 00:57:51.720
[Guest 1]: said that, have markets just managed to solve everything? Has decentralized and spontaneous

00:57:51.720 --> 00:57:56.640
[Guest 1]: order figured everything out? There are a lot of, you know, decentralized spontaneous

00:57:56.640 --> 00:58:03.440
[Guest 1]: long-term orders, which are quite perverse, you know, and you can find examples of witchcraft

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:07.960
[Guest 1]: abroad. You can find examples of caste system, misogyny, patriarchy. These are all, by the

00:58:07.960 --> 00:58:13.960
[Guest 1]: way, also spontaneous orders like markets and language. They're not so great. Okay.

00:58:13.960 --> 00:58:19.880
[Guest 1]: So everything's going to have something. So anyone who says that we figured this out is

00:58:19.880 --> 00:58:26.120
[Guest 1]: very problematic. What we can do, the best we can do as experts is find a framework through

00:58:26.120 --> 00:58:31.280
[Guest 1]: which we can carefully look through both theoretical frameworks and the empirical evidence and

00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:35.240
[Guest 1]: say, this is what we know. And given what we know, I think this is what we proceed.

00:58:35.240 --> 00:58:38.920
[Guest 1]: And I think Nehru and company did that reasonably well.

00:58:38.920 --> 00:58:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, I don't know why you went off on the Nehru tangent because I wasn't

00:58:43.080 --> 00:58:47.520
[Amit Varma]: even talking about Nehru. Like my last few questions were just general broad questions

00:58:47.520 --> 00:58:51.360
[Amit Varma]: and I'm not litigating Nehru. I have great admiration for him, though it must be pointed

00:58:51.360 --> 00:58:54.720
[Amit Varma]: out to listeners that he was anything but liberal. In fact, you know, these days people

00:58:54.720 --> 00:58:58.400
[Amit Varma]: are talking about the sedition law and the thing is the Supreme Court of India struck

00:58:58.400 --> 00:59:03.760
[Amit Varma]: down the sedition law in 1950. Nehru brought it back with the first amendment, right? So

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:08.400
[Amit Varma]: in many ways, he was an anti-liberal and definitely in his thinking of markets.

00:59:08.400 --> 00:59:12.880
[Guest 1]: To overcome the Communist Party. There is that part of the story, right?

00:59:12.880 --> 00:59:17.120
[Amit Varma]: To overcome his political enemies. You know, it doesn't matter who your political enemies

00:59:17.120 --> 00:59:20.160
[Amit Varma]: are. You know, they are not anti-national just because they're opposed to you and you're

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:24.760
[Amit Varma]: in power. A lesson we should remember from today and something that, in fact, aligns

00:59:24.760 --> 00:59:29.320
[Amit Varma]: him with Mr. Modi today. The other thing I would say is that the right model of the world

00:59:29.320 --> 00:59:34.360
[Amit Varma]: you use that phrase is humility. You know, that is the only right model of the world.

00:59:34.360 --> 00:59:38.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, which kind of just to elaborate, though I won't ask you to respond to it, but

00:59:38.440 --> 00:59:43.200
[Amit Varma]: just to elaborate on what I meant by does character determine the kind of choices that

00:59:43.200 --> 00:59:49.040
[Amit Varma]: you make that I find that a lot of ideologies will draw intellectually lazy people because

00:59:49.040 --> 00:59:54.400
[Amit Varma]: it is far easier to say, for example, believe a particular narrative of victimhood, whether

00:59:54.400 --> 00:59:59.200
[Amit Varma]: it is coming from the right or the left and then think in terms of group identities, rather

00:59:59.200 --> 01:00:04.520
[Amit Varma]: than get down and messy and accept that everyone contains multitudes, the world is deeply complicated.

01:00:04.520 --> 01:00:08.700
[Amit Varma]: You can't just cast black and white judgments on different things. And I think gaining that

01:00:08.700 --> 01:00:14.840
[Amit Varma]: kind of humility to be able to have the rigor to constantly keep questioning your assumptions

01:00:14.840 --> 01:00:19.960
[Amit Varma]: is sort of an important quality to have. You know, you mentioned B.R. Shenoy. And the thing

01:00:19.960 --> 01:00:25.140
[Amit Varma]: is when Nehru, I think in the mid 50s, got those 21 economists together to give their

01:00:25.140 --> 01:00:29.560
[Amit Varma]: perspectives on, you know, I think the second planet was. B.R. Shenoy was the only one who

01:00:29.560 --> 01:00:33.320
[Amit Varma]: dissented and therefore he was completely cast out. A bureaucrat, in fact, described

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:38.400
[Amit Varma]: him as quote unquote a madman and which is just crazy. Similarly, you look at Massani,

01:00:38.400 --> 01:00:43.240
[Amit Varma]: great admiration because he bucked the trend. You know, first he followed the trend by,

01:00:43.240 --> 01:00:47.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, becoming a communist like his peers, following the whatever the intellectual fashion

01:00:47.280 --> 01:00:52.160
[Amit Varma]: around him must have been. But then he had the humility to keep questioning his assumptions

01:00:52.160 --> 01:00:57.240
[Amit Varma]: and to sort of look beyond that. So that was a question unrelated to this episode or to

01:00:57.240 --> 01:01:02.160
[Amit Varma]: Nehru or to anything. It's just something that I generally sort of think about, which

01:01:02.160 --> 01:01:06.320
[Amit Varma]: is why, you know, I sort of deployed labels when they are used in modern times, even a

01:01:06.320 --> 01:01:10.840
[Amit Varma]: label like libertarian, because it immediately seems to put you in a tribe. It seems to put

01:01:10.840 --> 01:01:14.760
[Amit Varma]: you in a fixed place that this is where you are and this is who you are and these are

01:01:14.760 --> 01:01:19.600
[Amit Varma]: the people with whom you belong. And I find that at some level that it's a problem. Like

01:01:19.600 --> 01:01:25.000
[Amit Varma]: my view of the world is that I am firm on values, which is individual rights and freedom

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:30.720
[Amit Varma]: and whatever. But I am completely open on, you know, accepting new facts about the world

01:01:30.720 --> 01:01:36.040
[Amit Varma]: and changing the way I think with regard to those new facts. But that's a digression.

01:01:36.040 --> 01:01:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Another quick general question before we come to the specifics of post-independence India,

01:01:40.720 --> 01:01:46.560
[Amit Varma]: which is that one criticism people can make is that we refer to everything before 1991

01:01:46.560 --> 01:01:51.280
[Amit Varma]: as socialism. And people will point to the textbook definition of socialism and say that,

01:01:51.280 --> 01:01:55.640
[Amit Varma]: hey, that's, you know, socialism is good. It means the state owns everything. There's

01:01:55.640 --> 01:02:00.360
[Amit Varma]: no private property. What was there wasn't socialism. And the way that I think about

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:04.880
[Amit Varma]: it and you know, you can respond to that and say how you think is that I think a more accurate

01:02:04.880 --> 01:02:11.120
[Amit Varma]: way of describing India before 91 was statist and it is less statist but still very statist.

01:02:11.120 --> 01:02:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And that statism is actually inevitable if you go down the socialist road, because power

01:02:16.120 --> 01:02:20.840
[Amit Varma]: always corrupts. So you will always under a socialist system or for that matter, a Nazi

01:02:20.840 --> 01:02:26.040
[Amit Varma]: system or, you know, various different systems which look different, end up in the state

01:02:26.040 --> 01:02:31.360
[Amit Varma]: having too much power. So I don't really care so much about the terms. The way that I kind

01:02:31.360 --> 01:02:36.080
[Amit Varma]: of view them is how much power does the state have? How much statism is there? And that's

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:40.320
[Amit Varma]: really the fault line along which I look at those things. So how would you guys think

01:02:40.320 --> 01:02:42.000
[Amit Varma]: about that?

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:46.840
[Guest 1]: I would disagree a little bit in the following sense. I mean, I know this word socialism

01:02:46.840 --> 01:02:51.320
[Guest 1]: means like 40 different things to many people. For some people, it just means good intentions.

01:02:51.320 --> 01:02:56.160
[Guest 1]: For some people, it means removing inequality. And for at least Ajay and I here are professional

01:02:56.160 --> 01:03:02.760
[Guest 1]: economists, right? There is something very specific about socialism here, where number

01:03:02.760 --> 01:03:07.920
[Guest 1]: one, you control the means of production, right? So that is a very classic socialist

01:03:07.920 --> 01:03:14.160
[Guest 1]: system thing, which is different from progressivism or, you know, the kind of guild forms under

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:19.040
[Guest 1]: fascism. There is something very specific about socialism where the aim is to control

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:22.960
[Guest 1]: the means of production. The second is the kind of price and quantity controls. You can

01:03:22.960 --> 01:03:28.880
[Guest 1]: have a very statist economy. You can have a huge welfare economy that doesn't actively

01:03:28.880 --> 01:03:34.880
[Guest 1]: distort prices, right? Or quantities. And one classic aspect of socialism is that it

01:03:34.880 --> 01:03:39.800
[Guest 1]: will actually impose price and quantity controls. So I will disagree. I do agree with you that

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:45.240
[Guest 1]: India has always been statist, okay? And that some of it is worse and some of it is better.

01:03:45.240 --> 01:03:51.200
[Guest 1]: In fact, on some margins, India is more statist today than it was before. But I will very

01:03:51.200 --> 01:04:01.040
[Guest 1]: explicitly say that India was socialist for a very large chunk of time between, say, 1938,

01:04:01.040 --> 01:04:08.920
[Guest 1]: 1939, till 1988, you know, and some parts even maybe until 1993, depending on when you

01:04:08.920 --> 01:04:14.400
[Guest 1]: are choosing the cutoff of which price controls come in and which ones go away. But for a

01:04:14.400 --> 01:04:20.880
[Guest 1]: good part of those four or five decades, it's very clear that India is socialist. The aim

01:04:20.880 --> 01:04:25.400
[Guest 1]: is to control means of production. And the aim is whatever the market allocation is,

01:04:25.400 --> 01:04:28.080
[Guest 1]: we're not happy with it. We're going to impose price and quantity controls.

01:04:28.080 --> 01:04:34.680
[Guest 2]: I fully agree. The right way to think about it is that what is the role of markets in

01:04:34.680 --> 01:04:39.520
[Guest 2]: determining the organization of economic activity? It's about prices. It's about technology.

01:04:39.520 --> 01:04:44.800
[Guest 2]: It's about products, processes, industries, firms. Okay, so do you want the government

01:04:44.800 --> 01:04:48.600
[Guest 2]: to decide? Do you want the government to pick winners? Do you want the government to choose

01:04:48.600 --> 01:04:53.680
[Guest 2]: what is appropriate technology? Or do you want to let private people figure out what

01:04:53.680 --> 01:04:58.480
[Guest 2]: is right and let the price system sort out what works and what doesn't work? A big date

01:04:58.480 --> 01:05:04.600
[Guest 2]: in my mind is 1942, when there were large scale controls brought in by the British,

01:05:04.600 --> 01:05:08.280
[Guest 2]: which were in the nature of trade controls, trade restrictions, and capital controls.

01:05:08.280 --> 01:05:15.040
[Guest 2]: The first capital controls in India's history came in 1942. So it seems like an unbelievably

01:05:15.040 --> 01:05:21.880
[Guest 2]: free age that before 1942 in British India, people from within India were able to travel

01:05:21.880 --> 01:05:27.640
[Guest 2]: all over the British Empire without a passport or a visa, and move assets in and out of India

01:05:27.640 --> 01:05:35.320
[Guest 2]: and build multinational empires. So it's a level of freedom that is just incomprehensibly

01:05:35.320 --> 01:05:41.160
[Guest 2]: far away from where we are in India today. So it's bracing to look back at how much freedom

01:05:41.160 --> 01:05:46.000
[Guest 1]: has been lost. But you know, even on this traveling abroad

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:51.560
[Guest 1]: thing, like Ajay talked about how he went in 1987 to start his PhD, he didn't tell you

01:05:51.560 --> 01:05:57.800
[Guest 1]: how hard it was to collect the foreign exchange through legal means, to be able, you know,

01:05:57.800 --> 01:06:01.520
[Guest 1]: like that those $200 or whatever it is you need to, I don't know what the allotment was

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:07.720
[Guest 1]: in 87. But to just collect that, I mean, it's like, it's not a family effort. It's like

01:06:07.720 --> 01:06:14.320
[Guest 1]: a quasi city effort, right? Every single person you know, has been drafted into the effort

01:06:14.320 --> 01:06:19.320
[Guest 1]: of getting that very limited foreign exchange. And all this just so someone like Ajay can

01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:24.920
[Guest 1]: show up in LA and you know, the first couple of weeks of meals and basics are sorted out

01:06:24.920 --> 01:06:30.480
[Guest 1]: and then he'll figure out his own foreign exchange from that point on, right? It's sort

01:06:30.480 --> 01:06:35.680
[Guest 1]: of incredible when we talk about these controls, we talk about it in a mythical sense, right?

01:06:35.680 --> 01:06:40.240
[Guest 1]: There's a control on foreign exchange as a foreign exchange as a person and a sentient

01:06:40.240 --> 01:06:45.260
[Guest 1]: being. It's just current. The control is really on human beings, right? Human beings ability

01:06:45.260 --> 01:06:50.860
[Guest 1]: to trade, human beings ability to spend, Narayan Murthy's ability to get a mainframe computer.

01:06:50.860 --> 01:06:54.760
[Guest 1]: So these foreign exchange controls, we just call them currency controls, we should call

01:06:54.760 --> 01:07:00.240
[Guest 1]: them I'm controlling your ability to do whatever it is you wish to do with your money.

01:07:00.240 --> 01:07:05.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a good clarification. And also a useful clarification about socialism and

01:07:05.880 --> 01:07:09.640
[Amit Varma]: I'll defer to your views. It's kind of irritating, you know, in popular parlance, people will

01:07:09.640 --> 01:07:14.800
[Amit Varma]: often use socialism as a synonym for something that is good for society. And actually, a

01:07:14.800 --> 01:07:18.520
[Amit Varma]: lot of these terms are very loaded because they really mean the opposite. Like socialism

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:23.440
[Amit Varma]: certainly is not good for society, as we've seen all through the 20th century. You know,

01:07:23.440 --> 01:07:27.160
[Amit Varma]: progressives are often the least progressive people around. In America, especially liberals

01:07:27.160 --> 01:07:30.960
[Amit Varma]: aren't really that liberal. So these terms are kind of very loaded. So if you're a lay

01:07:30.960 --> 01:07:34.880
[Amit Varma]: person just kind of listening in from the outside, you'll say, hi, I'm a progressive

01:07:34.880 --> 01:07:40.160
[Amit Varma]: too. Socialism is a good thing. But then you talk to an economist and you are like, oh,

01:07:40.160 --> 01:07:44.560
[Amit Varma]: these economists are such boring people. Socialism is still a good thing. But moving on from

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:48.720
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, I keep telling my writing students that avoid abstract things, speak

01:07:48.720 --> 01:07:53.920
[Amit Varma]: about the concrete. So let's kind of get concrete, that fine, we gain independence, Nehru takes

01:07:53.920 --> 01:07:58.940
[Amit Varma]: over, we already know his mindset, as he said to JRD Tata once, quote, do not speak to me

01:07:58.940 --> 01:08:02.880
[Amit Varma]: of profit, profit is a dirty word, stop quote. So you know that this is not only someone

01:08:02.880 --> 01:08:09.480
[Amit Varma]: who wants the state to play a big role in society, he also distrusts private enterprise

01:08:09.480 --> 01:08:14.960
[Amit Varma]: and is against individual liberty in that particular domain. Now, is economic policy

01:08:14.960 --> 01:08:21.020
[Amit Varma]: really evolving during this time? And why is it so bad for us? And what about it works?

01:08:21.020 --> 01:08:26.280
[Amit Varma]: Like you pointed out, he did get the growth rate up from 1% to 3.5%, which was famously

01:08:26.280 --> 01:08:30.320
[Amit Varma]: called the Hindu rate of growth. But it was, you know, that was a pun on the secular rate

01:08:30.320 --> 01:08:35.080
[Amit Varma]: of growth, which is a term economists use. But so what worked about it? And what didn't

01:08:35.080 --> 01:08:42.800
[Guest 2]: work about it? As I see that period, there was a view including amongst folks like the

01:08:42.800 --> 01:08:48.440
[Guest 2]: Bombay plan, there were things like steel mills and machine tools, and electricity generation

01:08:48.440 --> 01:08:54.560
[Guest 2]: equipment that were difficult to organize for private persons. Okay, so I remember I

01:08:54.560 --> 01:08:58.680
[Guest 2]: had a conversation with Bimal Jalan once, who said something remarkable to me, he said

01:08:58.680 --> 01:09:07.000
[Guest 2]: in the 50s, when we in India, which is a mixture of private or public, when we in India, would

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:12.960
[Guest 2]: desire to set up a factory, very often we would fail. It seems inconceivable today.

01:09:12.960 --> 01:09:17.820
[Guest 2]: Today, it seems that you just have to have the money, you'll be able to get the right

01:09:17.820 --> 01:09:22.240
[Guest 2]: engineering consultants who will do the design of the factory, you'll buy all the right capital

01:09:22.240 --> 01:09:25.840
[Guest 2]: goods today, all the world's good capital goods available in India, there is an ample

01:09:25.840 --> 01:09:29.640
[Guest 2]: supply of construction contractors who build the factory, they switch on the factory, it's

01:09:29.640 --> 01:09:35.760
[Guest 2]: going to work. Okay, but the level of capability in India at that time was unbelievably low.

01:09:35.760 --> 01:09:40.640
[Guest 2]: There was also a lack of finance. Now, you and I, one of our first responses will be

01:09:40.640 --> 01:09:44.920
[Guest 2]: very well, if you can't make steel, that's okay, let's import steel. There's nothing

01:09:44.920 --> 01:09:49.240
[Guest 2]: wrong with importing steel. It's no sin to say that in my country, I'm unable to make

01:09:49.240 --> 01:09:54.680
[Guest 2]: steel and I'd rather import steel. And for whatever reasons, these people were mistrustful

01:09:54.680 --> 01:10:00.480
[Guest 2]: of international trade and wanted to do it themselves. They wanted to build steel themselves.

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:05.840
[Guest 2]: So then they were posed with a certain problem that there was an area of so-called heavy

01:10:05.840 --> 01:10:12.000
[Guest 2]: industry, which were large complex capital intensive factories that were essential for

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:17.680
[Guest 2]: the rest of industrialization. So that led to proposition one, that the government's

01:10:17.680 --> 01:10:22.160
[Guest 2]: going to do it, the government will build the public sector companies who will be that

01:10:22.160 --> 01:10:28.580
[Guest 2]: heavy industry. It almost seems farcical today to think that this would be a bright idea.

01:10:28.580 --> 01:10:32.440
[Guest 2]: But a lot of very smart people at that time thought this was the way to go. And amusingly

01:10:32.440 --> 01:10:37.320
[Guest 2]: enough, if you read the Bombay Club, which is the business community of Bombay, they

01:10:37.320 --> 01:10:42.420
[Guest 2]: are pretty much asking for the same. They're saying that, look, I can make light machinery,

01:10:42.420 --> 01:10:48.120
[Guest 2]: I can make consumer goods, but I can't do the heavy industry myself.

01:10:48.120 --> 01:10:52.240
[Guest 2]: Side by side with this is a finance story, which is where is this money going to come

01:10:52.240 --> 01:10:58.240
[Guest 2]: from? And at that time, the taxation capabilities of the government were quite limited. The

01:10:58.240 --> 01:11:05.280
[Guest 2]: formalization of the economy was quite limited. There were also a bunch of regulatory disasters

01:11:05.280 --> 01:11:12.040
[Guest 2]: on insurance companies and banks. And again, with the benefit of hindsight, we would say

01:11:12.040 --> 01:11:18.360
[Guest 2]: what was needed was to build state capacity in banking regulation, or state capacity in

01:11:18.360 --> 01:11:22.000
[Guest 2]: insurance regulation. But those are very modern ideas which are not present today.

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:29.240
[Guest 2]: So alongside the government-led and government-planned machinery in the real sector, there came a

01:11:29.240 --> 01:11:34.160
[Guest 2]: government-led and government-planned machinery in the financial sector, where the government

01:11:34.160 --> 01:11:38.760
[Guest 2]: built a whole financial system. There were government banks, there were pretty much only

01:11:38.760 --> 01:11:43.640
[Guest 2]: government banks. The government had a monopoly in life insurance, the government had a monopoly

01:11:43.640 --> 01:11:48.000
[Guest 2]: in general insurance, the government had a monopoly in mutual funds, and so on.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:53.880
[Guest 2]: So in one after another element of finance, the government directly controlled the financial

01:11:53.880 --> 01:11:58.680
[Guest 2]: system. So the words used, again, I cringe at the words, but at the time, the words used

01:11:58.680 --> 01:12:07.040
[Guest 2]: were that the state would mobilize savings and direct them into applications in investment.

01:12:07.040 --> 01:12:12.880
[Guest 2]: So you really didn't have a modern concept of a market-based financial system where private

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:18.680
[Guest 2]: people and speculators and risk and return would generate the allocation of capital.

01:12:18.680 --> 01:12:24.280
[Guest 2]: Those are very modern concepts in India today. If I may say, only understood in a limited

01:12:24.280 --> 01:12:27.120
[Guest 2]: way by most people in the Indian landscape.

01:12:27.120 --> 01:12:32.600
[Guest 2]: So if I had to characterize that period, this was that story of government leadership in

01:12:32.600 --> 01:12:36.360
[Guest 2]: the real sector, based on the notion that if we don't do this, the private sector will

01:12:36.360 --> 01:12:42.200
[Guest 2]: not do it. Plus, government control of the financial system undertaken in an autarkic

01:12:42.200 --> 01:12:45.960
[Guest 2]: environment where you don't do international trade, you don't do international capital

01:12:45.960 --> 01:12:50.600
[Guest 2]: flows. So that's my rough description of what was done.

01:12:50.600 --> 01:12:54.240
[Guest 2]: And exactly, Amit, as you said a moment ago, once you go down this route, it just goes

01:12:54.240 --> 01:13:00.720
[Guest 2]: bad and it gets worse because we will experience one failure after another. Today, we know

01:13:00.720 --> 01:13:07.760
[Guest 2]: that the only flexible, endlessly thinking, endlessly adapting system is a market economy.

01:13:07.760 --> 01:13:14.040
[Guest 2]: When they try to do these state-led projects, then every day the steam would come out of

01:13:14.040 --> 01:13:18.400
[Guest 2]: some sprockets that doesn't work and there'd be a problem there. So you would layer on

01:13:18.400 --> 01:13:23.160
[Guest 2]: one more rule and one more rule and one more rule. And this is a complexity layers on complexity

01:13:23.160 --> 01:13:27.920
[Guest 2]: and it becomes an incomprehensibly rigid, inflexible system where basically nobody's

01:13:27.920 --> 01:13:33.240
[Guest 2]: thinking. So there's the silence of a graveyard that happens in a centrally planned system.

01:13:33.240 --> 01:13:37.280
[Guest 2]: When the government is telling you about products and processes, the private sector switches

01:13:37.280 --> 01:13:41.960
[Guest 2]: off their minds and they say, just tell me what to do, I'll do it. And it becomes just

01:13:41.960 --> 01:13:46.680
[Guest 2]: one big bureaucracy, becomes a world of obedience. There's a lack of creativity, there's a lack

01:13:46.680 --> 01:13:52.060
[Guest 2]: of innovation, there's a lack of hunger. And there's more than an echo of all these maladies

01:13:52.060 --> 01:13:57.440
[Guest 2]: around us in India today. In large parts of the Indian economy today, you've got the deadness

01:13:57.440 --> 01:14:01.680
[Guest 2]: of central planning systems where a government chooses the technology, a government tells

01:14:01.680 --> 01:14:06.960
[Guest 2]: you, which is the way to do something. And the employees of private firms basically become

01:14:06.960 --> 01:14:11.040
[Guest 2]: like glorified bureaucrats. They just say, look, you tell me the policy, I'll do it.

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:16.040
[Guest 2]: It's too risky for a private person to put capital on the line and take a risk of innovating

01:14:16.040 --> 01:14:18.120
[Guest 2]: and building something.

01:14:18.120 --> 01:14:23.640
[Guest 1]: I would add a couple of things to this. One is the state capacity problem goes on for

01:14:23.640 --> 01:14:27.600
[Guest 1]: a very long time in India, and it really starts with the East India Company. And I don't want

01:14:27.600 --> 01:14:31.880
[Guest 1]: to blame everything wrong with India on East India Company and the colonial powers. But

01:14:31.880 --> 01:14:38.040
[Guest 1]: the fact of the matter is that investments in state capacity were very low. So there

01:14:38.040 --> 01:14:43.040
[Guest 1]: are multiple reasons why they call India the extractive, the worst victim of the British

01:14:43.040 --> 01:14:48.120
[Guest 1]: extractive economy, because all the taxation that was collected, all the resources that

01:14:48.120 --> 01:14:54.920
[Guest 1]: were diverted, not much of it was invested in India. And if we really think about Scottish

01:14:54.920 --> 01:15:00.920
[Guest 1]: enlightenment values, right, and we bring them on to the modern world, especially the

01:15:00.920 --> 01:15:09.120
[Guest 1]: financial sector, nobody is saying that there is no role for the state. Most of us who are

01:15:09.120 --> 01:15:14.920
[Guest 1]: talking about a certain kind of decentralized emergent order, we think of the role of the

01:15:14.920 --> 01:15:19.320
[Guest 1]: state in a very specific way, which is it needs to enforce contracts, right? It needs

01:15:19.320 --> 01:15:23.640
[Guest 1]: to bring in some basic financial regulation. It needs to have disclosure requirements so

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:27.920
[Guest 1]: that people who are investing know what kind of risks they are exposed to, right? It needs

01:15:27.920 --> 01:15:32.680
[Guest 1]: to have some kind of financial, you know, regulatory infrastructure so that there aren't

01:15:32.680 --> 01:15:37.160
[Guest 1]: like repeated runs on banks and, you know, all the basic stuff. Now, the fact of the

01:15:37.160 --> 01:15:44.480
[Guest 1]: matter is this infrastructure was not present in India, okay? India was low on bureaucrats

01:15:44.480 --> 01:15:50.360
[Guest 1]: per capita. It was low on judges per capita, on contract enforcement per capita. Even in

01:15:50.360 --> 01:15:56.400
[Guest 1]: colonial times, this is not just a modern day problem. So now if you don't have a sensible

01:15:56.400 --> 01:16:02.200
[Guest 1]: way of enforcing contracts, then obviously you're going to worry a lot about fraud in

01:16:02.200 --> 01:16:07.680
[Guest 1]: the market, right? Which means I live in the United States and I have very little fear

01:16:07.680 --> 01:16:13.080
[Guest 1]: of fraud, right? Because there is so much, you know, both market competition and consumer

01:16:13.080 --> 01:16:19.120
[Guest 1]: protection and litigation and tort law and, you know, like the regulatory, you know, sort

01:16:19.120 --> 01:16:24.440
[Guest 1]: of they will throw the book at any firm that is, you know, negligent in the behavior and

01:16:24.440 --> 01:16:29.480
[Guest 1]: I drink something adulterated and get sick or something like that. I literally have zero

01:16:29.480 --> 01:16:36.960
[Guest 1]: fear, okay? There is an enormous fear in India in the 1950s of failure that comes from the

01:16:36.960 --> 01:16:41.880
[Guest 1]: private sector. So there are two kinds, two, three kinds of fear. One is the basic fear,

01:16:41.880 --> 01:16:45.520
[Guest 1]: which is, you know, like what happens when your weed gets adulterated and people get

01:16:45.520 --> 01:16:51.360
[Guest 1]: poisoned, you know, that kind of basic level fear and fraud. The second kind of fear is

01:16:51.360 --> 01:16:58.040
[Guest 1]: a misallocation. Resources are so scarce that if they went in the hands of the wrong industrialist,

01:16:58.040 --> 01:17:01.920
[Guest 1]: then we are wasting these resources, right? They don't understand that, that when there's

01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:06.520
[Guest 1]: a bankruptcy, resources just need to switch ownership. The resources themselves don't

01:17:06.520 --> 01:17:13.520
[Guest 1]: die. Okay. But there is this great fear. And the third fear is in some sense, the collapse

01:17:13.520 --> 01:17:17.560
[Guest 1]: of the system or loss in the faith of the system, right? Like this is your classic run

01:17:17.560 --> 01:17:26.160
[Guest 1]: on private banks kind of fear. So if you don't have a sensible state led infrastructure to

01:17:26.160 --> 01:17:32.000
[Guest 1]: kind of provide this scaffolding to prevent the worst things that come out of, you know,

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:36.880
[Guest 1]: private or decentralized emergent orders, then you're going to want to clamp down on

01:17:36.880 --> 01:17:42.440
[Guest 1]: everything. And I think that is part of it, right? You simply don't trust what is happening

01:17:42.440 --> 01:17:47.280
[Guest 1]: in the markets. When markets do function. Now, a lot of the times what I was talking

01:17:47.280 --> 01:17:52.000
[Guest 1]: about this, you know, I don't worry about adulteration and like, you know, eating unsafe

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:56.580
[Guest 1]: foods and things like that. Most of it is not state regulated, actually. I'm never checking

01:17:56.580 --> 01:18:02.000
[Guest 1]: if there is a, you know, FDA stamp or an ISI stamp on what I'm doing. It's just, I live

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:07.240
[Guest 1]: in a world where market competition is so strong and so robust and reputation is so

01:18:07.240 --> 01:18:14.080
[Guest 1]: strong and litigation is so aggressive that I know that I can exist in the shadow of that

01:18:14.080 --> 01:18:19.800
[Guest 1]: system and still be safe. Right? Now, even that shadow of that system did not exist in

01:18:19.800 --> 01:18:24.480
[Guest 1]: 1950. So I think we need to think about this. It's not like there was this incredible market

01:18:24.480 --> 01:18:28.640
[Guest 1]: system which was thriving and amazing and contracts were enforced and Nehru came out

01:18:28.640 --> 01:18:32.360
[Guest 1]: of the blue, swooped in and said, no, we're going to end that system and we're going to

01:18:32.360 --> 01:18:35.400
[Guest 1]: replace it with this. That system simply didn't exist.

01:18:35.400 --> 01:18:40.000
[Guest 2]: I want to disagree slightly. If you think of the capitalism that was present in Bombay

01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:46.280
[Guest 2]: pre-independence, if you went on the fort, there was actually something remarkable there,

01:18:46.280 --> 01:18:52.120
[Guest 2]: which we sometimes don't give enough credit for. As an example, the Metropolitan Magistrates

01:18:52.120 --> 01:18:58.520
[Guest 2]: Court in Bombay was adjudicating commercial disputes based on the British Quality Contracts

01:18:58.520 --> 01:19:05.280
[Guest 2]: Act of 1870 and the British Evidence Act of 1870. They came side by side and was writing

01:19:05.280 --> 01:19:11.080
[Guest 2]: orders that were decent by early 20th century British standards. It's absolutely mind blowing

01:19:11.080 --> 01:19:17.720
[Guest 2]: that in a developing country like India, there was a certain judicial capability, the likes

01:19:17.720 --> 01:19:23.680
[Guest 2]: of which, again, we have completely lost in India today. We have declined very badly compared

01:19:23.680 --> 01:19:29.560
[Guest 2]: to that period. Where I will fault the policy community of that period, the Nehru of that

01:19:29.560 --> 01:19:37.320
[Guest 2]: period, was a failure to recognize the value and the importance of the infrastructure of

01:19:37.320 --> 01:19:43.000
[Guest 2]: civilization that we got from the British. We were so angry about the freedom movement.

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:50.960
[Guest 2]: We were so convinced that the British dealt us a bad hand of cards, that we did not sufficiently

01:19:50.960 --> 01:19:57.480
[Guest 2]: treasure some of these things and nurture them and build them. And over 20, 30 years,

01:19:57.480 --> 01:20:03.640
[Guest 2]: a lot of that collapsed. One little thing about unintended consequences was that all

01:20:03.640 --> 01:20:08.720
[Guest 2]: the best lawyers and judges of India at the time were trained in London because there

01:20:08.720 --> 01:20:14.320
[Guest 2]: were really no law schools and law universities in India. And it's incredible how damaging

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:19.080
[Guest 2]: it was when the currency controls prevented people from going abroad to study because

01:20:19.080 --> 01:20:22.960
[Guest 2]: you couldn't get foreign exchange. Even if you were rich enough to go abroad to study,

01:20:22.960 --> 01:20:27.860
[Guest 2]: you couldn't get the foreign exchange. And sure enough, 25 years later, you got a precipitous

01:20:27.860 --> 01:20:33.880
[Guest 2]: collapse in the quality of judges and lawyers all over the country because that pipeline

01:20:33.880 --> 01:20:40.200
[Guest 2]: had broken. And so I think of some of the British infrastructure of civilization, of

01:20:40.200 --> 01:20:47.400
[Guest 2]: the common law, of the courts, of the criminal enforcement as something that the INC did

01:20:47.400 --> 01:20:54.040
[Guest 2]: not treasure adequately. We were the sorcerer's apprentice. We got the reins of power, but

01:20:54.040 --> 01:20:58.600
[Guest 2]: we didn't understand the intricate checks and balances through which civilization is

01:20:58.600 --> 01:21:04.240
[Guest 2]: upheld every day. And we went off with this grand idea of a developmental state and we

01:21:04.240 --> 01:21:09.640
[Guest 2]: didn't nurture the foundations of civilization, which is the machinery like the criminal justice

01:21:09.640 --> 01:21:15.320
[Guest 2]: system and the courts, the commercial disputes.

01:21:15.320 --> 01:21:21.320
[Guest 1]: I think we disagree less than you imagine, Ajay. I agree with you that we have excellent

01:21:21.320 --> 01:21:25.040
[Guest 1]: judges at the time. The point is not that we don't have them. The point is we don't

01:21:25.040 --> 01:21:31.240
[Guest 1]: have enough of them. So you have excellent courts in all the presidency towns. You have

01:21:31.240 --> 01:21:37.480
[Guest 1]: them in Bombay, in Madras, in Calcutta. You go to rural India, there is virtually no modern

01:21:37.480 --> 01:21:42.880
[Guest 1]: kind of dispute resolution penetration because these zamindars have simply not made the investments

01:21:42.880 --> 01:21:47.560
[Guest 1]: and the colonial powers have just let them run amok with whatever the hell the zamindars

01:21:47.560 --> 01:21:53.400
[Guest 1]: want to do. On the other extreme, you have, say, the Maharaja of Mysore or the Maharaja

01:21:53.400 --> 01:21:59.240
[Guest 1]: of Travancore, right? They have made enormous investments in education, health, you know,

01:21:59.240 --> 01:22:05.760
[Guest 1]: basic public sanitation, court system. And you can see the benefits of that even today

01:22:05.760 --> 01:22:09.760
[Guest 1]: in modern day India coming from those states because of investments that were made a hundred

01:22:09.760 --> 01:22:14.400
[Guest 1]: years ago. So it's not that I think the British investments, the quality was bad. It's just

01:22:14.400 --> 01:22:22.040
[Guest 1]: that I think it wasn't enough and as widespread that India could overnight switch to, you

01:22:22.040 --> 01:22:28.160
[Guest 1]: know, removing all market controls and switching. Like if we think about banking, you know,

01:22:28.160 --> 01:22:32.360
[Guest 1]: you spoke about Larry White and there's this whole thing. I mean, his whole work is on

01:22:32.360 --> 01:22:38.080
[Guest 1]: free banking that emerged during, you know, in Scotland. You look at the Chettiar community

01:22:38.080 --> 01:22:42.760
[Guest 1]: in the southern part of India. I mean, just the entrepreneurship, they were basically

01:22:42.760 --> 01:22:48.920
[Guest 1]: the financiers of Singapore and Malaysia, right? They would actually travel and they

01:22:48.920 --> 01:22:55.000
[Guest 1]: would finance huge projects, right? You had this thing going on in India and then of course

01:22:55.000 --> 01:22:58.520
[Guest 1]: all the banking regulation came in and none of their, you know, networks could function

01:22:58.520 --> 01:23:03.280
[Guest 1]: anymore and they couldn't quite convert it into a formal bank as easily as they wanted.

01:23:03.280 --> 01:23:08.360
[Guest 1]: So all this human capability existed. Some of it existed formally through the British

01:23:08.360 --> 01:23:13.240
[Guest 1]: conduits through lawyers and bureaucrats and civil servants and things. Some of it existed

01:23:13.240 --> 01:23:17.880
[Guest 1]: through our caste networks, right? There's a Chettiar community, there is a Marwadi community

01:23:17.880 --> 01:23:24.840
[Guest 1]: and things like that. But these are still small pockets. The great Scottish enlightenment

01:23:24.840 --> 01:23:31.400
[Guest 1]: idea that we can trade with strangers because the institution allows us to trade with strangers

01:23:31.400 --> 01:23:39.400
[Guest 1]: and both sides can benefit. That was not the reality in India as I understand India at

01:23:39.400 --> 01:23:45.880
[Guest 1]: that time. So I think Ajay and I disagree a lot less than we originally imagined.

01:23:45.880 --> 01:23:51.240
[Guest 2]: If I may just try to restate just for both of you to take a stab at it, the proposition

01:23:51.240 --> 01:23:59.360
[Guest 2]: I want to hold up for examination is it is remarkable that standing in 2021, we feel

01:23:59.360 --> 01:24:06.760
[Guest 2]: that it is more likely for a criminal matter or a commercial dispute to generate a bad

01:24:06.760 --> 01:24:12.160
[Guest 2]: outcome with the criminal justice system and the courts of India today as compared to where

01:24:12.160 --> 01:24:24.360
[Guest 2]: we were, say, in 1943. I find that a mind-blowing proposition and I wonder why. I blame Nehru

01:24:24.360 --> 01:24:30.520
[Guest 2]: and his community for being the sorcerer's apprentice. They were so fascinated that we

01:24:30.520 --> 01:24:35.480
[Guest 2]: will go build steel mills. They didn't understand that the real temple of democracy is the courts

01:24:35.480 --> 01:24:38.960
[Guest 2]: and the police stations.

01:24:38.960 --> 01:24:43.280
[Amit Varma]: Those are really wise words and I can see that you disagree a little bit about disagreeing.

01:24:43.280 --> 01:24:47.280
[Amit Varma]: So I don't know how we will unravel that. But obviously, I'm not a student of history

01:24:47.280 --> 01:24:52.200
[Amit Varma]: and can't talk about the rule of law back then. But just looking around me, every single

01:24:52.200 --> 01:24:56.440
[Amit Varma]: businessman friend I have, and I have people who run small businesses and all that, will

01:24:56.440 --> 01:25:00.040
[Amit Varma]: tell you that the rule of law is absent. That if there is a dispute, you know, there will

01:25:00.040 --> 01:25:04.000
[Amit Varma]: be no dispute resolution. It's just there on paper. You can't actually get anything

01:25:04.000 --> 01:25:09.160
[Amit Varma]: done. You survive on different systems that are not encoded in the law, different systems

01:25:09.160 --> 01:25:12.040
[Amit Varma]: of trust within the community and so on and so forth.

01:25:12.040 --> 01:25:16.080
[Amit Varma]: Ajay, a little while back, referred to the deadness of the system and that reminded me

01:25:16.080 --> 01:25:22.160
[Amit Varma]: of this great quote by Shashi Tharoor where he's talking about one of Nehru's big mistakes.

01:25:22.160 --> 01:25:26.560
[Amit Varma]: And there Tharoor said, quote, Nehru felt it was necessary to have the state to be the

01:25:26.560 --> 01:25:31.160
[Amit Varma]: disinterested maibap of the people who would act in the interest of the common person because

01:25:31.160 --> 01:25:35.960
[Amit Varma]: a state would not be motivated by profit. Of course, what he failed to realize was that

01:25:35.960 --> 01:25:40.040
[Amit Varma]: as a result, he'd put bureaucrats in charge of the commanding heights of the economy rather

01:25:40.040 --> 01:25:45.920
[Amit Varma]: than businessmen. And these bureaucrats were better at regulating stagnation and distributing

01:25:45.920 --> 01:25:51.840
[Amit Varma]: poverty than actually generating wealth. Stop quote. And you know, Ajay also spoke about

01:25:51.840 --> 01:25:56.480
[Amit Varma]: how difficult it was to do any kind of innovation or get permissions to do anything. And there's

01:25:56.480 --> 01:26:00.480
[Amit Varma]: a great passage by Gurcharan Das, which I want to read out, which is from his book India

01:26:00.480 --> 01:26:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Unbound, which really illustrates this, where he writes, quote, The way that the bureaucracy

01:26:04.440 --> 01:26:09.000
[Amit Varma]: went about administering the licensing system created a nightmare for the entrepreneur. An

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:14.680
[Amit Varma]: untrained army of underpaid third-rate engineers with inadequate and ill-organized information

01:26:14.680 --> 01:26:20.640
[Amit Varma]: and without clear-cut criteria vetted thousands of applications on an ad hoc basis. The low-level

01:26:20.640 --> 01:26:25.960
[Amit Varma]: functionaries took months in the futile micro-review of an application and finally sent it for

01:26:25.960 --> 01:26:30.600
[Amit Varma]: approval to the administrative ministry. The ministry again lost months reviewing the same

01:26:30.600 --> 01:26:35.200
[Amit Varma]: data before it sent the application to an inter-ministerial licensing committee of senior

01:26:35.200 --> 01:26:40.720
[Amit Varma]: bureaucrats who were equally ignorant of entrepreneurial realities and who also operated on ad hoc

01:26:40.720 --> 01:26:45.400
[Amit Varma]: criteria in the absence of well-ordered priorities. After the minister's approval, the investor

01:26:45.400 --> 01:26:50.080
[Amit Varma]: had to seek approval for the import of machinery from the capital goods licensing committee.

01:26:50.080 --> 01:26:54.800
[Amit Varma]: If a foreign collaboration was involved, an inter-ministerial foreign agreements committee

01:26:54.800 --> 01:26:59.320
[Amit Varma]: also had to give its consent. If finance was needed from a state finance institution, the

01:26:59.320 --> 01:27:04.680
[Amit Varma]: same scrutiny had to be repeated afresh. The result was enormous delays, sometimes lasting

01:27:04.680 --> 01:27:11.280
[Amit Varma]: years with staggering opportunities for corruption. Large business houses set up parallel bureaucracies

01:27:11.280 --> 01:27:17.380
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi to follow up on their files, organize bribes and win licenses. Tragically, the system

01:27:17.380 --> 01:27:22.280
[Amit Varma]: ended in thwarting competition, entrepreneurship and growth without achieving any of his social

01:27:22.280 --> 01:27:27.400
[Amit Varma]: objectives. And there's a similar passage I marked out by Rakesh Mohan from his introduction

01:27:27.400 --> 01:27:31.320
[Amit Varma]: to the book Transforming India, which I'll link from the show notes. I'm not going to

01:27:31.320 --> 01:27:36.600
[Amit Varma]: just keep reading out dystopian passages. And Gurcharan Das's book India Unbound is

01:27:36.600 --> 01:27:42.240
[Amit Varma]: also an excellent sort of narrative of this entire period of history, which I think disillusioned

01:27:42.240 --> 01:27:47.160
[Amit Varma]: him so much that the moment that it seemed that there could be a turn away from the dispensation

01:27:47.160 --> 01:27:51.920
[Amit Varma]: that led India through all these decades of misery, he went all in for Modi and then he

01:27:51.920 --> 01:27:57.360
[Amit Varma]: didn't adjust when he saw the reality of what a Modi administration actually was, which

01:27:57.360 --> 01:28:01.860
[Amit Varma]: is which is kind of tragic when it happens to people, right, that you have rational reasons

01:28:01.860 --> 01:28:07.560
[Amit Varma]: to say support a person. But even when it all goes south, you know, and you should rationally

01:28:07.560 --> 01:28:12.600
[Amit Varma]: turn away, you just become sort of embedded in that position. Sorry, that's an aside.

01:28:12.600 --> 01:28:14.600
[Amit Varma]: But any thoughts on that?

01:28:14.600 --> 01:28:21.960
[Guest 1]: No, but, you know, there is something valuable. I mean, the passage that you're reading, OK,

01:28:21.960 --> 01:28:26.680
[Guest 1]: now, you know, again, this is I don't just want to keep separating Ajay and myself from

01:28:26.680 --> 01:28:31.360
[Guest 1]: like the rest of the people as if we're like some special category of humans. But you're

01:28:31.360 --> 01:28:36.760
[Guest 1]: special for me. Well, well, thank you. Both of you are special to me. But economists do

01:28:36.760 --> 01:28:42.080
[Guest 1]: think a little bit differently about this. And especially people like Ajay and myself

01:28:42.080 --> 01:28:47.240
[Guest 1]: who are like particularly trained in public choice economics. Right. The way one way to

01:28:47.240 --> 01:28:52.320
[Guest 1]: interpret the passage that you read from Gurcharan is that this is about bureaucrats versus entrepreneurs.

01:28:52.320 --> 01:28:56.440
[Guest 1]: Right. It's almost like one type of person versus another type. It's very like it's about

01:28:56.440 --> 01:29:04.520
[Guest 1]: incentives. But it is the the first thing I know from public choice theory is behavioral

01:29:04.520 --> 01:29:10.960
[Guest 1]: symmetry. Right. That every individual is fundamentally the same. There is nothing special

01:29:10.960 --> 01:29:15.400
[Guest 1]: about an entrepreneur that is different from a bureaucrat, except that the entrepreneur

01:29:15.400 --> 01:29:21.400
[Guest 1]: is the residual claimant in a firm and a bureaucrat is not. Right. So if I put the exact same

01:29:21.400 --> 01:29:27.360
[Guest 1]: people and I did some kind of, you know, crazy Chris Nolan type like switch them from one

01:29:27.360 --> 01:29:32.400
[Guest 1]: to another in some crazy science fiction movie, they would act the way there's a movie plot

01:29:32.400 --> 01:29:36.960
[Guest 2]: that we should have two twins who are separated at birth and one of them becomes the bureaucrat

01:29:36.960 --> 01:29:41.520
[Guest 1]: and one of them becomes an entrepreneur. Yeah. And then you flip them and now they act completely

01:29:41.520 --> 01:29:46.440
[Amit Varma]: differently than what they are supposed to act like. Right. Well, you could argue Shashi

01:29:46.440 --> 01:29:49.720
[Amit Varma]: Kapoor and Amitabh Bachchan did all those films where they are brothers and one is a

01:29:49.720 --> 01:29:55.200
[Amit Varma]: police officer and the other is a criminal is exactly that. I want to pick up on that

01:29:55.200 --> 01:30:00.520
[Guest 1]: criminal thing later for a minute. OK, but yeah. So it almost seems like, oh, there is

01:30:00.520 --> 01:30:05.080
[Guest 1]: this Brahmin Baniya conflict or this, you know, entrepreneur civil servant conflict

01:30:05.080 --> 01:30:10.600
[Guest 1]: or, you know, the person who is the low level engineer. I mean, they are low level engineers,

01:30:10.600 --> 01:30:13.680
[Guest 1]: not because there's something wrong with them, but because that's the incentive they're in.

01:30:13.680 --> 01:30:17.680
[Guest 1]: Their engineers being made to push files is supposed to solve engineering problems. Right.

01:30:17.680 --> 01:30:22.960
[Guest 1]: That's why they're low. So there is something problematic, I think, about putting this as

01:30:22.960 --> 01:30:28.400
[Guest 1]: a group, this group versus that group or this category of persons versus that category of

01:30:28.400 --> 01:30:32.360
[Guest 1]: persons. I don't know if that's what Gurcharan intended to do, but that's the way it seemed

01:30:32.360 --> 01:30:37.840
[Guest 1]: to me, just taking one quote out of context. And I think that is where the economists would

01:30:37.840 --> 01:30:45.480
[Guest 1]: disagree that the problem lies with. It doesn't matter who ran the system. They could not

01:30:45.480 --> 01:30:53.760
[Guest 1]: make it work. Right. You could get, you know, God himself to show up and they couldn't possibly

01:30:53.760 --> 01:30:58.800
[Guest 1]: do a better job of the permits than the low class or low quality engineers that, you know,

01:30:58.800 --> 01:31:04.520
[Guest 1]: Gurcharan is so mad about. Right. Similarly, there is no entrepreneur who can easily overcome

01:31:04.520 --> 01:31:08.560
[Guest 1]: the system and still manage to make a profit and still remain honest. To me, that is the

01:31:08.560 --> 01:31:12.280
[Guest 1]: big takeaway. And it also connects to the thing that you said about there's a whole

01:31:12.280 --> 01:31:16.600
[Guest 1]: category of people in India who are so exhausted by socialism. They just latched on to Modi

01:31:16.600 --> 01:31:21.440
[Guest 1]: when he came around. That again tells you that there is a fundamental misunderstanding.

01:31:21.440 --> 01:31:25.920
[Guest 1]: This is not about groups. This is not about people. This is not about Brahmins and Baniyas

01:31:25.920 --> 01:31:33.560
[Guest 1]: and Nehru Gandhi versus someone else. It's just a misunderstanding that Modi continued

01:31:33.560 --> 01:31:41.600
[Guest 1]: a system without changing it very much, continued a commitment to a status system. In fact,

01:31:41.600 --> 01:31:47.480
[Guest 1]: in some margins, like increased the centralized control, did not really trust markets and

01:31:47.480 --> 01:31:52.680
[Guest 1]: decentralized actions to do their job. So he's making the same mistake as Nehru did.

01:31:52.680 --> 01:31:59.800
[Guest 1]: Nehru's original sin is not investing in education, in primary education. Right. He only invested

01:31:59.800 --> 01:32:05.120
[Guest 1]: in like higher level education in health and in local government. I think the lack of local

01:32:05.120 --> 01:32:10.880
[Guest 1]: government, which is a byproduct of high degree of centralized planning in India. I mean,

01:32:10.880 --> 01:32:15.120
[Guest 1]: no thought of, yeah, we need steel mills, but who's going to pick up the garbage? Right.

01:32:15.120 --> 01:32:18.880
[Guest 1]: This is something that was never planned for or thought through. And I think it's the same

01:32:18.880 --> 01:32:23.680
[Guest 1]: thing with Modi and his followers, which is because there is a fundamental misunderstanding

01:32:23.680 --> 01:32:29.040
[Guest 1]: of what the system is and why it works. There's a lot of blaming of this group versus that

01:32:29.040 --> 01:32:34.960
[Guest 1]: group. And there is no real understanding of what is the scaffolding I need to provide?

01:32:34.960 --> 01:32:38.880
[Guest 1]: What are the investments I need to make so that a decentralized system can actually do

01:32:38.880 --> 01:32:42.640
[Guest 1]: the magic that it's supposed to do the way Adam Smith talked about it? So I think that

01:32:42.640 --> 01:32:46.880
[Guest 1]: quote that you read is very valuable, but for a different reason than why you read it.

01:32:46.880 --> 01:32:51.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, first of all, I'll come out and say that I don't think that Mr. Daswood necessarily

01:32:51.240 --> 01:32:55.080
[Amit Varma]: was taking that view. I think he'd also be aware of the power of incentives. And that's

01:32:55.080 --> 01:32:59.560
[Amit Varma]: a point worth underscoring that whenever people talk about a particular system, the bottom

01:32:59.560 --> 01:33:02.960
[Amit Varma]: line is we will all respond to incentives, which is why whenever I talk about a system

01:33:02.960 --> 01:33:07.640
[Amit Varma]: of governance, I point out that the system of governance you want is a system in which

01:33:07.640 --> 01:33:12.440
[Amit Varma]: you should assume the worst person you can think of, the biggest sociopath as a person

01:33:12.440 --> 01:33:16.840
[Amit Varma]: in charge. And then if you're okay with it, it's a good system of government because there

01:33:16.840 --> 01:33:21.760
[Amit Varma]: are enough checks and balances, there are mechanisms within that which increase accountability,

01:33:21.760 --> 01:33:26.840
[Amit Varma]: the incentives are going in the right direction. The other thing I would say, and I don't want

01:33:26.840 --> 01:33:30.920
[Amit Varma]: to defend Gurcharan necessarily. And in this case, I'm not because he didn't change his

01:33:30.920 --> 01:33:35.420
[Amit Varma]: mind after Modi did all the things that he did. But the point is, you know, the Congress

01:33:35.420 --> 01:33:41.720
[Amit Varma]: politician Salman Sos was on my show a year and a half ago or so. And he made the point

01:33:41.720 --> 01:33:46.880
[Amit Varma]: that a lot of Modi's rhetoric in 2014 was great, you know, minimum government, maximum

01:33:46.880 --> 01:33:50.920
[Amit Varma]: governance, and obviously, he's gone in the opposite direction, that the business of government

01:33:50.920 --> 01:33:54.560
[Amit Varma]: is not to be in business or something to that effect, obviously, he's gone in the opposite

01:33:54.560 --> 01:33:59.880
[Amit Varma]: direction. A lot of the rhetoric could have fooled people who were open to being fooled,

01:33:59.880 --> 01:34:04.600
[Amit Varma]: or who were just simply tired of the existing system as it were. So I don't judge people

01:34:04.600 --> 01:34:10.340
[Amit Varma]: who supported say, Modi in 2014, too harshly. But at the same time, if you hadn't realized

01:34:10.340 --> 01:34:15.520
[Amit Varma]: what was going on by 2017, then shame on you, then you had anchored yourself to the person

01:34:15.520 --> 01:34:20.880
[Amit Varma]: and the party instead of to the principles that you claim to espouse. So, yeah, I haven't

01:34:20.880 --> 01:34:25.120
[Guest 1]: spoken to Gurcharan about this personally. So I really can't comment on I don't know

01:34:25.120 --> 01:34:29.840
[Guest 1]: what his views were then. And I don't know what they are now. I mean, I meant more generally

01:34:29.840 --> 01:34:35.680
[Guest 1]: about how we think of different groups of people, even the entrepreneurs of that time,

01:34:35.680 --> 01:34:39.360
[Guest 1]: frankly, I'm not very impressed by them. I mean, we talk about the Bombay plan and things

01:34:39.360 --> 01:34:44.920
[Guest 1]: like that. But to me, there are aspects of the Bombay plan which just stink of this bootleggers

01:34:44.920 --> 01:34:50.800
[Amit Varma]: and Baptists kind of story, right? It's a point I made to Ram Guha also, he didn't respond

01:34:50.800 --> 01:34:54.880
[Amit Varma]: in the particular conversation we were having, but I'd because I guess I didn't push him.

01:34:54.880 --> 01:34:58.960
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, in his history of post-independent India, he had written about the Bombay plan.

01:34:58.960 --> 01:35:02.920
[Amit Varma]: And he said, you see, even the capitalists were aware that too much capitalism is a bad

01:35:02.920 --> 01:35:07.720
[Guest 1]: thing. Of course they were because it's barriers to entry. Exactly. So my point there was that,

01:35:07.720 --> 01:35:11.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, what is good for markets is not necessarily what is good for particular big

01:35:11.440 --> 01:35:16.000
[Amit Varma]: businesses. It's always the opposite, that what ideally a free market should be is that

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:19.680
[Amit Varma]: you have no barriers to entry. Anybody can come and compete, competition is the best

01:35:19.680 --> 01:35:25.120
[Amit Varma]: regulation. But what businessmen will always want, hey that protect my turf. So obviously,

01:35:25.120 --> 01:35:29.480
[Amit Varma]: a big businessman will want something which is very protectionist, where newcomers can't

01:35:29.480 --> 01:35:34.280
[Amit Varma]: come up and compete against them, where the state is protecting them, and so on and so

01:35:34.280 --> 01:35:39.600
[Amit Varma]: forth. So it is natural, you can't expect a capitalist necessarily to be in favor of

01:35:39.600 --> 01:35:44.160
[Amit Varma]: free markets, that you know, what is pro-business and pro-markets can often be exactly the opposite,

01:35:44.160 --> 01:35:49.840
[Guest 1]: which is a point a lot of people don't understand. No, and also just the arrogance of it, right?

01:35:49.840 --> 01:35:53.320
[Guest 1]: I mean, everyone talks about the Tatas and they're a great company, and I have nothing

01:35:53.320 --> 01:36:00.160
[Guest 1]: against them. But there's this idea of exceptionalism, right? Indian entrepreneurs can't really make

01:36:00.160 --> 01:36:08.560
[Guest 1]: steel except us. We are amazing. We can execute a big power plant really well. But the government

01:36:08.560 --> 01:36:13.520
[Guest 1]: is right, we can't trust anyone willy-nilly, right? I mean, today, globally, the largest

01:36:13.520 --> 01:36:18.160
[Guest 1]: steel company in the world is ArcelorMittal, okay? So this is, and if you talk to Mittal

01:36:18.160 --> 01:36:23.120
[Guest 1]: about it, he's like, oh, I couldn't run a small steel plant in India, so I went to Indonesia,

01:36:23.120 --> 01:36:27.240
[Guest 1]: and I decided that's how I'm going to build my steel empire. So it's a little bit interesting

01:36:27.240 --> 01:36:34.800
[Guest 1]: how everyone, whether it is with good intentions, whether it is because of hubris, or whether

01:36:34.800 --> 01:36:39.240
[Guest 1]: it is very explicit bootlegger and Baptist story that they just want to do this. I don't

01:36:39.240 --> 01:36:44.160
[Guest 1]: know these people in question personally, because I wasn't around in those times, nor

01:36:44.160 --> 01:36:48.880
[Guest 1]: have I studied them that keenly. So I don't know what was exactly going on in their mind.

01:36:48.880 --> 01:36:56.280
[Guest 1]: But I am always very wary of businessmen when they try to dictate economic policy in the

01:36:56.280 --> 01:37:01.040
[Guest 1]: specifics and not in the general. And even now, the greatest calls for protectionism

01:37:01.040 --> 01:37:06.080
[Guest 1]: in India and increase in tariffs and all this make in India nonsense, a lot of it is coming

01:37:06.080 --> 01:37:11.780
[Guest 1]: from industry, right? Your FICCI and CII, these guys are constantly, so the call is

01:37:11.780 --> 01:37:16.320
[Guest 1]: always more protectionism for my industry, right? Overall, we think free markets are

01:37:16.320 --> 01:37:20.320
[Guest 1]: a great idea. But in my case, I think you should increase the import tariffs so that,

01:37:20.320 --> 01:37:26.360
[Guest 1]: you know, my particular firm or industry is protected. So I am overall not, you know,

01:37:26.360 --> 01:37:32.480
[Guest 1]: thrilled about any group of people. You know, neither the lowly engineers nor the almighty

01:37:32.480 --> 01:37:36.920
[Guest 1]: entrepreneurs. I'm not thrilled with any of them, nor am I impressed.

01:37:36.920 --> 01:37:43.240
[Guest 2]: I want to go off on a slight tangent, but linking up to where Amit was a short while

01:37:43.240 --> 01:37:52.040
[Guest 2]: ago on how do people learn? How do people form views of the world? So if you are a practitioner,

01:37:52.040 --> 01:37:58.760
[Guest 2]: okay, either an employee in a government organization or an employee in a private organization,

01:37:58.760 --> 01:38:06.560
[Guest 2]: you're running a business, then it tends to be very difficult to envision a world five

01:38:06.560 --> 01:38:11.120
[Guest 2]: years out, 10 years out, 20 years out, that could be significantly different from where

01:38:11.120 --> 01:38:18.280
[Guest 2]: we are today. And at every point in India's journey, what I have experienced is that practitioners

01:38:18.280 --> 01:38:24.760
[Guest 2]: wear blinkers and consider X, Y, Z to be impossible. It's just too far. It's too complicated. It's

01:38:24.760 --> 01:38:28.120
[Guest 2]: too big. It's impossible. We in India will never be able to do it.

01:38:28.120 --> 01:38:33.640
[Guest 2]: Okay. I could narrate many examples of it. I want to single out two. The first of them

01:38:33.640 --> 01:38:40.680
[Guest 2]: was that when I landed up in India in 1993, at that time, it so happened that an aspirational

01:38:40.680 --> 01:38:47.800
[Guest 2]: value for exports, for merchandise exports from India was about a billion dollars a month.

01:38:47.800 --> 01:38:53.880
[Guest 2]: So month after month, people would watch that number. And it used to be the case that maybe

01:38:53.880 --> 01:38:57.600
[Guest 2]: two, three months a year, you'll be more than a billion dollars. And the rest of the year,

01:38:57.600 --> 01:39:04.160
[Guest 2]: we would be less than a billion dollars. And people were just incomprehensibly challenged

01:39:04.160 --> 01:39:11.720
[Guest 2]: at understanding the dollar values of exports that were being seen elsewhere in the world.

01:39:11.720 --> 01:39:16.800
[Guest 2]: And here we are today, not so many years after that, where we get numbers in excess of $30

01:39:16.800 --> 01:39:22.040
[Guest 2]: billion a month of merchandise exports. But the practitioner of that age could never have

01:39:22.040 --> 01:39:28.480
[Guest 2]: dreamed this. If you were in the world of business in 1993, you could never imagine

01:39:28.480 --> 01:39:36.520
[Guest 2]: an India where we will be doing $30, $35 billion a month of merchandise exports. Because practitioners

01:39:36.520 --> 01:39:42.240
[Guest 2]: tend to be extremely detailed and thorough in their understanding of the practical reality

01:39:42.240 --> 01:39:48.040
[Guest 2]: in front of them. And that comes with a lack of imagination and an ability to envision

01:39:48.040 --> 01:39:49.040
[Guest 2]: different worlds.

01:39:49.040 --> 01:39:53.480
[Guest 2]: I want to tell you another story. Some of my good friends were building the taxi company

01:39:53.480 --> 01:40:00.000
[Guest 2]: Meru. It was the first radio taxi company of India. And I remember them saying to me

01:40:00.000 --> 01:40:05.080
[Guest 2]: that, you know, really there's one particular Toyota car, which is the perfect car to be

01:40:05.080 --> 01:40:10.840
[Guest 2]: a taxi. It can take the beating, it can take the 100,000 kilometers a year that are required

01:40:10.840 --> 01:40:18.080
[Guest 2]: in the taxi business. But if you take the capital cost of that car into your spreadsheet,

01:40:18.080 --> 01:40:22.200
[Guest 2]: you end up with a price per kilometer that just doesn't work in India. And discount rates

01:40:22.200 --> 01:40:27.640
[Guest 2]: are bad. Interest rates are very high. So we end up having to buy crappy cars. And every

01:40:27.640 --> 01:40:32.520
[Guest 2]: few years we destroy, we throw away the cars and we start over. It's such a shame. Elsewhere

01:40:32.520 --> 01:40:38.320
[Guest 2]: in the world, any taxi company would buy these nice Toyota cars. Well, it took all of 10

01:40:38.320 --> 01:40:39.320
[Guest 2]: years.

01:40:39.320 --> 01:40:43.680
[Guest 2]: In 10 years, the price points in India had shifted, the interest rates in India had shifted,

01:40:43.680 --> 01:40:51.120
[Guest 2]: and there were entire taxi fleets coming about, which were those nice Toyota cars. So I think

01:40:51.120 --> 01:40:57.520
[Guest 2]: that it's difficult for people to dream deeper into the future. So if you talk to the folks

01:40:57.520 --> 01:41:02.720
[Guest 2]: in the Bombay club and you say to them that I will need, you know, a billion dollars to

01:41:02.720 --> 01:41:07.840
[Guest 2]: build a steel factory, a billion dollars to build an electricity generation plant, they

01:41:07.840 --> 01:41:12.680
[Guest 2]: would find it difficult to reconcile that with the kind of balance sheets and financial

01:41:12.680 --> 01:41:19.040
[Guest 2]: access that they were seeing in that age. And I think that's a reminder for all of us

01:41:19.040 --> 01:41:25.840
[Guest 2]: that we need to not worry about the practical constraints of the world around us. I think

01:41:25.840 --> 01:41:33.080
[Guest 2]: Bill Gates has a great line, the world changes less than you think in one year and more than

01:41:33.080 --> 01:41:38.920
[Guest 2]: you think in 10 years. So I think thinking for 10 years, thinking for 20 years is a very

01:41:38.920 --> 01:41:44.960
[Guest 2]: different project compared to small incremental improvements of one business or one government

01:41:44.960 --> 01:41:45.960
[Guest 2]: department.

01:41:45.960 --> 01:41:49.280
[Guest 2]: Practitioners find it very difficult to intellectualize.

01:41:49.280 --> 01:41:55.440
[Guest 1]: Just to add to what Ajay is saying, they also don't think about in a very dynamic way and

01:41:55.440 --> 01:42:02.580
[Guest 1]: accounting for innovation in particular, right? For them, every technology is improving 5%

01:42:02.580 --> 01:42:07.440
[Guest 1]: in productivity in each successive plan, right? That's a really important part. The reason

01:42:07.440 --> 01:42:12.680
[Guest 1]: why they don't imagine that the world is going to change that drastically 10 years from now

01:42:12.680 --> 01:42:16.800
[Guest 1]: is every year you're only going to make marginal improvements in productivity. So you're never

01:42:16.800 --> 01:42:21.680
[Guest 1]: going to get like a great phone or you're never going to get a breakthrough like an

01:42:21.680 --> 01:42:27.000
[Guest 1]: mRNA vaccine, right? Which is genuinely a game changer in how we do anything after that

01:42:27.000 --> 01:42:31.920
[Guest 1]: in terms of, you know, how little it costs to do things. So they don't think in terms

01:42:31.920 --> 01:42:36.740
[Guest 1]: of Zoom or, you know, technology like that, where we're recording right now as a genuine

01:42:36.740 --> 01:42:41.040
[Guest 1]: substitute for airline tickets for us to meet and do this in person, right? Those are just

01:42:41.040 --> 01:42:45.200
[Guest 1]: things that don't occur to the bureaucratic mind, which do occur to the ordinary mind

01:42:45.200 --> 01:42:50.640
[Guest 1]: and the entrepreneurial mind. So the problem is even worse in one sense than what Ajay

01:42:50.640 --> 01:42:56.040
[Guest 1]: is saying. It's that not only do they not do it, I don't think they can do it because

01:42:56.040 --> 01:43:00.280
[Guest 1]: their spreadsheets can't account for anything more than a marginal change in technology.

01:43:00.280 --> 01:43:05.960
[Guest 1]: They can't say, oh, I imagine like Martin Luther King, I have a dream that we're going

01:43:05.960 --> 01:43:09.440
[Guest 1]: to have this productivity breakthrough in 10 years. It can't be done.

01:43:09.440 --> 01:43:13.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think what Ajay said reminded me of, you know, that thing they say about futurists

01:43:13.720 --> 01:43:18.920
[Amit Varma]: and I say about creators in the modern creator economy, that, you know, we tend to overestimate

01:43:18.920 --> 01:43:22.000
[Amit Varma]: the short term and underestimate the long term. And I think that's something to watch

01:43:22.000 --> 01:43:26.880
[Amit Varma]: out for. And I'll talk about a framework that I find really fits this very well. But before

01:43:26.880 --> 01:43:31.080
[Amit Varma]: we do that, for my listeners, you mentioned bootleggers and Baptists. So I should clarify

01:43:31.080 --> 01:43:36.040
[Amit Varma]: for my listeners what exactly that is. Bootleggers and Baptists is a phrase coined by Bruce Sandel,

01:43:36.040 --> 01:43:41.640
[Amit Varma]: a regulatory economist. And the whole idea is, you know, if you take the example of prohibition,

01:43:41.640 --> 01:43:46.040
[Amit Varma]: a Baptist will preach that, you know, alcohol is a bad thing, it should be banned. And the

01:43:46.040 --> 01:43:50.400
[Amit Varma]: moment a ban is in place, a bootlegger will make lots of money. So typically Baptists

01:43:50.400 --> 01:43:55.000
[Amit Varma]: and bootleggers go hand in hand. And this is just something that is natural. In fact,

01:43:55.000 --> 01:43:59.560
[Amit Varma]: I had once written a film review of the Shah Rukh Khan film Raees, where one of my main

01:43:59.560 --> 01:44:00.560
[Guest 1]: criticisms was that...

01:44:00.560 --> 01:44:04.960
[Guest 1]: There's a problem with that movie. Because they don't get together.

01:44:04.960 --> 01:44:10.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly. So that was my criticism. Now, here's a framework that I quickly want to

01:44:10.680 --> 01:44:15.440
[Amit Varma]: talk about, which I think is moves on from what Ajay was talking about and is also valid

01:44:15.440 --> 01:44:20.520
[Amit Varma]: to how we think of the economy in general. And this is something I got from William Easterly,

01:44:20.520 --> 01:44:24.320
[Amit Varma]: who's written a bunch of great books, such as The White Man's Burden and The Tyranny

01:44:24.320 --> 01:44:30.000
[Amit Varma]: of Experts. And his framework is where he talks about searchers and planners. And he

01:44:30.000 --> 01:44:34.640
[Amit Varma]: writes in a 2006 paper, which I'll link from the show notes, he wrote, quote, historically

01:44:34.640 --> 01:44:39.920
[Amit Varma]: poverty has never been ended by central planners. It is only ended by searchers, both economic

01:44:39.920 --> 01:44:44.360
[Amit Varma]: and political, who explore solutions by trial and error, have a way to get feedback on the

01:44:44.360 --> 01:44:49.000
[Amit Varma]: ones that work and then expand the ones that work. All of this in an unplanned, spontaneous

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:55.160
[Amit Varma]: way. Examples of searchers are firms in private markets and democratically accountable politicians.

01:44:55.160 --> 01:44:59.120
[Amit Varma]: A planner thinks he already knows the answers. He thinks of poverty as a technical engineering

01:44:59.120 --> 01:45:04.560
[Amit Varma]: problem that his answers will solve. A searcher admits he doesn't know the answers in advance

01:45:04.560 --> 01:45:09.640
[Amit Varma]: – he believes that poverty is a complicated tangle of political, social, historical, institutional

01:45:09.640 --> 01:45:14.400
[Amit Varma]: and technological factors. A searcher only hopes to find answers to individual problems

01:45:14.400 --> 01:45:19.680
[Amit Varma]: by trial and error experimentation. A planner believes outsiders know enough to impose solutions.

01:45:19.680 --> 01:45:24.320
[Amit Varma]: A searcher believes only insiders have enough knowledge to find solutions, and that most

01:45:24.320 --> 01:45:28.200
[Amit Varma]: solutions must be homegrown. Stop quote. And which brings you to the power of local knowledge

01:45:28.200 --> 01:45:32.880
[Amit Varma]: in markets and local government and so on. But at one point, and this is where I want

01:45:32.880 --> 01:45:37.280
[Amit Varma]: to sort of come at my next question for you guys. At one point, Easterly says, quote,

01:45:37.280 --> 01:45:41.920
[Amit Varma]: the planners have the rhetorical advantage of promising great things, the end of poverty.

01:45:41.920 --> 01:45:45.920
[Amit Varma]: The only thing the planners have against them is that plans don't work to help the world's

01:45:45.920 --> 01:45:49.200
[Amit Varma]: poor. Poor people die not only because of the world's indifference to the poverty, but

01:45:49.200 --> 01:45:54.080
[Amit Varma]: also because of ineffective efforts on behalf of those who do care. To escape the cycle

01:45:54.080 --> 01:45:58.800
[Amit Varma]: of tragedy, we have to be tough on the ideas of the planners, even while we salute their

01:45:58.800 --> 01:46:05.320
[Amit Varma]: goodwill. Stop quote. And it seems to me that here is sort of a key narrative problem. Like

01:46:05.320 --> 01:46:10.800
[Amit Varma]: earlier Ajay, you spoke about how we should think of oppression as a default of people

01:46:10.800 --> 01:46:15.160
[Amit Varma]: accumulating more and more power as a default and freedom as something we have to fight

01:46:15.160 --> 01:46:19.880
[Amit Varma]: for something that requires eternal vigilance as Jefferson put it. So that is one thing

01:46:19.880 --> 01:46:23.840
[Amit Varma]: that's the nature of institutions that the moment you give power, power corrupts, and

01:46:23.840 --> 01:46:30.040
[Amit Varma]: then it tends to expand. But the other reason that freedom is always got to fight is that

01:46:30.040 --> 01:46:34.920
[Amit Varma]: all of these narratives are very appealing. You know, when Indira Gandhi wins an election

01:46:34.920 --> 01:46:39.920
[Amit Varma]: on the basis of gareebi hatao, even though all of our policies are actually hurting the

01:46:39.920 --> 01:46:47.040
[Amit Varma]: poor, perpetuating poverty, that also kind of becomes a difficult fight to tackle. So

01:46:47.040 --> 01:46:51.600
[Amit Varma]: sort of dual questions, I guess that, what do you think of this framework? And is there

01:46:51.600 --> 01:46:57.680
[Amit Varma]: something to that, that narrative battle is a real one to fight, otherwise we slip back?

01:46:57.680 --> 01:47:04.080
[Guest 2]: It is a huge issue in human affairs. It's not efficient for most people to think for

01:47:04.080 --> 01:47:10.560
[Guest 2]: more than 10 minutes before voting. So there will always be an information problem. As

01:47:10.560 --> 01:47:15.840
[Guest 2]: Kelkar and I say in the book, most people know more about a motorcycle that they will

01:47:15.840 --> 01:47:21.800
[Guest 2]: buy as compared to knowing about the GST because they couldn't care less about what happens

01:47:21.800 --> 01:47:28.000
[Guest 2]: or what goes wrong with the GST. So I think of human societies as going through long,

01:47:28.000 --> 01:47:32.400
[Guest 2]: slow processes of waking up to figure out that something doesn't work. You know, that

01:47:32.400 --> 01:47:35.800
[Guest 2]: the worst thing that you can do for a nation is nationalism. The worst thing you can do

01:47:35.800 --> 01:47:43.240
[Guest 2]: for a society is socialism, even though these things sound like very nice labels. So unfortunately,

01:47:43.240 --> 01:47:47.240
[Guest 2]: you know, men and nations will do the right thing after trying every reasonable alternative.

01:47:47.240 --> 01:47:51.560
[Guest 2]: And it really takes a certain kind of shock therapy to wake up and realize that, oh my

01:47:51.560 --> 01:47:58.240
[Guest 2]: God, this really didn't work. If you look back, you needed the second world war to get

01:47:58.240 --> 01:48:05.320
[Guest 2]: a lot of sensible people away from the ideology of control, ideology of state domination.

01:48:05.320 --> 01:48:09.800
[Guest 2]: Without that, you know, Germany and Japan would not be as perfect and as amazing as

01:48:09.800 --> 01:48:14.440
[Guest 2]: they are today. In similar fashion, you know, you needed the murder of Gandhiji to wake

01:48:14.440 --> 01:48:19.360
[Guest 2]: up the people of India and, you know, get India going for 50 years in a certain direction

01:48:19.360 --> 01:48:25.920
[Guest 2]: and so on. So it is these things that make us learn. Unfortunately, most of us don't

01:48:25.920 --> 01:48:31.960
[Guest 2]: learn readily and it's a very slow process and seductive, catchy phrases go a long way.

01:48:31.960 --> 01:48:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And in fact, public choice theorists have a phrase for that rational ignorance

01:48:37.640 --> 01:48:41.960
[Amit Varma]: that for any one voter, it is simply not rational to spend too much time figuring out who to

01:48:41.960 --> 01:48:46.400
[Amit Varma]: vote for, because the chance of your one vote making a difference is very minuscule. Though

01:48:46.400 --> 01:48:50.600
[Amit Varma]: there was apparently a local election, I think somewhere in the North UP or Rajasthan, which

01:48:50.600 --> 01:48:55.720
[Amit Varma]: was lost by a guy with exactly one vote whose family didn't vote, you know, wouldn't have

01:48:55.720 --> 01:48:58.280
[Amit Varma]: made for the best dinner table conversation.

01:48:58.280 --> 01:49:03.240
[Amit Varma]: Main toh aapke liye ghar pe khana pakha rahi thi. Nahi, woh booth pe kyu nahi gayi.

01:49:03.240 --> 01:49:08.840
[Amit Varma]: Nauroji won his MP seat by five votes. Yeah, back in the day where the world population

01:49:08.840 --> 01:49:14.240
[Amit Varma]: was 40 people. Yeah, it's different. No, and I'd say to add to rational ignorance, you

01:49:14.240 --> 01:49:18.280
[Amit Varma]: know, I think the term rational apathy also works. Because, you know, we speak about how

01:49:18.280 --> 01:49:22.400
[Amit Varma]: voters are so apathetic all the time. But I'd say that that apathy is also rational

01:49:22.400 --> 01:49:27.000
[Amit Varma]: that man, I gotta get on with my life. It is safe for me to assume that nothing I do

01:49:27.000 --> 01:49:30.800
[Amit Varma]: or say in the public domain will make a difference to the world, or will make a difference to

01:49:30.800 --> 01:49:34.240
[Amit Varma]: governance or to society. So to hell with it, I'll just get on with my life.

01:49:34.240 --> 01:49:42.120
[Guest 2]: So can I take this as a prop to ponder some of the developments that gave us 1991? Okay,

01:49:42.120 --> 01:49:50.440
[Guest 2]: so we as a country were sinking into bad rates of growth. And there was just one long period

01:49:50.440 --> 01:49:56.720
[Guest 2]: of absolutely horrible things that were happening. Okay, so let's just go back. In 1962, Nehru

01:49:56.720 --> 01:50:02.280
[Guest 2]: died. Sorry, in 1962, we have the China war. In 1964, Nehru died. In 1965, we had another

01:50:02.280 --> 01:50:12.720
[Guest 2]: war and Shastri died. In 1969, Indira Gandhi nationalized banks. In early 1971, she won

01:50:12.720 --> 01:50:19.280
[Guest 2]: elections on the platform of Gareebi Hatao. In late 1971, we had a winning war, but one

01:50:19.280 --> 01:50:28.080
[Guest 2]: that involved tremendous demands upon resources. And then by 74, 75, the economy was down in

01:50:28.080 --> 01:50:33.920
[Guest 2]: the dumps and the country was burning with the various agitations all over the place.

01:50:33.920 --> 01:50:39.620
[Guest 2]: And then we got to 1976, that was the emergency. It was just one terrible long period. I wish

01:50:39.620 --> 01:50:45.720
[Guest 2]: to say to everybody who's gloomy in India today, that this gloomy period ran from 1962

01:50:45.720 --> 01:50:55.000
[Guest 2]: to 1977. Okay, so 15 years of bad times happens. Okay, so you've got to rescale your fortitude

01:50:55.000 --> 01:51:00.520
[Guest 2]: and be willing to live through bad times and bad times don't have to be short. It can be

01:51:00.520 --> 01:51:06.960
[Guest 2]: pretty long and they can be pretty disastrous. What was going on in the minds of the elite?

01:51:06.960 --> 01:51:13.720
[Guest 2]: And how did the elite consensus shift? It's not voters, really, who woke up and started

01:51:13.720 --> 01:51:19.880
[Guest 2]: saying that Indian socialism is not working. It was an elite led project, where more and

01:51:19.880 --> 01:51:23.680
[Guest 2]: more thinking people started waking up and saying, you know, this ain't working. So,

01:51:23.680 --> 01:51:27.960
[Guest 2]: I consider one of the most important pioneers in this field to be Arun Shourie, who was

01:51:27.960 --> 01:51:34.760
[Guest 2]: writing fundamental homegrown wisdom in the EPW about how the license permit Raj is generating

01:51:34.760 --> 01:51:40.320
[Guest 2]: terrible incentives. It was just an observation of my own backyard, you know, all science

01:51:40.320 --> 01:51:46.440
[Guest 2]: at its best is I turn around in my backyard and I describe the phenomena that I see. And

01:51:46.440 --> 01:51:51.280
[Guest 2]: that was Arun Shourie by the mid 60s. There were people waking up and saying that, look

01:51:51.280 --> 01:51:55.720
[Guest 2]: at East Asia, they are getting their act together, they're learning to export, they're getting

01:51:55.720 --> 01:52:00.040
[Guest 2]: a kind of prosperity that we have not got in India. You don't need to be so pessimistic

01:52:00.040 --> 01:52:06.080
[Guest 2]: about exports. That was Manmohan Singh's PhD thesis, and so on. So, the challenge to the

01:52:06.080 --> 01:52:10.720
[Guest 2]: status quo came from people looking back at these 15 years and saying, you know, it's

01:52:10.720 --> 01:52:15.760
[Guest 2]: broken. And clearly, we could do better than this, both based on observation of what went

01:52:15.760 --> 01:52:22.800
[Guest 2]: wrong in India, and on the observation of other countries were faring better than India.

01:52:22.800 --> 01:52:28.000
[Guest 2]: There was an 81 IMF program, there was a 91 IMF program. And that was very humiliating

01:52:28.000 --> 01:52:32.920
[Guest 2]: for all the senior policymakers who took it personally, that this is my failure, that

01:52:32.920 --> 01:52:37.760
[Guest 2]: we failed. And so, we had to go to the IMF and the World Bank with a begging bowl, and

01:52:37.760 --> 01:52:44.440
[Guest 2]: take loans and aid in order to tide over these situations. And one last element I would add

01:52:44.440 --> 01:52:49.800
[Guest 2]: to that was the fall of the USSR. It also changed the geopolitical configuration of

01:52:49.800 --> 01:52:55.280
[Guest 2]: the world. So, in 1971, when Indira Gandhi went to war in Bangladesh, she made India

01:52:55.280 --> 01:53:00.720
[Guest 2]: more cozy with the USSR than ever before, with the Friendship Treaty. And when there

01:53:00.720 --> 01:53:06.200
[Guest 2]: was a fall of the USSR in 1989, folks like Narasimha Rao clearly understood that the

01:53:06.200 --> 01:53:11.640
[Guest 2]: world had changed, and we needed to find a new place in this world. And this was one

01:53:11.640 --> 01:53:17.160
[Guest 2]: more element of the understanding, not just an economic understanding. Of course, there

01:53:17.160 --> 01:53:22.040
[Guest 2]: was an economic understanding that the great proponent of socialism had collapsed, but

01:53:22.040 --> 01:53:27.720
[Guest 2]: also that we in India now needed to find our way in a difficult world, where we did not

01:53:27.720 --> 01:53:32.240
[Guest 2]: have friends in the form of the USSR. And so, now what were we going to do? And it reiterated

01:53:32.240 --> 01:53:36.160
[Guest 2]: the importance that we had to become strong economically, otherwise, there were going

01:53:36.160 --> 01:53:41.640
[Guest 2]: to be dreadful consequences. So, I think of this as the theory of change that brought

01:53:41.640 --> 01:53:52.560
[Guest 2]: us through the market orientation from 1977 to 1991, as opposed to the stagnation and

01:53:52.560 --> 01:53:57.920
[Guest 2]: the mistakes of 1962 to 1977.

01:53:57.920 --> 01:54:06.040
[Guest 1]: I would add a few more things to this, if I may. I very much agree with Ajay. I would

01:54:06.040 --> 01:54:13.880
[Guest 1]: say that I think some of the unsung heroes of this time are some very senior bureaucrats

01:54:13.880 --> 01:54:19.760
[Guest 1]: and technocrats, right? And these people are not necessarily like, you know, free market

01:54:19.760 --> 01:54:27.800
[Guest 1]: people, right? A lot of the reforms for socialism came from people who were fundamentally socialist

01:54:27.800 --> 01:54:32.480
[Guest 1]: and who said, hey, the system's not working very well, right? Industrial licensing, we

01:54:32.480 --> 01:54:36.440
[Guest 1]: set it up with a particular goal in mind, and it's not working the way we think it should

01:54:36.440 --> 01:54:41.880
[Guest 1]: be working. So, something needs to change for us to meet our goal. So, they saw this

01:54:41.880 --> 01:54:47.040
[Guest 1]: huge like, sort of, it was very incongruent, you know, the means they were using and the

01:54:47.040 --> 01:54:52.880
[Guest 1]: ends that they intended. I think that's a really important part. So, one tradition we

01:54:52.880 --> 01:55:01.200
[Guest 1]: have lost in India is very good expert committee reports and very high quality, you know, parliamentary,

01:55:01.200 --> 01:55:05.760
[Guest 1]: you know, bipartisan or multi-partisan standing committee reports and things like that. This

01:55:05.760 --> 01:55:12.700
[Guest 1]: is a tradition which was, I mean, when you called a parliamentary committee, it was always

01:55:12.700 --> 01:55:17.360
[Guest 1]: given to the best people. It was typically not a cronyist event. Now, they always had

01:55:17.360 --> 01:55:21.520
[Guest 1]: the option of ignoring the committee report, right? So, they never tried to rig it or,

01:55:21.520 --> 01:55:25.320
[Guest 1]: you know, the tendencies were not what they are today, which is either you don't call

01:55:25.320 --> 01:55:30.000
[Guest 1]: the committee or you just kind of undermine it before it begins. So, I think some of those

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:35.200
[Guest 1]: committee reports from that time are still relevant, you know. So, that's one thing I

01:55:35.200 --> 01:55:39.000
[Guest 1]: want to highlight, that there are some of these unsung heroes, we don't know their names.

01:55:39.000 --> 01:55:43.760
[Guest 1]: So, you know, I mean, we know the names of, you know, for instance, like Abid Hussain

01:55:43.760 --> 01:55:48.560
[Guest 1]: committee on like trade reforms in the early 80s or something like that. So, we know the

01:55:48.560 --> 01:55:51.920
[Guest 1]: person who led the committee, but there were a lot of people doing good work like this.

01:55:51.920 --> 01:55:58.840
[Guest 1]: That's one. The second is there is also a lot of historical accidents here. You know,

01:55:58.840 --> 01:56:02.680
[Guest 1]: it's not clear to me that Indira Gandhi, I mean, she's very socialist. So, don't get

01:56:02.680 --> 01:56:07.320
[Guest 1]: me wrong. I'm not saying that she's not socialist, but I don't think she came in with the same

01:56:07.320 --> 01:56:13.760
[Guest 1]: commitment to socialism like say Nehru did. Okay. Her commitment to socialism is a little

01:56:13.760 --> 01:56:18.680
[Guest 1]: bit more accidental, and it's also the consequence of a power struggle that happens within India.

01:56:18.680 --> 01:56:24.260
[Guest 1]: So, if you look at what happened in 1966, right, India had to undergo a devaluation.

01:56:24.260 --> 01:56:30.440
[Guest 1]: It had a very similar foreign exchange currency crisis at the time. IMF and, you know, World

01:56:30.440 --> 01:56:35.400
[Guest 1]: Bank, basically the Washington consensus before it was even called the Washington consensus,

01:56:35.400 --> 01:56:38.520
[Guest 1]: came up with the prescription. They said, we'll give you the loan. You need to devalue.

01:56:38.520 --> 01:56:43.720
[Guest 1]: You need to do like, you know, this laundry list of things. But a few things happen simultaneously.

01:56:43.720 --> 01:56:49.680
[Guest 1]: One is there were two moments of a break within the Congress party, right? And the people

01:56:49.680 --> 01:56:54.840
[Guest 1]: who were against Indira Gandhi were the more liberal minded, reform minded politicians,

01:56:54.840 --> 01:56:58.400
[Guest 1]: right? And she wanted to split from them because she was the one who wanted to be in power.

01:56:58.400 --> 01:57:03.520
[Guest 1]: So, this is the split with the syndicate in Congress, right? And it just so happens that

01:57:03.520 --> 01:57:07.920
[Guest 1]: she was against the liberal side, so she became more socialist. That's one part of it.

01:57:07.920 --> 01:57:13.880
[Guest 1]: The second part of it is interpersonal relationships, right? Like the way the, you know, Lyndon

01:57:13.880 --> 01:57:20.840
[Guest 1]: Johnson administration behaves by making India beg for PL480, you know, each week shipment

01:57:20.840 --> 01:57:25.560
[Guest 1]: when India is going through a terrific shortage is going to come one at a time and it needs

01:57:25.560 --> 01:57:29.840
[Guest 1]: to like, you need to beg and then it'll be approved as opposed to just opening arms and

01:57:29.840 --> 01:57:35.720
[Guest 1]: giving aid to a country which is clearly struggling in, you know, a moment of crisis. Now, these

01:57:35.720 --> 01:57:41.560
[Guest 1]: things make them very suspicious of America, once again. Now, in 66, Anne Kruger has a

01:57:41.560 --> 01:57:46.280
[Guest 1]: great quote, it's a long one, so I'm not going to read it out. But she kind of, you know,

01:57:46.280 --> 01:57:51.400
[Guest 1]: tries to think of a counterfactual that in 66, if India had done what IMF had suggested

01:57:51.400 --> 01:57:55.760
[Guest 1]: and Indira Gandhi had gone the South Korea way, like where would India be today, right?

01:57:55.760 --> 01:57:59.880
[Guest 1]: Like, look at South Korea's economy today. It's a developed country. And when South Korea

01:57:59.880 --> 01:58:05.560
[Guest 1]: started in the 1950s, it was like equivalent to what Syria or Yemen is today, right? It

01:58:05.560 --> 01:58:10.320
[Guest 1]: was torn by civil war. It's the third poorest economy in the world. And a matter of 15,

01:58:10.320 --> 01:58:15.440
[Guest 1]: 20 years, they kind of just, you know, escaped out of that poverty trap. So Anne Kruger talks

01:58:15.440 --> 01:58:21.920
[Guest 1]: about how 1966 may or could have been a moment and what if it had been that moment. So there

01:58:21.920 --> 01:58:29.080
[Guest 1]: is a bunch of historical accidents and there is some internal churn going on by well-meaning

01:58:29.080 --> 01:58:34.120
[Guest 1]: economists and technocrats, many of whom are actually dealing with the IMF at this time

01:58:34.120 --> 01:58:39.320
[Guest 1]: and they recognize the kind of failures of their policy. And when you come to the 1980s,

01:58:39.320 --> 01:58:46.600
[Guest 1]: about 10 to 12 years before the reform period that, you know, that as Ajay mentioned, there

01:58:46.600 --> 01:58:53.680
[Guest 1]: is a series of really good reports. Okay. And the reports matter for two reasons. One,

01:58:53.680 --> 01:58:57.240
[Guest 1]: they are coming from an elite perspective and we know the collective action problems

01:58:57.240 --> 01:59:01.920
[Guest 1]: of voters getting together to defeat one ideology versus another ideology. I don't think the

01:59:01.920 --> 01:59:06.960
[Guest 1]: voters have still managed to do that, you know, even 30 years after liberalization.

01:59:06.960 --> 01:59:13.040
[Guest 1]: But the second part is these elites have buy-in within the government. They are part of the

01:59:13.040 --> 01:59:18.640
[Guest 1]: state machinery. It's very different than Shruti Rajgopalan, Ajay Shah and Amit Verma

01:59:18.640 --> 01:59:24.640
[Guest 1]: talking over a podcast about MRTP being bad, right? There is a difference when there is

01:59:24.640 --> 01:59:31.520
[Guest 1]: actually a Sachar committee report on MRTP, right? And that report from the inside examines

01:59:31.520 --> 01:59:36.800
[Guest 1]: it. They understand what is going on. They understand how to write the recommendations

01:59:36.800 --> 01:59:42.000
[Guest 1]: in a way that they have buy-in within the community that they are involved in and how

01:59:42.000 --> 01:59:48.000
[Guest 1]: to make these things go through. Now, of course, this happens in 1979, early 80s. MRTP doesn't,

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:53.120
[Guest 1]: you know, get reformed until the early 2000s. So there's a long time period. But as Ajay

01:59:53.120 --> 01:59:58.960
[Guest 1]: said, 15 years, 20 years for these kinds of elite-led reforms is not that long a period

01:59:58.960 --> 02:00:04.480
[Guest 1]: of time. It takes that long for ideas to come in and for them to take root and, you know,

02:00:04.480 --> 02:00:11.680
[Guest 1]: things like that. And the third is, here I have a bit of an issue with my own community,

02:00:11.680 --> 02:00:17.360
[Guest 1]: which is that of professional economists, right? If you think about the 70s, you know,

02:00:17.360 --> 02:00:22.320
[Guest 1]: once the Korean miracle has happened, by the 70s, I mean, early 70s, you have Bhagwati

02:00:22.320 --> 02:00:26.800
[Guest 1]: and Padma Desai have written their book on how industrial licensing and, you know, the

02:00:26.800 --> 02:00:33.120
[Guest 1]: entire industrial planning system is simply not working. By the mid to late 70s, you have

02:00:33.120 --> 02:00:37.520
[Guest 1]: TN Srinivasan, you have Jagdish Bhagwati. I mean, Jagdish Bhagwati is at MIT, TN Srinivasan

02:00:37.520 --> 02:00:44.800
[Guest 1]: is at Yale. These are elite economists at top institutions. And when they have a position

02:00:44.800 --> 02:00:51.440
[Guest 1]: on economic development in Asia, it matters, okay? Look at what today's development economists

02:00:51.440 --> 02:00:56.320
[Guest 1]: are doing, right? I mean, they're very credible. They're excellent people. But today's development

02:00:56.320 --> 02:01:03.200
[Guest 1]: economists are not talking about trade as the route to prosperity, right? Today's development

02:01:03.200 --> 02:01:08.320
[Guest 1]: economists are tinkering social protection programs. If we tinker a little bit and pull

02:01:08.320 --> 02:01:13.840
[Guest 1]: this liver and give a sari instead of 200 rupees or have a timestamp instead of this

02:01:13.840 --> 02:01:20.080
[Guest 1]: other mechanism, what are we going to get, right? So there has also been a really big

02:01:20.080 --> 02:01:26.800
[Guest 1]: problem within the elite economics community. There is a crisis where development economics

02:01:26.800 --> 02:01:31.840
[Guest 1]: has become a field in its own. I don't even know sometimes what it means, but the engines

02:01:31.840 --> 02:01:37.280
[Guest 1]: of growth, which is, you know, strong macro monetary policy or trade policy, these things

02:01:37.280 --> 02:01:42.560
[Guest 1]: are now just taken for granted. It's not fashionable to work on these things anymore. I can't remember

02:01:42.560 --> 02:01:48.720
[Guest 1]: the last time I read something new, which was not like a journal of economics perspectives piece

02:01:48.720 --> 02:01:54.400
[Guest 1]: that was really good on free trade as the engine of growth or like endogenous growth

02:01:54.400 --> 02:01:59.360
[Guest 1]: theory or innovation specifically applied to developing economies or sub-Saharan Africa

02:01:59.360 --> 02:02:05.120
[Guest 1]: or something like that. That work is not existing, right? Which means the next generation of economists

02:02:05.120 --> 02:02:10.080
[Guest 1]: who are trained are going to be doing something a little bit different. And it does matter.

02:02:10.080 --> 02:02:15.920
[Guest 1]: And it matters not because of what Modi is going to do tomorrow, but it matters 15 years from now,

02:02:15.920 --> 02:02:22.240
[Guest 1]: who is going to dig us out of this grave when the opportune moment comes, right? Who is that

02:02:22.240 --> 02:02:28.480
[Guest 1]: Sachar committee report going to be written by in 2034? Those people need to exist and they need

02:02:28.480 --> 02:02:34.400
[Guest 1]: to be trained and they need to be influenced by an economics elite. That actually depresses me

02:02:34.400 --> 02:02:41.440
[Guest 1]: more than virtually anything else that we're seeing right now. If I may just continue on the

02:02:41.440 --> 02:02:48.000
[Guest 2]: sociology of the economics profession, Shruti, as you know well, Jagdish Bhagwati and T. N. Srinivasan

02:02:48.000 --> 02:02:53.520
[Guest 2]: started out at the Delhi School of Economics. And so I actually claimed them as Indian economists

02:02:53.520 --> 02:03:02.320
[Guest 1]: and not as MIT or Yale economists. No, they're Indian economists, but they get the world stage

02:03:02.320 --> 02:03:07.680
[Guest 1]: and they're talking about India at a global platform with a certain amount of credibility,

02:03:07.680 --> 02:03:13.280
[Guest 1]: which really makes a difference even for the Indians listening to them. The Indians are

02:03:13.280 --> 02:03:16.960
[Guest 1]: more likely to listen to T. N. Srinivasan and Bhagwati when they come from MIT.

02:03:16.960 --> 02:03:20.880
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I'd just like to emphasize, they picked their knowledge here out of observation of their

02:03:20.880 --> 02:03:27.600
[Guest 2]: backyard. So it was in the great traditions, as I said earlier, that, you know, George Akerlof

02:03:27.600 --> 02:03:35.120
[Guest 2]: went out walking from ISI Delhi and saw people selling vegetables and invented the lemons model.

02:03:35.120 --> 02:03:41.760
[Guest 2]: And so observation is the key being immersed authentically in that reality is what gave

02:03:41.760 --> 02:03:49.040
[Guest 2]: Jagdish Bhagwati and T. N. Srinivasan the novel insights that they had. Turning to the Indian

02:03:49.040 --> 02:03:54.880
[Guest 2]: landscape of that period, I felt there is an interesting distinction between a Delhi community

02:03:54.880 --> 02:04:00.640
[Guest 2]: and a Bombay community of that period. The Delhi community was very much part of Nehru's

02:04:00.640 --> 02:04:06.800
[Guest 2]: central planning of the idea that the economists had access to some unique knowledge and the

02:04:06.800 --> 02:04:16.240
[Guest 2]: ability to plan. So the economists cast themselves as social engineers, what might today be

02:04:16.240 --> 02:04:22.080
[Guest 2]: fashionable for the computer technologists to call platform designers, that they will design society.

02:04:22.080 --> 02:04:27.440
[Guest 2]: So those kinds of things were the flavor, the nature of the Delhi community. Whereas

02:04:28.160 --> 02:04:35.120
[Guest 2]: in Bombay, it seems to me that there was a greater nurturing of an economics that A.

02:04:35.120 --> 02:04:41.680
[Guest 2]: did not involve the key protagonists possessing any power. So they were more academic economists

02:04:41.680 --> 02:04:47.040
[Guest 2]: rather than going and running some central planning operation or the other and being

02:04:47.040 --> 02:04:52.480
[Guest 2]: closer to the private sector and seeing private sector dynamism and capabilities and

02:04:53.120 --> 02:05:00.160
[Guest 2]: internationalization and so on. And it seems to me that there is a very interesting moment in 1977

02:05:00.800 --> 02:05:07.600
[Guest 2]: where Morarji Desai became prime minister and H. M. Patel became the finance minister

02:05:07.600 --> 02:05:14.000
[Guest 2]: and D. T. Lakdawala became the deputy chairman of the planning commission. And these three people

02:05:14.000 --> 02:05:19.280
[Guest 2]: brought in a different ideology, a different framework. It was a lot of gnashing of teeth

02:05:19.280 --> 02:05:24.800
[Guest 2]: and biting of nails on the part of some of the Delhi establishment because these were not

02:05:24.800 --> 02:05:30.400
[Guest 2]: the cool kids who were spinning planning models. But then that was the point. That was how we

02:05:30.400 --> 02:05:36.800
[Guest 2]: started bringing new ideas to bear as compared to the old establishment, which was this mixture of

02:05:36.800 --> 02:05:41.840
[Guest 2]: poverty and redistribution and mistrust of markets and central planning.

02:05:43.040 --> 02:05:51.680
[Guest 1]: And one last addition to this Delhi-Bombay thing, there is also a majority of the pushback is

02:05:51.680 --> 02:05:57.200
[Guest 1]: coming from, you know, the Forum for Free Enterprise, right? I mean, Ajay mentioned Arun

02:05:57.200 --> 02:06:03.120
[Guest 1]: Shourie. Rajaji fortnightly writes about the stupidity of price controls and the Essential

02:06:03.120 --> 02:06:08.400
[Guest 1]: Commodities Act and like the license. He coined the term license permit raj and so on. You know,

02:06:08.400 --> 02:06:12.880
[Guest 1]: you have people like Masani and A. D. Shroff giving lectures. So there is there is a whole

02:06:12.880 --> 02:06:23.120
[Guest 1]: Bombay intellectual community, which is far less, you know, mistrustful of private enterprise and

02:06:23.120 --> 02:06:29.520
[Guest 1]: far more in line with, hey, what are the engines of growth and what are the unintended consequences?

02:06:29.520 --> 02:06:34.000
[Guest 1]: One person I want to mention here, who's like never thought of as an economist,

02:06:34.000 --> 02:06:39.840
[Guest 1]: but I think had great writings of that time is Nani Palkiwala, right? Palkiwala is like the first

02:06:39.840 --> 02:06:46.080
[Guest 1]: public finance, like sensible public finance thinker we have in India, because he started

02:06:46.080 --> 02:06:51.600
[Guest 1]: out as a tax lawyer and about talking about look at what the tax code is. And he came at it from

02:06:51.600 --> 02:06:56.640
[Guest 1]: two points of view, right, which are very valuable to the conversation we're having. One is, hey,

02:06:56.640 --> 02:07:00.880
[Guest 1]: this simply doesn't work, right? It has all these unintended consequences. They're terrible. And the

02:07:00.880 --> 02:07:06.400
[Guest 1]: second is the constitutional rule of law perspective, which is what kind of society can you

02:07:06.400 --> 02:07:11.760
[Guest 1]: have if your highest tax rates are 97 percent and you're going to end up making a criminal out of

02:07:11.760 --> 02:07:16.960
[Guest 1]: everybody because no reasonable person is going to be willing to part with 97 percent of the income

02:07:16.960 --> 02:07:21.520
[Guest 1]: that they've earned, you know, so on and so forth. And so he comes at it from a very interesting

02:07:21.520 --> 02:07:27.040
[Guest 1]: perspective. And Ajay is absolutely right that there is something very interesting going on in

02:07:27.040 --> 02:07:34.320
[Guest 1]: Bombay at that time, culturally, that there is this group of people who are not just writing

02:07:34.320 --> 02:07:38.880
[Guest 1]: about it, but they actively engage with the public, which is also something missing in Delhi,

02:07:38.880 --> 02:07:43.920
[Guest 1]: right? Delhi people are not doing these huge public lectures and they're not really trying

02:07:43.920 --> 02:07:49.680
[Guest 1]: to persuade people. It's a very insider game. We know how the game is played. We are technical

02:07:49.680 --> 02:07:53.600
[Guest 1]: economists. We know how the system works and we are going to make these clever plans and talk to

02:07:53.600 --> 02:07:59.760
[Guest 1]: each other about it at the IIC. And I think Bombay is just a fundamentally different culture

02:07:59.760 --> 02:08:03.120
[Guest 1]: intellectually, not just in terms of ideas, but also the dissemination.

02:08:05.120 --> 02:08:08.320
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you said there's something interesting going on in Bombay. These days,

02:08:08.320 --> 02:08:12.880
[Amit Varma]: the only interesting thing going on in Bombay is the seen and the unseen. We'll take a quick

02:08:12.880 --> 02:08:17.680
[Amit Varma]: commercial break now, but after which we'll talk directly about the 91 reforms. I did want to spend

02:08:17.680 --> 02:08:23.360
[Amit Varma]: some time doing the segue from the Nehru years to the Indira years because things became much worse.

02:08:23.360 --> 02:08:28.320
[Amit Varma]: But you've, you know, put a very interesting kind of nuance there, like one view of Indira,

02:08:28.320 --> 02:08:33.120
[Amit Varma]: which is essentially correct, is that economically she was a complete disaster. People speak of the

02:08:33.120 --> 02:08:37.600
[Amit Varma]: emergency, but I think a lot of what she did in terms of her economics, there were crimes on

02:08:37.600 --> 02:08:42.400
[Amit Varma]: humanity that perpetuated poverty and suffering throughout the country. But the interesting

02:08:42.400 --> 02:08:47.760
[Amit Varma]: nuance that you pointed out is that she wasn't a committed socialist necessarily. She went in

02:08:47.760 --> 02:08:52.320
[Amit Varma]: that direction because of political imperatives. She had to combat the syndicate within the

02:08:52.320 --> 02:08:56.800
[Amit Varma]: Congress Party as it were. And this was just a positioning game that she could, you know,

02:08:56.800 --> 02:09:01.600
[Amit Varma]: position herself as apart from them using this. And it also sold well, you know,

02:09:02.720 --> 02:09:08.080
[Amit Varma]: good intentions sell well. But at the same time, you know, it could have been reason for hope for

02:09:08.080 --> 02:09:12.480
[Amit Varma]: some had she lived, because maybe she had no convictions, maybe she was just a sociopath

02:09:12.480 --> 02:09:17.840
[Amit Varma]: will do whatever. Certainly her young son Sanjay was and of course, a lot of the way she behaved

02:09:17.840 --> 02:09:23.760
[Amit Varma]: came from those incentives ki bete ko khush karna hai. But you know, so we'll go directly to 91

02:09:23.760 --> 02:09:28.640
[Amit Varma]: after the break. But before that, I'll leave my listeners with a thought that Ajay when he was

02:09:28.640 --> 02:09:32.720
[Amit Varma]: speaking, he mentioned he spoke about the elites of that period who were on these committees and

02:09:32.720 --> 02:09:38.080
[Amit Varma]: who had access to, you know, to bureaucrats and to politicians and not just people sitting around

02:09:38.080 --> 02:09:42.720
[Amit Varma]: doing a podcast. And the thought struck me that imagine if I was to try and do a podcast in that

02:09:42.720 --> 02:09:47.840
[Amit Varma]: period, I would never get a license, right? Because first of all, the conception of my

02:09:47.840 --> 02:09:52.800
[Amit Varma]: podcast originally was very different 20 minute episodes, a lot of experimentation brought me

02:09:52.800 --> 02:09:57.520
[Amit Varma]: here, I would have had to apply for a license for the original conception, which would have taken

02:09:57.520 --> 02:10:01.920
[Amit Varma]: five years to come. And the experimentation would never have happened. And there would have been

02:10:01.920 --> 02:10:06.400
[Amit Varma]: monthly bribes I would have had to pay. The other thought I'll leave people with, which I've, you

02:10:06.400 --> 02:10:10.400
[Amit Varma]: know, mentioned sometimes in the context of agriculture, which was a one part of our economy,

02:10:10.400 --> 02:10:16.080
[Amit Varma]: which wasn't sort of reformed in 91, is that imagine that if writers had to go through an

02:10:16.080 --> 02:10:21.680
[Amit Varma]: APMC, so you're a writer, but you can't sell to any publication, but you know, according to sort

02:10:21.680 --> 02:10:26.320
[Amit Varma]: of mutual consultation that you know, this is you pay me this much, I'll give it to you for this

02:10:26.320 --> 02:10:32.080
[Amit Varma]: much blah, blah, you can't, you have to sell it to an APMC for writers, right, maybe a WPMC,

02:10:32.080 --> 02:10:37.040
[Amit Varma]: as it were, and they'll give you a fixed price. And then they have all the writing in front of

02:10:37.040 --> 02:10:42.640
[Amit Varma]: them. And they sell that on to publications and so on. So it would really be the equivalent of

02:10:42.640 --> 02:10:47.840
[Amit Varma]: you getting say 200 rupees for a piece, which they then sell on to the publication for 10,000 rupees.

02:10:47.840 --> 02:10:51.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's exactly what's been happening in agriculture for decades. Ajay and I have a great

02:10:51.920 --> 02:10:58.480
[Amit Varma]: episode on these recent farm laws. In fact, which is, I think one of my top 10 episodes. So

02:10:58.480 --> 02:11:03.360
[Amit Varma]: much lucidity and insight there, as they will be in this episode also after we come back from the

02:11:03.360 --> 02:11:11.040
[Amit Varma]: break. Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances are that many of you

02:11:11.040 --> 02:11:17.360
[Amit Varma]: first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut, which was active between 2003 and 2009 and became

02:11:17.360 --> 02:11:22.880
[Amit Varma]: somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the form gave me. And I feel I was shaped by it

02:11:22.880 --> 02:11:28.720
[Amit Varma]: in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced to think about many different

02:11:28.720 --> 02:11:33.120
[Amit Varma]: things because I wrote about many different things. Well, that phase in my life ended for

02:11:33.120 --> 02:11:38.960
[Amit Varma]: various reasons. And now it is time to revive it. Only now I'm doing it through a newsletter.

02:11:38.960 --> 02:11:45.120
[Amit Varma]: I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com where I will write

02:11:45.120 --> 02:11:49.840
[Amit Varma]: regularly about whatever catches my fancy. I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this

02:11:49.840 --> 02:11:56.720
[Amit Varma]: podcast and about much else. So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe.

02:11:56.720 --> 02:12:02.240
[Amit Varma]: It is free. Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox,

02:12:02.240 --> 02:12:07.600
[Amit Varma]: you don't need to go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The India Uncut newsletter

02:12:07.600 --> 02:12:13.840
[Amit Varma]: at indiancut.substack.com. Thank you. Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm

02:12:13.840 --> 02:12:19.920
[Amit Varma]: chatting with Ajay Shah and Shruti Rajgopalan on the importance of the 91 reforms. And finally,

02:12:19.920 --> 02:12:24.880
[Amit Varma]: after two hours of conversation and hopefully, delightful digressions, which you would have

02:12:24.880 --> 02:12:30.880
[Amit Varma]: found as interesting as I did, we have reached 1991 or not yet. Because people I think often

02:12:30.880 --> 02:12:35.920
[Amit Varma]: speak of 1991 as if it is this fixed moment in time where there was a quantum leap in events

02:12:35.920 --> 02:12:39.840
[Amit Varma]: and everything just changed. But actually, there was a gradual process as both of you pointed out

02:12:39.840 --> 02:12:46.240
[Amit Varma]: before the break, which was underway, you know what some economists have termed as liberalization

02:12:46.240 --> 02:12:52.000
[Amit Varma]: by stealth happening through the 1980s. So tell me a little bit about that. I mean, especially,

02:12:52.000 --> 02:12:56.960
[Amit Varma]: it's always fascinating to me to speak to you, Ajay, on all of this, because it almost seems

02:12:56.960 --> 02:13:00.640
[Amit Varma]: like you're discussing the French Revolution with someone who was actually there when people

02:13:00.640 --> 02:13:05.280
[Guest 1]: were getting beheaded and who knew Robespierre personally and all of that. He just called you old.

02:13:05.280 --> 02:13:11.200
[Amit Varma]: Because I didn't call him old. He's a, he's a statesman. His co author Vijay Kelkar was

02:13:11.200 --> 02:13:15.600
[Amit Varma]: part of some of these committees, I was just reading Rakesh Mohan's essays on, you know,

02:13:15.600 --> 02:13:20.400
[Amit Varma]: what went on behind the scenes at that time. And Mr. Kelkar was a part of that to some extent,

02:13:20.400 --> 02:13:25.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, so Ajay, so take me through a bit of that process in the decade past. Like when we

02:13:25.520 --> 02:13:31.680
[Amit Varma]: look back, it's easy to think of Indira as a socialist, sociopathic monster, which of course,

02:13:31.680 --> 02:13:36.000
[Amit Varma]: she was for a significant period of time. But there is also this narrative that at a certain

02:13:36.000 --> 02:13:41.920
[Amit Varma]: point in time in the late 70s and early 80s, even she was beginning to give in to reason and sense,

02:13:41.920 --> 02:13:47.360
[Amit Varma]: which was coming from others, you know, and so on with Rajiv Gandhi as well. And had Rajiv

02:13:47.360 --> 02:13:51.440
[Amit Varma]: actually lived, perhaps a liberalization would have happened anyway, because he was already

02:13:51.440 --> 02:13:56.880
[Amit Varma]: turning towards the conclusion that we needed all of this, regardless of the crisis that

02:13:56.880 --> 02:14:01.840
[Amit Varma]: eventually happened. So take me through the landscape. There's a really important break in

02:14:01.840 --> 02:14:10.640
[Guest 2]: this history in 1977, where, as I mentioned, Morarji Desai, H M Patel, and DT Lakhdawala

02:14:10.640 --> 02:14:15.680
[Guest 2]: became the three, the big three economic policy people of that period. In those days, the Deputy

02:14:15.680 --> 02:14:21.760
[Guest 2]: Chairman Planning Commission really mattered much more than is the case today. And it was a cautious

02:14:21.760 --> 02:14:30.160
[Guest 2]: process of liberalization. So, for example, instead of a tariff being 300%, it would be 200%.

02:14:30.800 --> 02:14:36.720
[Guest 2]: In the early 80s, it was the concept of broadbanding of industrial licenses, where instead

02:14:36.720 --> 02:14:42.320
[Guest 2]: of having a license to make a 20 minute podcast, they would say anybody who has a license to make

02:14:42.320 --> 02:14:48.000
[Guest 2]: a 20 minute podcast is automatically deemed permitted to make a podcast of any length

02:14:48.000 --> 02:14:53.600
[Guest 2]: between 10 minutes and 30 minutes. Okay, and that would be liberalization, because you suddenly got

02:14:53.600 --> 02:14:59.280
[Guest 2]: to move in an incremental way around your ecosystem and find something that made a little more sense.

02:14:59.840 --> 02:15:07.920
[Guest 2]: And these early steps in reform were actually successful rather quickly. If you do the

02:15:07.920 --> 02:15:16.240
[Guest 2]: econometrics of structural breaks in GDP growth, right there in 1979-80, we get a jump to 5.5%

02:15:16.240 --> 02:15:20.720
[Guest 2]: growth compared to the so called Hindu rate of growth of three and a half percent. So,

02:15:20.720 --> 02:15:28.640
[Guest 2]: fairly modest changes generated a decent impact on growth fairly early. There are two big features

02:15:28.640 --> 02:15:35.120
[Guest 2]: of that early period, which we in hindsight, would see as very different compared to what

02:15:35.120 --> 02:15:43.360
[Guest 2]: happened after 1991. The first was that it was very domestic centric, there was not a liberalization

02:15:43.360 --> 02:15:48.800
[Guest 2]: opening up to the outside world. So, it was like a pre-globalization phase of fixing up some of the

02:15:48.800 --> 02:15:54.320
[Guest 2]: domestic economy. And the second big feature of that period is very little was done on finance.

02:15:54.320 --> 02:16:00.320
[Guest 2]: It was all real sector focused, because can we get goods and services and raw materials to move a

02:16:00.320 --> 02:16:06.560
[Guest 2]: little better? My good friend, Vivek Bhatia, who used to be in business today, tells me of the

02:16:06.560 --> 02:16:13.520
[Guest 2]: time when he was a reporter. And in 1981, we got the decontrol of the price of steel and cement.

02:16:13.520 --> 02:16:18.320
[Guest 2]: And there was like a funeral atmosphere in the Ministry of Steel and Ministry of Cement. Okay,

02:16:18.320 --> 02:16:22.000
[Guest 2]: so did you know there was a Ministry of Cement or things like, I don't even remember what was

02:16:22.000 --> 02:16:26.560
[Guest 2]: the name of the department. But this sounds trivial that there should be no government

02:16:26.560 --> 02:16:33.360
[Guest 2]: involvement in the price of steel, there should be no government involvement in the price of cement.

02:16:33.360 --> 02:16:41.120
[Guest 2]: But at the time, it was a big deal. It was a very big deal. It was as strange as the few

02:16:41.120 --> 02:16:46.160
[Guest 2]: market-oriented economists in India today who get the idea that there is no role for government in

02:16:46.160 --> 02:16:50.880
[Guest 2]: the currency market. If you try to say in India today, that the exchange rate should move based

02:16:50.880 --> 02:16:55.840
[Guest 2]: on market forces, it would be a novel proposition for many people. In similar fashion, it might

02:16:55.840 --> 02:17:01.200
[Guest 2]: sound obvious today, but at the time, it was a big deal. And these were important liberalizations.

02:17:01.200 --> 02:17:08.640
[Guest 2]: I can't help tell a funny story of my family story. We moved into my present house in Bandra

02:17:08.640 --> 02:17:15.040
[Guest 2]: East in 1972. And that was, it was a cooperative housing society where in those days, the people

02:17:15.040 --> 02:17:18.800
[Guest 2]: who were members of the cooperative society had to do a lot of the heavy lifting to make the thing

02:17:18.800 --> 02:17:25.040
[Guest 2]: happen. And that was an age where there were shortages of cement. So, the thing got delayed

02:17:25.040 --> 02:17:32.080
[Guest 2]: for years and years in getting built until 1972 when we moved in. Because individuals had to just

02:17:32.080 --> 02:17:36.000
[Guest 2]: figure out that, oh, there's a little bit of cement here, so now let's scramble over and get

02:17:36.000 --> 02:17:40.080
[Guest 2]: that cement. And then the project would make some progress. And then again, it would grind to a halt

02:17:40.080 --> 02:17:44.800
[Guest 2]: because there was not enough cement. So, these seem like small things, but they are a very big

02:17:44.800 --> 02:17:50.800
[Guest 2]: deal that a government involvement in the price of cement or the price of steel is a huge distortion.

02:17:50.800 --> 02:17:57.360
[Guest 2]: And many of these incremental things were getting done. And as Shruti emphasized a moment ago with

02:17:57.360 --> 02:18:03.760
[Guest 2]: Nehru, there was a positive feedback process that Nehru and Mahalanobis scored a significant

02:18:03.760 --> 02:18:07.440
[Guest 2]: acceleration of Indian growth compared with pre-colonial times. In similar fashion,

02:18:08.320 --> 02:18:14.320
[Guest 2]: this community of the reformers gained confidence and earned respect and gained credibility because

02:18:14.320 --> 02:18:21.760
[Guest 2]: right there after 1977, in 1979-80, there was a structural break in GDP growth and growth

02:18:21.760 --> 02:18:29.360
[Guest 2]: accelerated to 5.5%. And so, this process was working its way through the 80s. And then we had

02:18:29.360 --> 02:18:36.160
[Guest 2]: a terrible mess in the late 80s where many things came together. There was domestic political

02:18:36.160 --> 02:18:42.240
[Guest 2]: difficulties that led to reckless fiscal policy, which spilled over into a large current account

02:18:42.240 --> 02:18:50.000
[Guest 2]: deficit. And then we had oil shocks after 1979. And those things came together and generated a

02:18:50.000 --> 02:18:55.600
[Guest 2]: balance of payments crisis at a time when the political conditions in the union government

02:18:55.600 --> 02:19:01.920
[Guest 2]: were completely broken. So, that gave us the big messy BOP crisis. Once again, to underline what

02:19:01.920 --> 02:19:07.520
[Guest 2]: Shruti was saying a moment ago about many people thinking about these things and rebuilding

02:19:07.520 --> 02:19:14.160
[Guest 2]: the policy framework, it is not widely known that the Chandrasekhar government with Yashwant

02:19:14.160 --> 02:19:19.600
[Guest 2]: Sinha as the finance minister had worked out a good chunk of a complex policy package that would

02:19:19.600 --> 02:19:26.720
[Guest 2]: be done that looks a lot like what was finally unveiled by Narasimha Rao and Manmohan Singh.

02:19:27.280 --> 02:19:32.880
[Guest 2]: But it didn't happen because that government collapsed. And then finally, we get to that

02:19:32.880 --> 02:19:40.960
[Guest 2]: epochal final moment where we had the absolute genius of folks like Narasimha Rao as prime

02:19:40.960 --> 02:19:47.040
[Guest 2]: minister, A.N. Varma in the prime minister's office, Chidambaram as commerce minister,

02:19:47.680 --> 02:19:52.000
[Guest 2]: Manmohan Singh as finance minister, Monte Kaluwalia as finance secretary. Earlier,

02:19:52.000 --> 02:19:57.760
[Guest 2]: he was the commerce secretary with Chidambaram and Ashok Desai as the chief economic advisor to

02:19:57.760 --> 02:20:03.280
[Guest 2]: Manmohan Singh. And all this came together and we just got a huge jump forward. And my

02:20:03.280 --> 02:20:09.520
[Guest 2]: important characterization of the second phase is that it was opening up to the world,

02:20:09.520 --> 02:20:15.040
[Guest 2]: was reducing trade barriers, it was reducing capital controls, and it was commencing on

02:20:15.040 --> 02:20:22.800
[Guest 2]: domestic financial system. So these are the two different phases of 77 to 91 as being more

02:20:22.800 --> 02:20:28.560
[Guest 2]: domestically oriented and the 91 reforms as being more about the external sector and about finance.

02:20:30.240 --> 02:20:35.120
[Guest 1]: I would add a few things to what Ajay said. So first, I should plug the project, right? So

02:20:35.840 --> 02:20:39.920
[Guest 1]: some of the things that Ajay spoke about are directly about the 1991 project.

02:20:39.920 --> 02:20:47.520
[Guest 1]: So the website is the1991project.com. There were two crises that were happening simultaneously.

02:20:47.520 --> 02:20:53.200
[Guest 1]: So you know, Ajay is absolutely right, the structural break happens in the 80s. But one

02:20:53.200 --> 02:20:57.440
[Guest 1]: is some of this, you know, the benefits you're getting because of broadbanding, right? Like

02:20:57.440 --> 02:21:02.480
[Guest 1]: first you could make spoons, now you can also make forks. So of course, there's an expansion

02:21:02.480 --> 02:21:08.240
[Guest 1]: in what you can make and there is a reallocation of goods going to slightly higher valued users.

02:21:08.240 --> 02:21:15.120
[Guest 1]: So it's more productivity. But simultaneously, the government had gotten into all sorts of crazy

02:21:15.120 --> 02:21:22.880
[Guest 1]: welfare spending. You know, by the 80s, the cronyist socialist state is kind of at its peak,

02:21:22.880 --> 02:21:29.600
[Guest 1]: right? So everything you have from your, you know, loan waivers to, you know, a complete

02:21:29.600 --> 02:21:34.720
[Guest 1]: mess that is happening with the banking system to increase in all your agricultural subsidies,

02:21:34.720 --> 02:21:39.840
[Guest 1]: post green revolution, all this is like, you know, there's a huge fiscal burden. So while

02:21:39.840 --> 02:21:46.320
[Guest 1]: there is growth in the 80s, I mean, we should also talk about how the deficit started to become

02:21:46.320 --> 02:21:52.000
[Guest 1]: very large in the 80s and became a little bit unmanageable, right? So both on the books deficit

02:21:52.000 --> 02:21:56.720
[Guest 1]: and off the books deficit. So that's number one. The second is there's always all these

02:21:56.720 --> 02:22:01.120
[Guest 1]: global accidents that really matter, right? So we knew that there is a balance of payments

02:22:01.120 --> 02:22:05.760
[Guest 1]: crisis brewing. It's not like they woke up one day in 1991 and they realized that it's a problem.

02:22:05.760 --> 02:22:12.160
[Guest 1]: They knew that this is going to come and go, but they thought at least the way the bureaucrats,

02:22:12.160 --> 02:22:18.000
[Guest 1]: many of them tell the story is that Rajiv Gandhi was supposed to be the intended reformer of India,

02:22:18.000 --> 02:22:22.960
[Guest 1]: right? He had already brought in some technocrats. He was being advised by Jairam Ramesh and Sam

02:22:22.960 --> 02:22:28.480
[Guest 1]: Petroda. You know, they were like very, it was very unusual because they were very young people

02:22:28.480 --> 02:22:33.600
[Guest 1]: who were liberal minded and studied in America, as opposed to the old Nehruvian guard,

02:22:33.600 --> 02:22:36.640
[Guest 1]: which were, which had been advising members of his family before that.

02:22:37.600 --> 02:22:43.200
[Guest 1]: And Monte Singh Ahluwalia has talked about how he prepared a reform document, which later became

02:22:43.200 --> 02:22:47.360
[Guest 1]: like a blueprint called the M document. But he started preparing it initially thinking that

02:22:47.360 --> 02:22:52.800
[Guest 1]: Rajiv Gandhi is going to come to power. And there were some murmurs that Rajiv Gandhi was a little

02:22:52.800 --> 02:23:00.160
[Guest 1]: bit more reform oriented than, than his mother and the previous prime minister. Simultaneously,

02:23:00.160 --> 02:23:05.360
[Guest 1]: globally, the Gulf war happens, and this is where it's the balance. You know, you could have had a

02:23:05.360 --> 02:23:09.200
[Guest 1]: fiscal deficit crisis that pushed India into reform, just happened to be a balance of payments

02:23:09.200 --> 02:23:14.800
[Guest 1]: crisis, right? And what really ends up happening is we don't have enough foreign exchange to buy

02:23:14.800 --> 02:23:21.040
[Guest 1]: essentials. And by the time you get to the mid nineties, right? And the late nineties, you can't

02:23:21.040 --> 02:23:27.840
[Guest 1]: afford more than three, four weeks of oil imports because the Gulf war has made oil suddenly very

02:23:27.840 --> 02:23:32.560
[Guest 1]: expensive, right? And you're not exporting enough to earn enough foreign exchange to buy the imports.

02:23:32.560 --> 02:23:36.960
[Guest 1]: That is, that is, you know, in a, in a nutshell, what the balance of payments crisis is,

02:23:36.960 --> 02:23:41.840
[Guest 1]: but people know this is coming. So there are a few things going on. You have A. N. Verma,

02:23:41.840 --> 02:23:47.680
[Guest 1]: who is Narsimha Rao's, you know, sort of like the prime minister's office, the main guy,

02:23:47.680 --> 02:23:55.200
[Guest 1]: but he was industry secretary before that. So he had written with Rakesh Mohan, a detailed note

02:23:55.200 --> 02:23:59.840
[Guest 1]: on de-licensing while he was in the industry secretary, right? That work had been going on

02:23:59.840 --> 02:24:06.480
[Guest 1]: since 1988. For instance, you had Montek, who immediately after Rajiv Gandhi died,

02:24:06.480 --> 02:24:10.960
[Guest 1]: it just so happened that in those years, the world was a little bit less partisan, right?

02:24:10.960 --> 02:24:17.120
[Guest 1]: So VP Singh invited Montek Aluwalia to be an advisor to his government. When VP Singh's

02:24:17.120 --> 02:24:22.880
[Guest 1]: government suddenly lost confidence and he had to resign, the Chandrashekhar government kept

02:24:22.880 --> 02:24:29.840
[Guest 1]: kept a lot of these old people on, right? So they were, they continued to be advised by the A. N.

02:24:29.840 --> 02:24:36.000
[Guest 1]: Verma's and, you know, the Rakesh Mohan. So all these people, there was a lot of continuity.

02:24:36.000 --> 02:24:39.680
[Guest 1]: So the idea that there were these three or four people who just suddenly showed up on the scene

02:24:39.680 --> 02:24:44.640
[Guest 1]: and there was a balance of payments crisis and boy, last six weeks later, we had big bang reforms.

02:24:44.640 --> 02:24:49.520
[Guest 1]: That's a very reductive view. These things were cooking for a long period, because if they don't

02:24:49.520 --> 02:24:53.600
[Guest 1]: cook for a long period, you get blunders like demonetization. You know, I want to put this out

02:24:53.600 --> 02:24:59.840
[Guest 1]: there. Demonetization is also an economic reform. It is just a very, very bad idea. And it had no

02:24:59.840 --> 02:25:05.280
[Guest 1]: consultative process and it didn't go through the two things that Ajay has been flagging this whole

02:25:05.280 --> 02:25:10.160
[Guest 1]: time, which is, I look in my backyard and I talk about what's happening, right? And second,

02:25:10.160 --> 02:25:15.520
[Guest 1]: a very clean analytical framework to say, why do we have these restrictions on industries?

02:25:15.520 --> 02:25:20.560
[Guest 1]: Why do we have 75 industries on this list? Why can't we just remove it? Right. Why do small

02:25:20.560 --> 02:25:25.360
[Guest 1]: scale industries deserve protection? So on and so forth. So that's one part of it. And the second

02:25:25.360 --> 02:25:30.240
[Guest 1]: part of it that I want to flag, and I think we've done a good job of this in the project. So right

02:25:30.240 --> 02:25:35.280
[Guest 1]: now, when we launched the project, we kind of gave the series of events that I told you about,

02:25:35.280 --> 02:25:40.560
[Guest 1]: and it eventually precipitated in India can't afford imports. The world economy has lost

02:25:40.560 --> 02:25:46.960
[Guest 1]: confidence in India. Moody's and S&P downgrades the economy. India is literally forced to sell

02:25:46.960 --> 02:25:50.800
[Guest 1]: its gold, which is a matter of great shame, because this is something even the public

02:25:50.800 --> 02:25:59.600
[Guest 1]: understands, right? You only pawn your family assets when, as they say, you're at the brink

02:25:59.600 --> 02:26:07.040
[Guest 1]: of bankruptcy. So all this stuff is going on. Two more things which are interesting here. One is

02:26:07.040 --> 02:26:13.280
[Guest 1]: Narsimha Rao, when he was the external affairs minister with Rajiv Gandhi, has been to China,

02:26:13.280 --> 02:26:19.600
[Guest 1]: has he's been to Singapore, he's been to Korea, right? These guys have seen the Asian miracle,

02:26:19.600 --> 02:26:26.320
[Guest 1]: and Narsimha Rao in particular is very inspired by Deng Xiaoping, right? And China matters a lot.

02:26:26.320 --> 02:26:30.320
[Guest 1]: So Ajay mentioned that, you know, the Berlin Wall fell, and you know, the Soviet Union is

02:26:30.320 --> 02:26:35.600
[Guest 1]: kind of collapsing and breaking down. We already know about the South Korean miracle. But at that

02:26:35.600 --> 02:26:41.680
[Guest 1]: point, when Ann Krueger and Bhagwati were talking about South Korea and Taiwan being these amazing

02:26:41.680 --> 02:26:45.920
[Guest 1]: examples of growth, most of the development economists said, yeah, but they are small

02:26:45.920 --> 02:26:52.560
[Guest 1]: countries. You can't have this for India or China. So when China sees a big difference in rates of

02:26:52.560 --> 02:26:59.520
[Guest 1]: growth, when they start liberalizing in the late 70s, now clearly there is a template for Indians

02:26:59.520 --> 02:27:04.480
[Guest 1]: to follow, right? And it seems like Narsimha Rao, either because he was personally enamored or

02:27:04.480 --> 02:27:09.600
[Guest 1]: otherwise, is a big fan of this template. He wasn't able to meet Deng Xiaoping. That's an

02:27:09.600 --> 02:27:14.880
[Guest 1]: interesting aside, but he's very inspired by it. And Manmohan Singh is quite important in this

02:27:14.880 --> 02:27:21.520
[Guest 1]: story because he has, at that point, occupied every important office within the bureaucracy

02:27:21.520 --> 02:27:25.760
[Guest 1]: that an economist could have occupied. He's been at the Ministry of Finance, he's been a chief

02:27:25.760 --> 02:27:30.240
[Guest 1]: economic advisor, he's been a deputy governor at the RBI. And these things matter because they

02:27:30.240 --> 02:27:37.120
[Guest 1]: foster trust, right? When you want to push something through in the government and you want

02:27:37.120 --> 02:27:41.360
[Guest 1]: to do it quickly, you have to be able to pick up the phone and call five people and they're more

02:27:41.360 --> 02:27:46.080
[Guest 1]: likely to listen to you if you worked with them before or you've established a certain amount of

02:27:46.080 --> 02:27:51.760
[Guest 1]: credibility or people trust your economic judgment and your political savvy and they know that you

02:27:51.760 --> 02:27:56.480
[Guest 1]: have the ear of the prime minister and so on and so forth. So I would say in this instance,

02:27:56.480 --> 02:28:01.440
[Guest 1]: the technical skills of Manmohan Singh may have mattered less than his actual experience within

02:28:01.440 --> 02:28:06.080
[Guest 1]: the Indian government. So one of the things we came across was we wanted to put this story together

02:28:07.040 --> 02:28:11.920
[Guest 1]: and we came up with a list of about 20 to 22 bureaucrats and many of them, you know,

02:28:12.800 --> 02:28:18.400
[Guest 1]: Ajay already mentioned. So it's A. N. Varma, but it's also C. Rangarajan, right? Who is at the

02:28:19.360 --> 02:28:24.880
[Guest 1]: RBI at the time. C. Rangarajan went on later to write the balance of payments committee report

02:28:24.880 --> 02:28:28.720
[Guest 1]: for the Reserve Bank of India, which is still, you know, it's like a textbook kind of thing

02:28:28.720 --> 02:28:33.440
[Guest 1]: that we all studied in college, the Rangarajan committee report. So these guys are very sound

02:28:33.440 --> 02:28:38.880
[Guest 1]: economists. They are entrenched in a system in a good way in the sense that they all know each

02:28:38.880 --> 02:28:43.200
[Guest 1]: other. They worked with each other. They were together in a different capacity at a previous

02:28:43.200 --> 02:28:49.600
[Guest 1]: time. They know what they are doing, which is a very large part of the reform story. I don't

02:28:49.600 --> 02:28:55.200
[Guest 1]: think we've been able to recreate that in modern times because one, there is a lot of partisan

02:28:55.200 --> 02:29:00.480
[Guest 1]: who belongs to which party kind of thing. Now there is a whole, you know, the prime minister

02:29:00.480 --> 02:29:05.520
[Guest 1]: is a Gujarati, so the Gujarat kadar will be given, you know, precedence in all important

02:29:05.520 --> 02:29:10.400
[Guest 1]: positions in the bureaucracy. So there's a lot of strange things going on. I mean, there's an

02:29:10.400 --> 02:29:16.960
[Guest 1]: insider outsider cut depending on caste and language and state and, you know, party and

02:29:16.960 --> 02:29:23.120
[Guest 1]: economic background, but that seemed to have not been the case in that, you know, sort of like a

02:29:23.120 --> 02:29:27.680
[Guest 1]: golden period of reform, as we call it. And the last thing I'd say here is, though we haven't

02:29:27.680 --> 02:29:33.840
[Guest 1]: gotten to that point in the project yet, a lot of these people continue to consult for the government

02:29:33.840 --> 02:29:40.160
[Guest 1]: even well into the Vajpayee years. You know, all this human capital and knowledge and expertise

02:29:40.160 --> 02:29:45.440
[Guest 1]: and connections that had been built up, they didn't just disappear, right? They were held on

02:29:45.440 --> 02:29:50.720
[Guest 1]: as people, you know, there was a lot of continuity, which is something we don't see in government

02:29:50.720 --> 02:29:56.720
[Guest 1]: today for a long time, right? And the people who do have continuity, we don't give them status.

02:29:56.720 --> 02:30:00.400
[Guest 1]: So the reason, one of the reasons we put up the bios of all these people and we wanted

02:30:00.400 --> 02:30:08.000
[Guest 1]: pictures and names and faces is people should know who C. Rangarajan is, you know, like,

02:30:08.000 --> 02:30:12.880
[Guest 1]: like they should recognize his face. This should be a very high status individual,

02:30:12.880 --> 02:30:18.000
[Guest 1]: right? Same with Ashok Desai. These people should be celebrated because they come with,

02:30:18.000 --> 02:30:21.760
[Guest 1]: like, you know, even scientists, the other day I saw in the Wimbledon, they stood up and gave

02:30:21.760 --> 02:30:26.960
[Guest 1]: a standing ovation to one of the people who was involved in the AstraZeneca vaccine, right?

02:30:26.960 --> 02:30:32.720
[Guest 1]: Like, we've got to recognize who are the people outside the prime minister alone, like one

02:30:32.720 --> 02:30:39.280
[Guest 1]: individual who work for 10, 15, 20 years for a very long and consistent period of time.

02:30:39.280 --> 02:30:45.200
[Guest 1]: And they're able to nurture ideas. They're able to mentor the next generation of bureaucrats.

02:30:45.200 --> 02:30:51.680
[Guest 1]: And therefore there is a continuity in reforms. So when I unpeel the 1991 story, the issue is not

02:30:51.680 --> 02:30:56.800
[Guest 1]: whether July 24, 1991 is a special date and some, you know, there was a secret sauce and some magic

02:30:56.800 --> 02:31:04.320
[Guest 1]: happened and the astrological universe aligned. That's not what it is. It is that when the moment

02:31:04.320 --> 02:31:10.720
[Guest 1]: could align and when the window opened, all this work had already been done and all these people

02:31:10.720 --> 02:31:17.120
[Guest 1]: were already in position to make sure that sensible ideas can actually be followed through in a

02:31:17.120 --> 02:31:22.160
[Guest 1]: sensible way. So I think that to me is the most interesting part to add to what Ajay said.

02:31:23.760 --> 02:31:28.720
[Guest 2]: I agree with everything Shruti has said. I have a few more aspects and illustrations of this. So I

02:31:28.720 --> 02:31:33.760
[Guest 2]: was just thinking about Vijay Kedkar's story. He started out as economic advisor in the

02:31:33.760 --> 02:31:39.760
[Guest 2]: Ministry of Petroleum. And so first, interestingly and surprisingly in the modern world, after

02:31:41.200 --> 02:31:46.000
[Guest 2]: some years in the Ministry of Petroleum, starting out as an economic advisor, he became the

02:31:46.000 --> 02:31:52.240
[Guest 2]: secretary, Ministry of Petroleum. Okay. So these days, career economists would not become the

02:31:52.240 --> 02:31:56.160
[Guest 2]: heads of department. It just doesn't happen anymore. But it was happening in those days.

02:31:56.160 --> 02:32:02.880
[Guest 2]: Similarly, Monte Kaluwalia was secretary commerce with Chidambaram as the minister in 1991, which

02:32:02.880 --> 02:32:08.400
[Guest 2]: was very important to the trade liberalization which happened in that period. The second

02:32:08.400 --> 02:32:12.880
[Guest 2]: interesting thing is Vijay Kedkar got six full years as secretary, which is something that is

02:32:12.880 --> 02:32:19.120
[Guest 2]: just unheard of these days. And in those six years, he basically got that entire pipeline done

02:32:19.120 --> 02:32:26.960
[Guest 2]: of opening up to private sector participation in oil exploration, in oil extraction, in refining,

02:32:26.960 --> 02:32:31.680
[Guest 2]: all the way to retail, which I think got a bit messed up. But six years is the kind of time

02:32:31.680 --> 02:32:36.320
[Guest 2]: horizon. And note, this is on top of many years spent in the ministry as the economic advisor.

02:32:36.320 --> 02:32:41.760
[Guest 2]: So earlier, he was the advisor to people like Lavraj Kumar, who were there. When Lavraj Kumar

02:32:41.760 --> 02:32:50.320
[Guest 2]: left, he blessed and anointed his successor. So again, it was a different age that a person like

02:32:50.320 --> 02:32:58.320
[Guest 2]: that was given the continuity of going on from being economic advisor to secretary and then got

02:32:58.320 --> 02:33:03.360
[Guest 2]: six years as secretary. And it's a big important change that the petroleum industry is one of the

02:33:03.360 --> 02:33:10.160
[Guest 2]: most important industries from the overall economy. And piece by piece, that kind of

02:33:10.160 --> 02:33:16.320
[Guest 2]: detailed technical attention was required in many, many parts of the ecosystem.

02:33:16.320 --> 02:33:20.240
[Guest 2]: Second story, I just want to tell at a more personal level. I was hired by Yashwant Sinha

02:33:20.240 --> 02:33:29.840
[Guest 2]: and Rakesh Mohan at the Department of Economic Affairs. And a short while later, Jaswant Singh

02:33:29.840 --> 02:33:37.120
[Guest 2]: became finance minister. And with him S. Narayan was the finance secretary and K. L. Kaur came in

02:33:37.120 --> 02:33:43.120
[Guest 2]: as advisor to the minister. And after that, there were the elections and Chidambaram became the

02:33:43.120 --> 02:33:50.240
[Guest 2]: minister. It never occurred to me that I was partisan, because I truly wasn't. I was just a

02:33:50.240 --> 02:33:56.640
[Guest 2]: technician. I was just used to solving technical puzzles and intellectual problems. It never

02:33:56.640 --> 02:34:03.520
[Guest 2]: occurred to me that I had one side of the ideological spectrum or the other. There was a

02:34:03.520 --> 02:34:09.680
[Guest 2]: whole world, there was a culture of experts and expertise and people worked with government period,

02:34:09.680 --> 02:34:15.680
[Guest 2]: it didn't matter who you were. So as an example, when Monte Kaluwalia finished up as finance

02:34:15.680 --> 02:34:20.560
[Guest 2]: secretary, he went to the planning commission, Vijay Kelkar replaced him. He came from being

02:34:20.560 --> 02:34:24.480
[Guest 2]: minister of petroleum, he became finance secretary at the Department of Economic Affairs. There was

02:34:24.480 --> 02:34:29.200
[Guest 2]: no fuss about these things. It didn't matter that are you with this government or that government.

02:34:29.200 --> 02:34:34.640
[Guest 2]: And then Kelkar went to the IMF as the director. And when Vajpayee was prime minister and Jaswant

02:34:34.640 --> 02:34:39.360
[Guest 2]: Singh was finance minister, Kelkar came back as advisor to the minister at the North Block. There

02:34:39.360 --> 02:34:43.680
[Guest 2]: was no fuss about all these things. And has it changed today?

02:34:43.680 --> 02:34:51.200
[Guest 2]: Yeah, today, all the features I described, you won't find career experts becoming secretaries,

02:34:51.200 --> 02:34:56.400
[Guest 2]: you won't find long tenures. So a younger person getting six years as secretary,

02:34:56.400 --> 02:35:02.080
[Guest 2]: I can't recall the last time it happened. And you don't find people spanning across governments.

02:35:02.080 --> 02:35:06.880
[Guest 2]: Today, you have to wear your loyalty on your sleeve on Twitter, then it becomes awkward.

02:35:06.880 --> 02:35:11.680
[Guest 1]: I mean, there are a lot of problems with the permanent executive and the way we have these

02:35:11.680 --> 02:35:15.600
[Guest 1]: bureaucratic appointments, and they're virtually lifelong tenure and things like that, right?

02:35:15.600 --> 02:35:20.800
[Guest 1]: I know all the problems with it. It's like a whole Yes Minister comedy in itself, right?

02:35:21.440 --> 02:35:27.520
[Guest 1]: But the single advantage of it is you can have continuity across government,

02:35:28.160 --> 02:35:33.840
[Guest 1]: right? And you can have people who can see through reforms past the point of like political

02:35:33.840 --> 02:35:38.960
[Guest 1]: opportunism and things like that. So it seems to me like we've taken the worst of every world,

02:35:38.960 --> 02:35:44.080
[Guest 1]: and we have made sure that the one benefit there is of this kind of, you know, permanent executive

02:35:44.080 --> 02:35:51.360
[Guest 1]: also goes away because the partisan politics has also been brought into that. The second is there,

02:35:51.360 --> 02:35:55.120
[Guest 1]: I mean, seniority was always important, and all these things were always important.

02:35:55.760 --> 02:36:02.640
[Guest 1]: But people did recognize someone of merit, and more importantly, someone of technical expertise.

02:36:02.640 --> 02:36:07.280
[Guest 1]: Right? So you did recognize that when Mohan Singh has a PhD in economics, and he has taught,

02:36:07.280 --> 02:36:12.880
[Guest 1]: and he is an expert in trade or, you know, something else, and therefore he should be

02:36:12.880 --> 02:36:17.760
[Guest 1]: this particular deputy governor at RBI, he should do this particular role at the finance ministry

02:36:17.760 --> 02:36:22.800
[Guest 1]: and so on, and, you know, kind of circulate. I feel like that has also disappeared now.

02:36:22.800 --> 02:36:28.880
[Guest 1]: Now it's more like, I need my guy to be at the environmental ministry because I need my guy to

02:36:28.880 --> 02:36:34.000
[Guest 1]: make sure that my files can move forward. And now multiply that across the Ministry of Finance and

02:36:34.000 --> 02:36:41.200
[Guest 1]: Commerce and Industry and everything else. So some of the second stage downstream problems of

02:36:41.200 --> 02:36:47.120
[Guest 1]: License Raj have also crept into this, you know, unintended part of how we treat the bureaucracy.

02:36:47.120 --> 02:36:51.760
[Guest 1]: You need your guy there because otherwise, things get stuck and there's no way to move them.

02:36:51.760 --> 02:36:56.880
[Guest 1]: But if you put your guy there, you're not always going to have expertise and expertise,

02:36:56.880 --> 02:37:02.080
[Guest 1]: you're not going to have expertise and loyalty. That's a very rare thing to get.

02:37:02.080 --> 02:37:05.200
[Guest 1]: And you might even get it in one person, you're not going to get it across the board.

02:37:05.200 --> 02:37:09.680
[Guest 1]: Right? So that's, I think, really, really important. It's also the same with judges.

02:37:09.680 --> 02:37:14.480
[Guest 1]: When was the last time you got a Supreme Court Chief Justice who had a tenure longer than,

02:37:14.480 --> 02:37:19.920
[Guest 1]: you know, a year, year and a half? Supreme Court Justice, the standard tenure is a couple of years,

02:37:19.920 --> 02:37:25.520
[Guest 1]: less than two years, right? So this is not just a bureaucracy thing. This plague is everywhere

02:37:25.520 --> 02:37:31.440
[Amit Varma]: inside the government. No, and a great example of this plague of loyalty, as it were, is what

02:37:31.440 --> 02:37:35.840
[Amit Varma]: happened after demonetization, where every economist either associated with the government

02:37:35.840 --> 02:37:40.080
[Amit Varma]: or who had otherwise supported it were essentially told that right in support of it. Of course,

02:37:40.080 --> 02:37:45.920
[Amit Varma]: the three of us all wrote opposing demonetization from day one. But there are so many people who

02:37:45.920 --> 02:37:50.560
[Amit Varma]: definitely knew better, who actually wrote in support of demonetization, even though they knew

02:37:50.560 --> 02:37:55.120
[Amit Varma]: it was a disaster, because they had to stay on the good books of the government. And there are

02:37:55.120 --> 02:38:00.560
[Amit Varma]: incidents which reveal something about a person's expertise and competence. And there are incidents

02:38:00.560 --> 02:38:05.520
[Amit Varma]: which reveal something about their character. And I think a lot of that happened around that time

02:38:05.520 --> 02:38:10.720
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, people who we would otherwise think of as fine thinkers, you realize that the

02:38:10.720 --> 02:38:14.720
[Amit Varma]: scholarship might be good, but they're deficient in character, when you know, they don't sort of

02:38:14.720 --> 02:38:19.920
[Guest 2]: vote with their conscience, as it were. I want to tell a character story. I had started writing a

02:38:19.920 --> 02:38:24.800
[Guest 2]: column in the Business Standard. Many years ago, Ashok Desai moved out of the Ministry of Finance

02:38:24.800 --> 02:38:30.720
[Guest 2]: and joined the Business Standard. And he got me going, writing a column in the Business Standard.

02:38:30.720 --> 02:38:35.760
[Guest 2]: And there was some situation where I had written something very critical of something that the

02:38:36.480 --> 02:38:42.960
[Guest 2]: DEA had done. And that day or the next day, I bumped into Monte Carlo. And I said, I kind of

02:38:42.960 --> 02:38:47.520
[Guest 2]: apologetically said, I hope you're okay with the fact that I really disagree with what you've done.

02:38:47.520 --> 02:38:53.200
[Guest 2]: And I wrote harsh words, criticizing you in the newspaper. He said, you know, on this subject,

02:38:53.200 --> 02:39:00.320
[Guest 2]: I agree with you completely. And he said, I am not monolithic. I am one creature out of a complex

02:39:00.320 --> 02:39:04.880
[Guest 2]: machine called the Ministry of Finance. Very often, I might advocate something internally,

02:39:04.880 --> 02:39:09.200
[Guest 2]: and I might lose. And the outcome that comes out is something that I may not agree with.

02:39:09.760 --> 02:39:14.000
[Guest 2]: And I might secretly applaud when you write something in the newspaper attacking the

02:39:14.000 --> 02:39:19.040
[Guest 2]: Ministry of Finance. He says, you should never worry about offending me when you write in the

02:39:19.040 --> 02:39:23.760
[Guest 2]: newspaper. And that was so great. It really gave me comfort. It gave me confidence. Similarly,

02:39:23.760 --> 02:39:29.920
[Guest 2]: I remember the times when I was at NIPFP, and we were explicitly funded by the Ministry of Finance.

02:39:29.920 --> 02:39:34.880
[Guest 2]: And, you know, fortnight after fortnight, I used to be writing stuff in the newspaper about all

02:39:34.880 --> 02:39:39.200
[Guest 2]: the things being done wrong by the government. And it was just, it was never a problem. It was

02:39:39.760 --> 02:39:43.920
[Guest 2]: an age when knowledge mattered, when arguments mattered, when criticisms mattered.

02:39:43.920 --> 02:39:49.280
[Guest 2]: The people at the top were secure enough to understand that this is the part of the process

02:39:49.280 --> 02:39:56.800
[Guest 2]: of how we fix things, that it is important to solve problems, and criticism is an integral

02:39:56.800 --> 02:40:04.880
[Guest 2]: part of that. My last funny story is that prior to the 2004 general elections, the Lok Sabha elections,

02:40:04.880 --> 02:40:09.440
[Guest 2]: there was a debate between Jaswant Singh and the shadow finance minister, namely Manmohan Singh,

02:40:09.440 --> 02:40:17.920
[Guest 2]: on TV. Okay, so imagine it, it was a more evolved India, where these things could happen. And Jaswant

02:40:17.920 --> 02:40:25.600
[Guest 2]: Singh was taken aback when Manmohan Singh said that there is a problem with interest rate exposure

02:40:25.600 --> 02:40:31.280
[Guest 2]: of banks in India. And it's not just me saying it, one of your own economic advisors has written a

02:40:31.280 --> 02:40:35.600
[Guest 2]: paper. There's this guy called Ajay Shah who has written a paper, which has demonstrated that

02:40:35.600 --> 02:40:40.400
[Guest 2]: the banks are facing a lot of difficulties, and you will potentially have a banking crisis

02:40:40.400 --> 02:40:44.400
[Guest 2]: because of the currency mismatch in the banks. And Jaswant Singh came back home and said,

02:40:44.400 --> 02:40:49.120
[Guest 2]: who is this guy, Ajay Shah, and I want his head on a platter. And it all boiled down to basically,

02:40:49.120 --> 02:40:53.440
[Guest 2]: him being explained that I've worked on this thing inside the Ministry of Finance forever.

02:40:53.440 --> 02:40:59.360
[Guest 2]: I have always been talking and worrying and writing and writing articles about these problems,

02:40:59.360 --> 02:41:03.920
[Guest 2]: and I wrote a research paper, and this is perfectly okay. And I have been part of the

02:41:03.920 --> 02:41:07.360
[Guest 2]: constructive process as an employee in the Ministry of Finance of trying to fix this.

02:41:07.360 --> 02:41:09.360
[Guest 2]: And at the end, it was okay, there was absolutely no friction.

02:41:10.240 --> 02:41:14.000
[Guest 1]: Also, I think I want to add one more layer to this. So, you know, one, of course,

02:41:14.000 --> 02:41:18.000
[Guest 1]: now it's all about tribal loyalties and things like that. But even on the tribal loyalty point,

02:41:18.000 --> 02:41:23.360
[Guest 1]: the other day, I think this was Devesh Kapoor who said this. He said, look at what has happened

02:41:23.360 --> 02:41:31.040
[Guest 1]: during COVID. All your so-called liberal elites and foreigners, you know, and this is really

02:41:31.040 --> 02:41:35.920
[Guest 1]: this is really people like me in particular, right, who are constantly criticizing the Modi

02:41:35.920 --> 02:41:42.800
[Guest 1]: government and all of that. We are also the biggest advocates that the Biden administration

02:41:42.800 --> 02:41:48.560
[Guest 1]: should help India and send vaccines and, you know, reduce the restrictions and make sure that exports

02:41:48.560 --> 02:41:56.720
[Guest 1]: can go so that India can manufacture more vaccines. So loyalty to a party or an individual is quite

02:41:56.720 --> 02:42:04.400
[Guest 1]: different than loyalty to the country or the cause. So here it's not that those times, you know,

02:42:04.400 --> 02:42:10.320
[Guest 1]: loyalty didn't matter. It is that the loyalty wasn't to an individual, right? This loyalty

02:42:10.320 --> 02:42:18.080
[Guest 1]: to an individual is a Narendra Modi and Indira Gandhi playbook. Okay. It is not a Nehru-Vajpayee

02:42:18.080 --> 02:42:22.880
[Guest 1]: playbook. It's not even a partisan thing. It's there are certain individuals who are demanding

02:42:22.880 --> 02:42:28.720
[Guest 1]: these very high degrees of, you know, loyalty, which which are frankly very counterproductive

02:42:28.720 --> 02:42:36.800
[Guest 1]: to the overall enterprise of governance. So I just want to flag that out there that they

02:42:36.800 --> 02:42:42.480
[Guest 1]: expected loyalty from Ajay even before. It just wasn't to tow the party line or the individual line.

02:42:44.640 --> 02:42:48.560
[Amit Varma]: So before we get to the reforms themselves, which I think it's about time we do, but before we get

02:42:48.560 --> 02:42:54.480
[Amit Varma]: to the reforms, one final sort of meta question about the stuff happening behind the scenes,

02:42:54.480 --> 02:42:59.600
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, on one hand, what you suddenly see in 91 is a lot of people who weren't really

02:42:59.600 --> 02:43:05.120
[Amit Varma]: speaking out before, at least in the public discourse about the necessity for reforms,

02:43:05.120 --> 02:43:10.640
[Amit Varma]: suddenly coming out very strongly in favor of it. Like, you know, Manmohan in his 91 budget

02:43:10.640 --> 02:43:14.560
[Amit Varma]: speech famously saying no power on earth can stop an idea whose time has come. You know,

02:43:14.560 --> 02:43:19.440
[Amit Varma]: Rakesh Mohan in India transformed describes how Manmohan had a meeting with all his bureaucrats

02:43:19.440 --> 02:43:24.880
[Amit Varma]: and secretaries as the reforms were being planned. And he told them, quote, if any of you have any

02:43:24.880 --> 02:43:29.600
[Amit Varma]: difficulty with the proposed reform program, we can find other things for you to do, stop code,

02:43:29.600 --> 02:43:34.160
[Amit Varma]: which is an act of great conviction. And there are various things that Manmohan, Chidambaram,

02:43:34.160 --> 02:43:38.880
[Amit Varma]: Jayaram Ramesh all said during this period, which showed that conviction. But at the same time,

02:43:38.880 --> 02:43:44.000
[Amit Varma]: the pace of change after these reforms is a little bit slow. And there is a lot of opposition

02:43:44.000 --> 02:43:48.960
[Amit Varma]: that they face internally, like Rakesh Mohan describes this cabinet meeting where their

02:43:48.960 --> 02:43:54.400
[Amit Varma]: initial note about the reforms, which they were planning to bring about in July 24, 91,

02:43:54.400 --> 02:43:59.600
[Amit Varma]: it met with opposition from within the cabinet, where people like ML Forte Dhar and Arjun Singh

02:43:59.600 --> 02:44:04.160
[Amit Varma]: were like, no, this is against everything Nehru and Indira stood for and you're turning your back

02:44:04.160 --> 02:44:08.800
[Amit Varma]: against our great heritage of the Congress Party and blah, blah, blah, and all this shit happened.

02:44:08.800 --> 02:44:14.640
[Amit Varma]: And what Mohan describes is that, you know, the framers of that document got to work

02:44:14.640 --> 02:44:20.480
[Amit Varma]: and adroitly they changed a lot of wording to say things like in continuation with Nehru's

02:44:21.040 --> 02:44:26.160
[Amit Varma]: concern for our economy and Indira Gandhi's love for the poor. And so they changed the political

02:44:26.160 --> 02:44:32.320
[Amit Varma]: messaging. But substantively, everything remained the same. And it kind of went through. Now,

02:44:32.320 --> 02:44:38.160
[Amit Varma]: this brings in mind that earlier phrase about the liberalization by stealth of the 1980s,

02:44:38.160 --> 02:44:45.360
[Amit Varma]: was that stealth necessary? Was this just a bunch of elites who fortuitously happened to think along

02:44:45.360 --> 02:44:51.520
[Amit Varma]: the same lines in the 80s and 90s, but they were fighting an establishment which didn't necessarily

02:44:51.520 --> 02:44:56.400
[Amit Varma]: agree, they were fighting inertia, they were fighting institutions and individuals who had

02:44:56.400 --> 02:45:02.640
[Amit Varma]: entirely different incentives. And therefore did that kind of complicate the whole process,

02:45:02.640 --> 02:45:09.040
[Amit Varma]: because what we then saw is we had that burst of liberalization in 91. We had some more under

02:45:09.040 --> 02:45:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayee perhaps, but there was a lot of liberalization that didn't happen. A lot of

02:45:14.000 --> 02:45:18.720
[Amit Varma]: reforms that I'm sure Manmohan and Chidambaram would agree made a lot of sense, but that never

02:45:18.720 --> 02:45:24.240
[Amit Varma]: happened at all. So what is that? What is that internal fight? Is there an internal narrative

02:45:24.240 --> 02:45:29.680
[Amit Varma]: battle within the state as well, which you know, has to be fought? So, you know, if you look at

02:45:29.680 --> 02:45:35.280
[Guest 1]: history, there has never been a situation where within a party, everyone agrees on everything,

02:45:35.280 --> 02:45:43.040
[Guest 1]: right? I mean, when we talked about the 1947, 1950 moment, right? Congress is like this umbrella

02:45:43.040 --> 02:45:50.240
[Guest 1]: party, but it has people like GB Panth, who are really, you know, closer to today's, you know,

02:45:50.240 --> 02:45:56.960
[Guest 1]: UP BJP faction. And, and you also have on the other extreme, like, you know, people like Nehru,

02:45:56.960 --> 02:46:02.480
[Guest 1]: right? There is always going to be the need for a particular kind of leadership,

02:46:03.040 --> 02:46:07.440
[Guest 1]: which is willing to take along people within the party and people in the opposition.

02:46:07.440 --> 02:46:12.720
[Guest 1]: Okay, the idea that you can have democratic politics without that, and everyone magically

02:46:12.720 --> 02:46:17.360
[Guest 1]: agrees upon the same idea at the same time, and everyone's willing to give up their entrenched

02:46:17.360 --> 02:46:22.480
[Guest 1]: interest. I mean, this is a pipe dream. So the question is always, who are these leaders who

02:46:22.480 --> 02:46:27.920
[Guest 1]: are able to make this happen? So we, we talked a brief moment ago about how Yashwant Sinha,

02:46:27.920 --> 02:46:33.040
[Guest 1]: you know, I think a few weeks ago, he said that he had almost the identical speech as Manmohan

02:46:33.040 --> 02:46:37.040
[Guest 1]: Singh, because you know, the blueprint of the reforms was ready, but he didn't have a prime

02:46:37.040 --> 02:46:42.480
[Guest 1]: minister who could push things through, right? One of the first few things that Narasimha Rao

02:46:42.480 --> 02:46:47.040
[Guest 1]: and Manmohan Singh do as a team is they talk to people within their party, and they talk to people

02:46:47.040 --> 02:46:53.360
[Guest 1]: outside the party. So Narasimha Rao calls this famous meeting of all opposition parties, right?

02:46:53.360 --> 02:46:57.760
[Guest 1]: And says, look, the country is in deep crisis, the only way to get out of the balance of payment

02:46:57.760 --> 02:47:02.560
[Guest 1]: situation crisis is to devalue, and then immediately after that announced trade and

02:47:02.560 --> 02:47:06.560
[Guest 1]: industrial reforms, because otherwise, you can't capitalize on the devaluation, like it's just not

02:47:06.560 --> 02:47:13.520
[Guest 1]: going to matter. In the midst of this, Manmohan Singh is tasked with keeping the internal bureaucracy,

02:47:13.520 --> 02:47:17.680
[Guest 1]: you know, the troops in check, right? That's why the famous Rakesh Mohan thing of, you know,

02:47:17.680 --> 02:47:21.200
[Guest 1]: making sure that all the secretaries are not going to create problems and things like that.

02:47:21.840 --> 02:47:28.400
[Guest 1]: And you do have to tell the old guard, now imagine, everyone who's in the system has

02:47:28.400 --> 02:47:34.400
[Guest 1]: gotten a certain amount of status and clout by being in the directorate of technical,

02:47:34.400 --> 02:47:39.520
[Guest 1]: whatever, right? The people who are in the cement department, giving you the cement permits,

02:47:39.520 --> 02:47:43.600
[Guest 1]: and you know, the commerce department, these people have clout for a particular reason,

02:47:43.600 --> 02:47:48.320
[Guest 1]: you're basically telling them that everything they've devoted their life to for the last 10

02:47:48.320 --> 02:47:53.120
[Guest 1]: years is complete bunkum, and we're going to take it away and what you did had no purpose.

02:47:53.120 --> 02:47:57.440
[Guest 1]: And not only did it have no purpose, you also impoverished the country and led to a balance

02:47:57.440 --> 02:48:02.640
[Guest 1]: of payments crisis. Now, you can't like make these people disappear, right? You got to take

02:48:02.640 --> 02:48:08.000
[Guest 1]: them along in some way. So what is that way? So sometimes you got to plead with them like,

02:48:08.000 --> 02:48:12.160
[Guest 1]: you know, Narasimha Rao did with opposition parties. Sometimes you negotiate with them.

02:48:12.160 --> 02:48:16.640
[Guest 1]: And sometimes you just plain tell them like Manmohan Singh, you better get in line or you,

02:48:16.640 --> 02:48:21.200
[Guest 1]: you know, fall by the wayside. So it was a combination of all of these things. And I

02:48:21.200 --> 02:48:26.400
[Guest 1]: don't think it's unique to 1991. This needs to happen every time there is reform. And it is

02:48:26.400 --> 02:48:32.080
[Guest 1]: any reform. So either you do this secretly with no consultative process and do it by ordinance,

02:48:32.080 --> 02:48:36.960
[Guest 1]: the way Indira Gandhi nationalizes banks or Narendra Modi does demonetization,

02:48:36.960 --> 02:48:42.800
[Guest 1]: or you do this the proper way. And the proper way incidentally takes time, right? So the 91

02:48:42.800 --> 02:48:47.120
[Guest 1]: reforms are also very unique in that in the beginning of July 91, you have two rounds of

02:48:47.120 --> 02:48:53.040
[Guest 1]: devaluation. Two, three days after that, you have a huge change in trade policy that's announced.

02:48:53.040 --> 02:48:57.200
[Guest 1]: Two weeks after that, you have complete industrial de-licensing. This has never happened before,

02:48:57.840 --> 02:49:03.760
[Guest 1]: right? And that pace of reforms is almost impossible to sustain, right? So the expectation

02:49:03.760 --> 02:49:07.120
[Guest 1]: that that's the pace at which it would have happened. And in five years, we've completely

02:49:07.120 --> 02:49:13.600
[Guest 1]: dismantled 50 years of socialism. That is also unlikely. So I think the question is not why did

02:49:13.600 --> 02:49:19.040
[Guest 1]: they not continue the reforms or what stopped? I think what people, at least I'm trying to

02:49:19.040 --> 02:49:22.960
[Guest 1]: understand, and I've also learned this from the way Ajay writes about these things is

02:49:22.960 --> 02:49:28.720
[Guest 1]: try and understand what is the institutional magic, which is missing in present day,

02:49:28.720 --> 02:49:34.160
[Guest 1]: right? Which is not able to mimic the speed or the quality or the substance of the reforms that

02:49:34.160 --> 02:49:39.600
[Guest 1]: happened in those years, right? So that I think is the more valuable way that I would pose the

02:49:39.600 --> 02:49:44.320
[Guest 1]: question. I don't have any optimal timeline for how these reforms should happen to actually say

02:49:44.320 --> 02:49:48.400
[Guest 1]: that 10 years is too soon or two months is too late. You know what I mean?

02:49:49.680 --> 02:49:56.000
[Guest 2]: I find it useful to think about the categorization of first generation reforms versus second

02:49:56.000 --> 02:50:01.600
[Guest 2]: generation reforms. First generation reforms are like a stroke of the pen, where you just get the

02:50:01.600 --> 02:50:07.680
[Guest 2]: state out of the way. And that's entirely good and appropriate. And if anything was not done

02:50:07.680 --> 02:50:12.160
[Guest 2]: enough, or we need to think and strategize how to do more of it. I want to talk about

02:50:12.160 --> 02:50:16.720
[Guest 2]: customs duties as an example. I thought one of the most brilliant milestones in India's history

02:50:16.720 --> 02:50:23.520
[Guest 2]: was when Yashwant Sinha pre-announced that every year, the peak customs rate will go down by 5%.

02:50:23.520 --> 02:50:29.600
[Guest 2]: Now, that's just pitch perfect. That's the right way to do these things. Because well ahead of time,

02:50:29.600 --> 02:50:34.720
[Guest 2]: you are reshaping the structure of everybody's expectations. Every firm starts going back into

02:50:34.720 --> 02:50:39.920
[Guest 2]: their spreadsheets and thinking one year out, this is the change in raw material price. This is the

02:50:39.920 --> 02:50:47.040
[Guest 2]: change in my foreign competitors. And what am I going to do? Either I bail out or I match the

02:50:47.040 --> 02:50:53.760
[Guest 2]: productivity and the pricing of my foreign imported rivals. So over a multi-year period, the firms were

02:50:53.760 --> 02:50:58.240
[Guest 2]: given that credible warning that look, this is coming. It's coming with probability one. It was

02:50:58.240 --> 02:51:05.280
[Guest 2]: very costly to fight with people up front and say this is happening. You fight as much as you want.

02:51:05.280 --> 02:51:10.880
[Guest 2]: Sorry, this is going to happen. And as you know, there would be parts of the very BJP that were

02:51:10.880 --> 02:51:16.080
[Guest 2]: inimical to this kind of project. But in the end, it just worked magically. And that's the

02:51:16.080 --> 02:51:22.400
[Guest 2]: it just worked magically because it actually ignited investment by firms as opposed to a large

02:51:22.400 --> 02:51:27.120
[Guest 2]: big trade reform that just throws firms into disarray and messes up the investment plans of a

02:51:27.120 --> 02:51:33.920
[Guest 2]: lot of people. So even better than doing a good trade reform is doing a phased but yet completely

02:51:33.920 --> 02:51:39.440
[Guest 2]: credible and predictable trade reform. And the magic of that age was that the announcement by

02:51:39.440 --> 02:51:45.360
[Guest 2]: the Ministry of Finance that every single year, the tariff is going to be cut by 5%. That statement

02:51:45.360 --> 02:51:50.400
[Guest 2]: actually had credibility, which is again, a very difficult currency to achieve. It's a comment on

02:51:50.400 --> 02:51:54.240
[Guest 2]: those people and that community that they were able to make statements that over the next five

02:51:54.240 --> 02:51:59.360
[Guest 2]: years, this is what we're going to do. And the whole private sector believed them. It would be

02:51:59.360 --> 02:52:03.360
[Guest 2]: very difficult to do those kinds of things today that any statements made about a future date

02:52:03.920 --> 02:52:10.080
[Guest 2]: are always up for doubt, because everything is so discretionary. So when you are tactical and

02:52:10.080 --> 02:52:16.080
[Guest 2]: expedient and tactical and expedient, then you stand for nothing. So it is important to stand

02:52:16.080 --> 02:52:24.800
[Guest 2]: for a coherent philosophy. And big speeches about philosophy matter because they generate credibility

02:52:24.800 --> 02:52:32.000
[Guest 2]: about these kinds of forward-looking designs. So this is an example where it was very important

02:52:32.000 --> 02:52:39.040
[Guest 2]: to make a pre-announced stroke of the pen reform. I find it interesting to compare and contrast

02:52:39.040 --> 02:52:43.120
[Guest 2]: with the more complex reforms of actually building state capacity, that there is a

02:52:43.120 --> 02:52:48.640
[Guest 2]: constructive problem. So imagine you're going to build a regulator like CEPI, or you're going to

02:52:48.640 --> 02:52:54.720
[Guest 2]: rebuild an organization like RBI. That is much more difficult. And I think by and large,

02:52:55.360 --> 02:52:58.720
[Guest 2]: that community did not know how to do that. So with all due respect to them,

02:52:59.280 --> 02:53:03.840
[Guest 2]: they are my friends. They are my elders. I love those people. I admire those people.

02:53:03.840 --> 02:53:07.760
[Guest 2]: But roughly speaking, I think that a certain amount of decontrol got done, and that was great.

02:53:07.760 --> 02:53:14.160
[Guest 2]: But the machinery of how to think public administration, how to draft laws, how to get

02:53:14.160 --> 02:53:18.960
[Guest 2]: checks and balances, so that in a public choice world, you will get to better functioning state

02:53:18.960 --> 02:53:23.520
[Guest 2]: agencies, that process just didn't begin in that period. And so in a way, we've got a partial

02:53:23.520 --> 02:53:29.120
[Guest 2]: delivery of stroke of the pen reform. But alongside that, we've got a Kafkaesque state

02:53:29.120 --> 02:53:35.520
[Guest 2]: that is creeping every day in terms of clawing back freedom and grabbing power. So I want to

02:53:35.520 --> 02:53:41.440
[Guest 2]: tell one little story as an example of what goes wrong in that first-generation reform approach

02:53:41.440 --> 02:53:46.960
[Guest 2]: of stroke of the pen. So the economists of that period wanted to announce that we will now have

02:53:46.960 --> 02:53:52.080
[Guest 2]: current account convertibility, which means that for you and I to import or export goods, there'll

02:53:52.080 --> 02:53:56.640
[Guest 2]: be nothing. There'll be absolutely no friction. And they wanted to begin a process towards

02:53:56.640 --> 02:54:01.200
[Guest 2]: capital account convertibility. Certainly, they wanted to decriminalize capital account

02:54:01.200 --> 02:54:05.040
[Guest 2]: violations, that it should be seen as economic law. There's no need to send a man to jail for

02:54:05.040 --> 02:54:10.960
[Guest 2]: having dollar bills in the pocket, which is the way it was earlier. So these are announcements.

02:54:10.960 --> 02:54:15.440
[Guest 2]: If you ask any economist in India, they will say, yeah, India has current account convertibility.

02:54:15.440 --> 02:54:21.600
[Guest 2]: Well, Bhargavi Zaveri and I are writing an article about the legal minefield that is there on the

02:54:21.600 --> 02:54:27.200
[Guest 2]: current account. It is not true that India has current account convertibility in the sense of

02:54:27.200 --> 02:54:33.120
[Guest 2]: unencumbered movement of goods and money across the border on the current account. For example,

02:54:33.120 --> 02:54:37.680
[Guest 2]: sometimes you will see you go to amazon.in and you try to buy goods and the merchant happens to be

02:54:37.680 --> 02:54:43.040
[Guest 2]: abroad. Amazon will say, give me KYC. Can you imagine that? For doing a cross-border transaction,

02:54:43.040 --> 02:54:48.880
[Guest 2]: they want your identity. One of the very high levels of privacy that you don't want a government

02:54:48.880 --> 02:54:53.680
[Guest 2]: organization to know that such and such name and person purchased such and such goods. But there

02:54:53.680 --> 02:54:59.040
[Guest 2]: is that breach of privacy that happens to demand your identity if you dare to buy goods from a

02:54:59.040 --> 02:55:04.080
[Guest 2]: foreign source. And that's because we didn't actually do current account convertibility.

02:55:04.080 --> 02:55:08.160
[Guest 2]: We just did a bunch of hacks here and there. We didn't get a clear framework

02:55:08.160 --> 02:55:13.520
[Guest 2]: of getting rid of all these restrictions. Similarly, on the capital account. So the old

02:55:14.560 --> 02:55:21.040
[Guest 2]: FERA, which was created by Indira Gandhi in 1973, was the rules about capital controls.

02:55:21.040 --> 02:55:24.960
[Guest 2]: And the owner and manager of the capital control system, the Reserve Bank of India,

02:55:24.960 --> 02:55:31.120
[Guest 2]: was given the job of drafting the 1999 law, which I will always say should be concerning

02:55:31.120 --> 02:55:35.040
[Guest 2]: because the incumbent that owns the system of controls is never going to really decontrol.

02:55:35.600 --> 02:55:44.160
[Guest 2]: And in the constitution of India, it is said that freedom is the default and state coercion to limit

02:55:44.160 --> 02:55:49.040
[Guest 2]: your behavior is the exception. Well, the very first sentence of FEMA says all transactions

02:55:49.040 --> 02:55:54.400
[Guest 2]: are forbidden unless we permit it. And we will show you the method through which we will give

02:55:54.400 --> 02:55:59.760
[Guest 2]: you some narrow windows of permission. But by default, everything is back. And it was...

02:55:59.760 --> 02:56:01.280
[Unknown]: FEMA is the improvement.

02:56:01.280 --> 02:56:07.360
[Guest 2]: FEMA is the improvement because it was said that, oh, this is so nice because we've removed

02:56:07.360 --> 02:56:13.280
[Guest 2]: criminal penalties. So this is supposed to be the improved law. Well, sure enough, some years later,

02:56:13.280 --> 02:56:20.560
[Guest 2]: criminal aspects to FEMA violations are back in the law. So we are actually back to a world of

02:56:20.560 --> 02:56:26.400
[Guest 2]: criminalized violations of capital controls and a Kafkaesque system of capital controls,

02:56:26.400 --> 02:56:32.720
[Guest 2]: and not even completely done current account liberalization. And what do I fault the great

02:56:32.720 --> 02:56:36.880
[Guest 2]: reformers for? For not being able to think institutionally, for not being able to read

02:56:36.880 --> 02:56:41.840
[Guest 2]: laws, for not being able to analyze law, for not thinking it through and actually executing

02:56:41.840 --> 02:56:47.760
[Guest 2]: on simple aspects, which at the time could have gone through, but there was a very simplistic

02:56:47.760 --> 02:56:52.000
[Guest 2]: economist thing that, of course, current account transactions should be completely open. Okay,

02:56:52.000 --> 02:56:56.880
[Guest 2]: let's do it. I pushed out some notification while the entire machinery of control was alive and

02:56:56.880 --> 02:57:02.240
[Guest 2]: well. I want to compare and contrast, for example, when Thatcher's people were doing the capital

02:57:02.240 --> 02:57:08.240
[Guest 2]: account decontrol of the UK. At that time, they correctly understood that it's not just the capital

02:57:08.240 --> 02:57:13.360
[Guest 2]: controls that have to go, also the reporting and monitoring requirements have to go. Because if the

02:57:13.360 --> 02:57:17.760
[Guest 2]: entire machinery of reporting and monitoring is there, then at the stroke of a pen tomorrow,

02:57:17.760 --> 02:57:22.880
[Guest 2]: somebody will bring back the controls. So not only did they destroy the capital controls at

02:57:22.880 --> 02:57:28.320
[Guest 2]: a deep legal level, they also removed the machinery of monitoring and reporting. That is freedom.

02:57:28.320 --> 02:57:32.560
[Guest 2]: Freedom is where you and I can do whatever we want, without needing to discuss or report with

02:57:32.560 --> 02:57:39.440
[Guest 2]: a sarkari guy. And you don't really see that in the environment of the 1904. So I think that's an

02:57:39.440 --> 02:57:44.720
[Guest 2]: important insight into what got done and what didn't get done. A certain incomplete version

02:57:44.720 --> 02:57:49.840
[Guest 2]: of stroke of the pen stuff got done. The state capacity building, the refashioning the Indian

02:57:49.840 --> 02:57:53.760
[Guest 2]: state to actually produce public goods and do the things that we need the state to do

02:57:53.760 --> 02:57:59.600
[Guest 2]: didn't really happen. We kind of started trying to build a SEBI, but we didn't really make progress

02:57:59.600 --> 02:58:06.560
[Guest 1]: on building high quality government organization. I would add just one thing to this, which is,

02:58:06.560 --> 02:58:12.080
[Guest 1]: so for exactly what Ajay was saying, we managed to do it for industrial de-licensing, right?

02:58:12.080 --> 02:58:17.200
[Guest 1]: So not only did we manage to, you know, remove licensing on stroke of the pen for almost all,

02:58:17.200 --> 02:58:21.120
[Guest 1]: except I think there was a handful of industries, 12 or 18 industries, which were still

02:58:21.120 --> 02:58:27.840
[Guest 1]: under licensing. But the more important part is this HR department issue, right? Which is everyone

02:58:27.840 --> 02:58:34.160
[Guest 1]: who was supposed to be in the directorate of this and controller of that now needed another job.

02:58:34.160 --> 02:58:39.440
[Guest 1]: Right? These people's jobs had to be taken away and they had to be refitted somewhere in the

02:58:39.440 --> 02:58:44.240
[Guest 1]: regulatory state, away from the command and control state. So we managed to do that with

02:58:44.240 --> 02:58:49.120
[Guest 1]: a certain degree of success with industrial controls. And Ajay is absolutely right. We

02:58:49.120 --> 02:58:54.640
[Guest 1]: never did it with capital controls and we never, we partially did it with trade and customs and

02:58:54.640 --> 02:59:00.160
[Guest 1]: tariffs, but never completely did it with that either. But I have, I think an even bigger grouse

02:59:00.160 --> 02:59:05.920
[Guest 1]: than Ajay, even on the first generation reforms, which is, we managed to do the first generation

02:59:05.920 --> 02:59:13.360
[Guest 1]: reforms, stroke of the pen in very few sectors of the economy. Right? So we managed to get basically,

02:59:13.360 --> 02:59:16.800
[Guest 1]: you know, I mean, instead of producing spoons, you can produce spoons and forks, which was the

02:59:16.800 --> 02:59:21.920
[Guest 1]: broadbanding. Then we said, okay, you can expand. Then we said we can import steel. But now if you

02:59:21.920 --> 02:59:27.520
[Guest 1]: need to produce steel at home to make spoons and forks, you cannot assemble the factors of

02:59:27.520 --> 02:59:32.480
[Guest 1]: production in India. Right? We never had the stroke of the pen reforms. I mean, we're talking

02:59:32.480 --> 02:59:36.240
[Guest 1]: about capital, which is, which is what I just been talking about all this while, but what about

02:59:36.240 --> 02:59:40.960
[Guest 1]: labor and land? Right? These are your two most important factors of production, which are

02:59:40.960 --> 02:59:46.240
[Guest 1]: virtually impossible to pull together without solving the labor and land problem. You're only

02:59:46.240 --> 02:59:51.360
[Guest 1]: going to get tech startups and software, like, you know, two people in an apartment in Bangalore

02:59:51.360 --> 02:59:56.800
[Guest 1]: kind of growth. You're never going to get like Bangladesh kind of, you know, you know,

02:59:56.800 --> 03:00:00.960
[Guest 1]: Bangladesh kind of, we have lots and lots of factories, which make lots of cheap t-shirts

03:00:00.960 --> 03:00:07.680
[Guest 1]: or cheap spoons or Nike shoes or shoelaces. That stroke of the pen first generation reform is still

03:00:07.680 --> 03:00:11.440
[Guest 1]: missing 30 years later. So I think there is another aspect of that. So, you know, there are

03:00:11.440 --> 03:00:16.160
[Guest 1]: two kinds of unfinished business. One unfinished business is what we started. We never quite saw

03:00:16.160 --> 03:00:21.360
[Guest 1]: through, which is actually propping up a sensible regulatory state. And the second is we never quite

03:00:21.360 --> 03:00:27.120
[Guest 1]: removed the permit raj, what I call permit raj, but you know, Ajay still thinks of license plus

03:00:27.120 --> 03:00:32.640
[Guest 1]: permit raj in all these other factors of production. And that is where all your choke

03:00:32.640 --> 03:00:37.200
[Guest 1]: holes and bottlenecks are today in the Indian economy. We cannot put up a plant in India.

03:00:37.200 --> 03:00:42.400
[Amit Varma]: It is impossible. And so many examples come to mind of that. Like, for example,

03:00:42.400 --> 03:00:47.200
[Amit Varma]: there was a story last year, I think about how it is easier to legally get a gun in Delhi than to

03:00:47.200 --> 03:00:52.400
[Amit Varma]: open a business. And, you know, I remember reading a few years back that the Four Seasons Hotel

03:00:52.400 --> 03:00:58.480
[Amit Varma]: took two years longer than they expected to open up in Mumbai, because they had to apply for 165

03:00:58.480 --> 03:01:04.000
[Amit Varma]: licenses, including separate licenses for the weighing scales in the kitchen and in the bedrooms.

03:01:04.000 --> 03:01:09.440
[Amit Varma]: So it's just kind of out of whack. Let's go on to the actual reforms itself of 91. You know,

03:01:09.440 --> 03:01:13.360
[Amit Varma]: if one is to explain to a layperson, what are these reforms? Why did they help? Why are they

03:01:13.360 --> 03:01:17.600
[Amit Varma]: so transformative? And I'll come back to the criticisms later, because I feel we should also

03:01:17.600 --> 03:01:22.240
[Amit Varma]: address that. And not just give hosannas, but also address the criticisms, which I am keen to do,

03:01:22.240 --> 03:01:28.400
[Amit Varma]: because I think they all have valid counters. But first, to begin with, let's sum up what the

03:01:28.400 --> 03:01:33.360
[Amit Varma]: reforms essentially were and what they did. We've mentioned bits of it in piecemeal ways that

03:01:33.360 --> 03:01:37.600
[Amit Varma]: anybody can buy and sell a phone, you know, anybody can start an airline, though obviously,

03:01:38.320 --> 03:01:42.800
[Amit Varma]: barriers to entry are different there are high there anyway. But you know, but those are little

03:01:42.800 --> 03:01:46.960
[Amit Varma]: things we've discussed in passing, if you had to sort of look at it, I was about to say from the

03:01:46.960 --> 03:01:52.880
[Amit Varma]: top down, but if you had to sort of talk about the reforms in a more systematic way, how would

03:01:52.880 --> 03:01:58.640
[Guest 1]: you explain their importance? I would put them in three categories, right? One is industrial policy,

03:01:58.640 --> 03:02:02.880
[Guest 1]: one is trade policy, and one is, you know, currency controls, right? So these are three

03:02:02.880 --> 03:02:09.280
[Guest 1]: main things. So if you just take July 1991, three major things happened. One is there was devaluing

03:02:09.280 --> 03:02:15.120
[Guest 1]: of currency, and then a further commitment in later years, which, you know, came up with a

03:02:15.120 --> 03:02:22.800
[Guest 1]: whole bunch of other committee reports and other parallel reforms, that India would not be this

03:02:22.800 --> 03:02:29.040
[Guest 1]: artificially pegged, overvalued currency, it would be more in line with what the value of the rupee

03:02:29.040 --> 03:02:34.560
[Guest 1]: is globally. So that's number one, and that's really important. Second, the restrictions on

03:02:34.560 --> 03:02:40.880
[Guest 1]: people's ability to hold even a very reasonable amount of foreign exchange, those restrictions

03:02:40.880 --> 03:02:47.040
[Guest 1]: would go away, right? And the third, initially, those people were criminalized, right? So if you

03:02:47.040 --> 03:02:55.120
[Guest 1]: held $200, instead of your allocated $80, Fera would literally put you in jail without any kind

03:02:55.120 --> 03:03:00.320
[Guest 1]: of due process, like you would go straight to jail, right? It's kind of really freaky. A lot

03:03:00.320 --> 03:03:05.120
[Guest 1]: of the smugglers that you see in Indian movies from the 70s, you mentioned Shashi Kapoor and

03:03:05.120 --> 03:03:10.880
[Guest 1]: Amitabh Bachchan, so that that's where this is coming from. What are they smuggling? You know,

03:03:10.880 --> 03:03:14.960
[Guest 1]: those smugglers are not smuggling drugs. If you notice those movies, those movies are quite

03:03:14.960 --> 03:03:23.200
[Guest 1]: sanitized. It's like Nike shoes, Walkman, you know, gold bars, VHS recorders, those are the

03:03:23.200 --> 03:03:28.080
[Guest 1]: sorts of things that they are smuggling, right? And they're smuggling because two parts. One is

03:03:28.080 --> 03:03:32.720
[Guest 1]: there is trade controls on what you can and cannot import. And second, there are these currency

03:03:32.720 --> 03:03:37.840
[Guest 1]: controls on how you pay for what you import. So one part of it is currency controls, right? This

03:03:37.840 --> 03:03:46.960
[Guest 1]: gets reformed. On part of trade controls, there are two aspects to it. One is the tariffs, okay?

03:03:47.760 --> 03:03:55.680
[Guest 1]: And the tariffs are mainly for imports, right? So now, just to give some background on where this

03:03:55.680 --> 03:04:01.920
[Guest 1]: is coming from, whenever you have a closed economic system and you say resources are

03:04:01.920 --> 03:04:07.120
[Guest 1]: very scarce and we can only use our precious foreign exchange for very specific imports,

03:04:07.120 --> 03:04:12.480
[Guest 1]: like we can't just waste all this willy-nilly on Nike shoes and Walkman, right? Like we need

03:04:12.480 --> 03:04:18.480
[Guest 1]: to import steel or whatever. Now, what ends up happening is twofold. You can do this through

03:04:18.480 --> 03:04:23.840
[Guest 1]: currency controls, but you also do it by having very, very high tariffs for imports such that

03:04:23.840 --> 03:04:28.880
[Guest 1]: they discourage imports, right? So even though there are only two cars in the market, which is

03:04:28.880 --> 03:04:34.720
[Guest 1]: your Fiat-Premier partnership and your Ambassador, and if I want to get a different car because I've

03:04:34.720 --> 03:04:41.120
[Guest 1]: been waiting in line too long, I can't easily get a car, right? Why? Because the import duties on

03:04:41.120 --> 03:04:46.560
[Guest 1]: cars, depending on whether they're basic cars or luxury cars, is anywhere between like 180% to

03:04:46.560 --> 03:04:53.280
[Guest 1]: 350%, right? This is the import duty in addition to the value of the car, which means you will do

03:04:53.280 --> 03:04:58.560
[Guest 1]: two things. You will one, protect the domestic industry of cars so that, you know, there is

03:04:58.560 --> 03:05:03.200
[Guest 1]: a dedicated demand for Ambassadors and Fiats, even though they're not such great cars.

03:05:03.200 --> 03:05:08.960
[Guest 1]: And second, you won't allow people to waste precious foreign exchange by, you know, wasting

03:05:08.960 --> 03:05:14.240
[Guest 1]: it on cars and instead use it, you know, for government to bring in steel or oil or whatever

03:05:14.240 --> 03:05:21.280
[Guest 1]: it is. That system started getting rationalized. So it didn't completely go away. But I believe the

03:05:21.280 --> 03:05:27.760
[Guest 1]: average tariffs were about 115% and the highest tariff band was like 355% or something, like just

03:05:27.760 --> 03:05:34.160
[Guest 1]: outrageous numbers that make no sense. So one is that started getting adjusted downwards, right?

03:05:34.160 --> 03:05:39.760
[Guest 1]: So what is the list? How much can you import? And what is the tariff you need to pay for imports?

03:05:39.760 --> 03:05:45.520
[Guest 1]: That process started. Very, very important. Now, the reason this is useful in line with

03:05:45.520 --> 03:05:50.320
[Guest 1]: devaluation is when you devalue your currency, your exports technically become more competitive.

03:05:50.320 --> 03:05:54.640
[Guest 1]: On paper, right? But for your exports to become more competitive, you have to actually produce

03:05:54.640 --> 03:05:58.800
[Guest 1]: stuff that other people want to buy. And if you want to actually produce things that other people

03:05:58.800 --> 03:06:04.160
[Guest 1]: want to buy, you have to be able to import high quality inputs that you require to produce them.

03:06:04.160 --> 03:06:08.880
[Guest 1]: This is like Narayan Murthy going, you know, 25 times to Delhi to get a good mainframe computer

03:06:08.880 --> 03:06:13.520
[Guest 1]: without which she can't export tech services, right? So this is a really important part.

03:06:13.520 --> 03:06:17.840
[Guest 1]: So any economy, like right now, there's this big rhetoric in India on make in India.

03:06:17.840 --> 03:06:23.920
[Guest 1]: We want to not import stuff in. We only want to export stuff. Any economy where exports are a

03:06:23.920 --> 03:06:28.880
[Guest 1]: high percentage of the GDP, imports will be a high percentage of the GDP. Because even economies

03:06:28.880 --> 03:06:34.480
[Guest 1]: that specialize in, say, steel, you're going to be exporting different kinds of steel and you're

03:06:34.480 --> 03:06:37.680
[Guest 1]: going to be importing different kinds of steel because you're that specialized. So this is

03:06:37.680 --> 03:06:43.040
[Guest 1]: something important to keep in mind. So that process of rationalizing how we trade and

03:06:43.040 --> 03:06:48.640
[Guest 1]: exchange with the rest of the world, that process began. The third part is industrial

03:06:48.640 --> 03:06:53.360
[Guest 1]: de-licensing. I think this has been the most successful element of the 1991 reforms.

03:06:53.360 --> 03:06:58.320
[Guest 1]: Industrial de-licensing is basically, you know, what we talked about, right? Like your podcast

03:06:58.320 --> 03:07:03.040
[Guest 1]: needing a license. And if you go from 20 minutes to 40 minutes, you need an expansion permit,

03:07:03.040 --> 03:07:08.240
[Guest 1]: right? If you need to import a mic, your blue Yeti mic, then you need to go to another controller

03:07:08.240 --> 03:07:11.360
[Guest 1]: to get the foreign exchange permit and then go to the customs officer to get.

03:07:11.360 --> 03:07:16.560
[Guest 1]: So none of these controls were mutually exclusive. You had to get every one of them to actually be

03:07:16.560 --> 03:07:21.680
[Guest 1]: able to, you know, conduct whatever enterprise you wanted to. That system started getting

03:07:21.680 --> 03:07:28.480
[Guest 1]: rationalized. OK, so one, they removed all these control systems, right? You could set up a firm

03:07:28.480 --> 03:07:34.080
[Guest 1]: without requiring government permission and any restriction on this is like a, you know,

03:07:34.080 --> 03:07:37.520
[Guest 1]: 10,000 crore project. I mean, those numbers were a lot smaller then, but, you know,

03:07:37.520 --> 03:07:41.840
[Guest 1]: 100 crore project or whatever. And then it also brings in the Monopoly Control Act,

03:07:41.840 --> 03:07:46.320
[Guest 1]: or we're going to put it on a separate list. Those kinds of very problematic things started

03:07:46.320 --> 03:07:52.480
[Guest 1]: getting streamlined. But the most important thing is overnight, from the default of every industry

03:07:52.480 --> 03:08:00.400
[Guest 1]: needs a permit, you went to no industry needs a permit except these 18 industries. I think that

03:08:00.400 --> 03:08:06.080
[Guest 1]: was the most exceptional reform that happened in July 1991. The reason this matters is,

03:08:06.080 --> 03:08:10.400
[Guest 1]: if you want to engage with the rest of the world and start trading, if you think about it,

03:08:10.400 --> 03:08:18.640
[Guest 1]: industrial licensing is like an import tariff is a tax on foreign producers, right? So I am

03:08:18.640 --> 03:08:24.160
[Guest 1]: penalizing a foreigner from selling to me domestically. But an industrial licensing

03:08:24.160 --> 03:08:30.160
[Guest 1]: system is a tax on domestic producers. Domestic producers can now no longer produce or, you know,

03:08:30.160 --> 03:08:34.400
[Guest 1]: need to keep paying bribes and things like that to be able to produce enough to export.

03:08:34.400 --> 03:08:41.280
[Guest 1]: So that domestic taxation system kind of lifted overnight, not completely,

03:08:41.280 --> 03:08:48.080
[Guest 1]: but in a very meaningful way that immediately opened up things. Now, the follow up reform

03:08:48.080 --> 03:08:55.200
[Guest 1]: that started in July, but kind of took a little while is they said that foreign investment is

03:08:55.200 --> 03:09:00.160
[Guest 1]: no longer a bad thing, right? So that was the other thing. So this is where people like A.N.

03:09:00.160 --> 03:09:06.800
[Guest 1]: Verma and all are very, very important because you can de-license industry overnight by the

03:09:06.800 --> 03:09:13.120
[Guest 1]: stroke of a pen, right? But to make sure that foreign manufacturers, whether it is Pepsi or

03:09:13.120 --> 03:09:18.320
[Guest 1]: General Motors or whoever, actually come into the country and are willing to set up plant and are

03:09:18.320 --> 03:09:23.280
[Guest 1]: willing to engage with you, that requires a fair bit of government maneuvering, starting with very

03:09:23.280 --> 03:09:28.720
[Guest 1]: credible signaling of, we are open for business. And they did that very well. So they had like a

03:09:28.720 --> 03:09:33.760
[Guest 1]: foreign investment board, which was set up under the Prime Minister's office. And A.N. Verma was

03:09:33.760 --> 03:09:38.800
[Guest 1]: like the coordinating person for that. So these were the things that kind of happened immediately

03:09:38.800 --> 03:09:43.040
[Guest 1]: in a period of one month. Now, a lot more happened, you know, before and after that,

03:09:43.040 --> 03:09:48.640
[Guest 1]: but this would be my quick summary of it. And I should point out here that to my

03:09:48.640 --> 03:09:54.320
[Amit Varma]: listeners that A.N. Verma is not a relative of mine. He is another Verma. And as for import

03:09:54.320 --> 03:10:00.400
[Amit Varma]: tariffs being sort of attacks on foreign producers, there are also attacks on domestic consumers.

03:10:00.400 --> 03:10:04.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's a scene in the unseen right there, but that's a whole new story. What did

03:10:04.480 --> 03:10:08.400
[Amit Varma]: we not do? Because it seems here that people might well ask that, oh, you say we've, you know,

03:10:08.400 --> 03:10:12.960
[Amit Varma]: dismantled the license and permit Raj, but there's still so much bureaucracy all around us. For

03:10:12.960 --> 03:10:16.880
[Amit Varma]: example, I did an episode with our mutual friend, Madhu Menon, long, long back on restaurant

03:10:16.880 --> 03:10:21.760
[Amit Varma]: regulations. And he pointed out that, you know, when he ran a restaurant, he had to apply for,

03:10:21.760 --> 03:10:27.520
[Amit Varma]: I think, some 40 licenses a month or whatever. So there was one regulation that he could only have

03:10:27.520 --> 03:10:32.560
[Amit Varma]: one entry into his restaurant, only one door. And I think that was from the excise people because

03:10:32.560 --> 03:10:37.280
[Amit Varma]: they wanted to regulate the flow of alcohol. So only one door and the fire safety regulation said

03:10:37.280 --> 03:10:41.120
[Amit Varma]: you have to have multiple doors. So the point is, it doesn't matter what he does. He's breaking the

03:10:41.120 --> 03:10:45.040
[Amit Varma]: law. It doesn't matter which of those two laws he's breaking. He's paying a bribe anyway.

03:10:45.040 --> 03:10:49.200
[Amit Varma]: So we have tons of those also. They're a little bit different. I mean,

03:10:49.200 --> 03:10:55.200
[Guest 1]: this is union government trying to centrally control who does business where and how they

03:10:55.200 --> 03:11:00.720
[Guest 1]: do their business, which is obviously much easier to reform overnight by the union government,

03:11:00.720 --> 03:11:07.040
[Guest 1]: right? Versus a lot of land use and, you know, this kind of, you know, restaurant regulation or

03:11:07.040 --> 03:11:11.840
[Guest 1]: school licensing regulation, which tends to be usually at the local level and sometimes at the

03:11:11.840 --> 03:11:16.240
[Guest 1]: state level. Right. So I think there is a fundamental difference between the two,

03:11:16.240 --> 03:11:20.400
[Guest 1]: the kind of distortionary, like, you know, this is a list of essential commodities,

03:11:20.400 --> 03:11:24.640
[Guest 1]: and now I'm no longer going to control the price of sugar, which I shouldn't have centrally

03:11:24.640 --> 03:11:29.120
[Guest 1]: controlled in the first place. But should I want to decontrol that? It's a stroke of a pen

03:11:29.120 --> 03:11:35.840
[Guest 1]: versus, you know, 500 different districts imposing their own specific small distortionary permit

03:11:35.840 --> 03:11:40.640
[Guest 1]: systems that they have. I think those are fundamentally different things. I don't think

03:11:40.640 --> 03:11:46.240
[Guest 1]: the 91 reforms were even aiming towards that. I mean, ideologically and as an economic vision,

03:11:46.240 --> 03:11:50.160
[Guest 1]: they would have agreed with it. But I don't think they were aiming towards fixing this kind of

03:11:50.160 --> 03:11:54.800
[Guest 1]: restaurant regulation, nor could they have done it. It was just completely beyond their purview.

03:11:54.800 --> 03:11:59.600
[Guest 1]: You know, that is a certain some of it is not even legislation. Some of it is delegated

03:11:59.600 --> 03:12:06.480
[Guest 1]: legislation. Right. There'll be like a restaurants management or in safety act, for instance. Right.

03:12:06.480 --> 03:12:10.000
[Guest 1]: And then the devil is in the details. Right. There will be like this one thing that says

03:12:10.000 --> 03:12:14.960
[Guest 1]: power to make rules. OK. And they've delegated the power to make rules to the local executive

03:12:14.960 --> 03:12:20.960
[Guest 1]: authority. And now those guys are making rules willy nilly, you know, which is completely bizarre

03:12:20.960 --> 03:12:25.920
[Guest 1]: and absurd, which is, you know, you need one, you need a single point of egress or you need two

03:12:25.920 --> 03:12:30.400
[Guest 1]: points of egress, you know, so on and so forth. So I don't think that could have been done by this

03:12:30.400 --> 03:12:35.280
[Guest 1]: kind of reform. And it frankly can't be done by Modi either. It just needs to be committed at the

03:12:35.280 --> 03:12:39.760
[Amit Varma]: local level. Rent seeking Zindabad. But the larger question I was getting at is what are the

03:12:39.760 --> 03:12:44.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of reforms that we didn't do and which, you know, still need to be done in a continuation of

03:12:44.960 --> 03:12:50.480
[Amit Varma]: the same spirit, like land, labor, blah, blah, blah. Ajay. So, as I said a short while ago,

03:12:50.480 --> 03:12:55.840
[Guest 2]: there is a stroke of the pen problem, which is just get out of the way. I feel a lot more needs

03:12:55.840 --> 03:13:02.160
[Guest 2]: to be done. There is a highly inappropriate interference by the Indian state in the affairs

03:13:02.160 --> 03:13:06.560
[Guest 2]: of everyday people. You know, there are consenting adults doing things and there is no role for the

03:13:06.560 --> 03:13:13.600
[Guest 2]: state to interfere. And there is a large class of impediments that are on the books or on the laws

03:13:13.600 --> 03:13:19.200
[Guest 2]: as of today. And then part two is the state capacity problem where there are things that

03:13:19.200 --> 03:13:24.160
[Guest 2]: will inevitably be done by states. And it could be financial regulation. It could be

03:13:25.120 --> 03:13:33.520
[Guest 2]: land title systems. It would be a taxation system and so on. And we did not begin understanding how

03:13:33.520 --> 03:13:38.960
[Guest 2]: to run a tax administration system. So, you know, for some time there was a period where the tax

03:13:38.960 --> 03:13:44.720
[Guest 2]: rates were coming down and tax laws were becoming a little insane. And the tax administration was

03:13:44.720 --> 03:13:52.080
[Guest 2]: never really fixed. We didn't build a high quality law to govern the checks and balances of how tax

03:13:52.080 --> 03:13:57.680
[Guest 2]: administrators behave. So, there is a whole lot of discretion in the hands of tax administrators.

03:13:57.680 --> 03:14:02.480
[Guest 2]: And then it depends on the character of the leadership. So, depending on how the leadership

03:14:02.480 --> 03:14:09.360
[Guest 2]: changes, the demands made upon these agencies can change. And that's a very dangerous place to be

03:14:09.360 --> 03:14:16.800
[Guest 2]: as a society. So, the checks and balances upon agencies, officers need to be coded into laws,

03:14:16.800 --> 03:14:21.920
[Guest 2]: not just left to good sense. Because the first lesson we know in politics is that you can't count

03:14:21.920 --> 03:14:26.000
[Guest 2]: on good sense emerging out of a liberal democratic system of elections.

03:14:26.000 --> 03:14:33.120
[Amit Varma]: So, if we look at the consequences of the reforms, you know, what are the metrics by which

03:14:33.120 --> 03:14:38.000
[Amit Varma]: we can say that, you know, these reforms work? Like, obviously, there are literally hundreds of

03:14:38.000 --> 03:14:43.200
[Amit Varma]: millions of people lifted out of poverty. Like Nitin Pai once pointed out that with every 1%

03:14:43.200 --> 03:14:47.840
[Amit Varma]: rise in the GDP, 2 million people come out of poverty. I think he subsequently revised that

03:14:47.840 --> 03:14:53.280
[Amit Varma]: figure to say that it's more, which tells you the enormous power of this. 3 million people,

03:14:53.280 --> 03:14:58.560
[Amit Varma]: Shruti points out, lifting three fingers, which is absolutely phenomenal. At the same time,

03:14:58.560 --> 03:15:02.960
[Amit Varma]: you have critics saying that, oh, there is greater inequality, to which my point is that

03:15:02.960 --> 03:15:06.960
[Amit Varma]: inequality and poverty are very different things. That if you think they are the same thing,

03:15:06.960 --> 03:15:10.800
[Amit Varma]: you're thinking in a zero sum way that, oh, if the rich are getting richer, the poor must be

03:15:10.800 --> 03:15:15.280
[Amit Varma]: getting poorer. But actually, everybody can sort of become richer at the same time, though,

03:15:15.280 --> 03:15:19.280
[Amit Varma]: obviously, the rich will become richer by more. My metric is poverty. It's Mahatma Gandhi's

03:15:19.280 --> 03:15:24.000
[Amit Varma]: metric. How will this policy affect the poor? That's the first question that I always ask and

03:15:24.000 --> 03:15:29.120
[Amit Varma]: poverty has gone down massively. There's again, no disputing that. Has inequality increased? Yes,

03:15:29.120 --> 03:15:33.520
[Amit Varma]: inequality has increased at the same time as poverty has gone down. I don't see that as a

03:15:33.520 --> 03:15:38.400
[Amit Varma]: problem. It's the absolute numbers like, you know, Harry Frankfurt has a great book called On

03:15:38.400 --> 03:15:43.120
[Amit Varma]: Inequality, where he coined this term, the doctrine of sufficiency, where he said that we should

03:15:43.120 --> 03:15:48.960
[Amit Varma]: measure human progress by how many people achieve what he called a sufficient level to stay alive,

03:15:48.960 --> 03:15:54.000
[Amit Varma]: which is again attacking poverty. Like one question I often ask when it comes to inequality

03:15:54.000 --> 03:15:59.200
[Amit Varma]: is in which of these two countries would you rather be poor, Bangladesh or the USA? And

03:15:59.200 --> 03:16:04.240
[Amit Varma]: obviously, you'd rather be poor in the USA, but the USA has far greater levels of inequality

03:16:04.240 --> 03:16:09.120
[Amit Varma]: than Bangladesh does. So I think inequality is really something that more advanced societies

03:16:09.120 --> 03:16:14.800
[Amit Varma]: can afford to worry about. But for us, our core problem is poverty and liberalization

03:16:14.800 --> 03:16:21.040
[Guest 1]: made a massive dent to that. What do you guys have to say? I agree. I mean, economic growth

03:16:21.040 --> 03:16:28.800
[Guest 1]: rates increased. We have very robust evidence that since late 80s, say 1988 onwards, you know,

03:16:28.800 --> 03:16:37.680
[Guest 1]: the kind of growth that took place. And from 1992, until say, you know, continuously for the next 20

03:16:37.680 --> 03:16:44.720
[Guest 1]: to 25 years, you have had consistently high growth rates on average, and it has lifted people out of

03:16:44.720 --> 03:16:49.760
[Guest 1]: poverty. The numbers you can quibble depending on when you start and finish, but the rough number

03:16:49.760 --> 03:16:54.960
[Guest 1]: people have come to agree upon is about a quarter of a billion people, 250 to 270 million people.

03:16:55.680 --> 03:17:02.880
[Guest 1]: The interesting thing is, it's not just this abstract thing. Every single socioeconomic group,

03:17:02.880 --> 03:17:08.240
[Guest 1]: the levels of income have increased. Every single socioeconomic group, right? So this is women,

03:17:08.240 --> 03:17:15.200
[Guest 1]: this is Dalits, this is minority religions, right? Muslims. This is across regions, even the poorest

03:17:15.200 --> 03:17:18.720
[Guest 1]: districts, the levels have increased, the richest districts, the levels have increased. So that is

03:17:18.720 --> 03:17:24.080
[Guest 1]: something I want to put out there, because I think there's some massive confusion on this issue of

03:17:24.080 --> 03:17:30.960
[Guest 1]: like poverty going away. This is across groups. And the evidence on this is very robust. And some

03:17:30.960 --> 03:17:35.760
[Guest 1]: of the work on this is like Amartya Lahiri has done work on this. You know, Paul Novosad has

03:17:35.760 --> 03:17:41.200
[Guest 1]: done work on this with Sam Asher. If you want to look at very specific, like sort of qualitative

03:17:41.200 --> 03:17:45.840
[Guest 1]: evidence, you have Chandrabhan Prasad, who has talked about how Dalits have specifically benefited

03:17:45.840 --> 03:17:50.720
[Guest 1]: from liberalization and how like the Dalit entrepreneurial movement really took off and,

03:17:50.720 --> 03:17:55.760
[Guest 1]: you know, so on and so forth. And there's also upward social mobility in virtually every socioeconomic

03:17:55.760 --> 03:17:59.840
[Guest 1]: group. So that's one thing I want to put out there. I'll tell you the margins on which the

03:17:59.840 --> 03:18:06.240
[Guest 1]: inequality part bothers me. OK, just regular wage inequality increasing, you're right. It's not the

03:18:06.240 --> 03:18:11.680
[Guest 1]: greatest priority for India or Indians, and that doesn't matter to me. For me, the kind of inequality

03:18:11.680 --> 03:18:18.400
[Guest 1]: which is very problematic is the crony capitalist inequality we are seeing today. You still need so

03:18:18.400 --> 03:18:24.400
[Guest 1]: many permits to start a business, right? Or you need this army of lawyers to escape the taxman.

03:18:24.400 --> 03:18:30.240
[Guest 1]: Otherwise, you know, the tax authority, the discretionary crap and wiretaps and raids is

03:18:30.240 --> 03:18:36.800
[Guest 1]: just going to the full force of the state is going to be upon you. So only rich people or people who

03:18:36.800 --> 03:18:46.160
[Guest 1]: are privileged can afford all that. Right. So the main means to economic growth is that regular folks

03:18:46.160 --> 03:18:51.360
[Guest 1]: can partake in greater, you know, in the gains from trade, from greater economic activity.

03:18:51.360 --> 03:18:57.440
[Guest 1]: Right. And if the barriers to entry are so high that regular folks cannot enter that and only

03:18:57.440 --> 03:19:01.920
[Guest 1]: people who are from business families or really big businesses and, you know, your Adani's and

03:19:01.920 --> 03:19:09.520
[Guest 1]: Ambani's and Tata's can get into it, then we are in very, very big trouble long term. That kind of

03:19:09.520 --> 03:19:15.680
[Guest 1]: inequality really bothers me. So the second kind of inequality that kind of really bothers me

03:19:15.680 --> 03:19:21.520
[Guest 1]: is the barriers of access to entry when it comes to business. Right. So for economic growth to lift

03:19:21.520 --> 03:19:26.000
[Guest 1]: people out of poverty, we need regular people to be able to partake in the gains from trade,

03:19:26.000 --> 03:19:30.560
[Guest 1]: from what's happening in the economy, in this liberalized economy. And if you are going to

03:19:30.560 --> 03:19:35.520
[Guest 1]: bring lots and lots of permits and barriers and not only permits and barriers, but like the entire

03:19:35.520 --> 03:19:41.600
[Guest 1]: rule book where the state and its coercion comes crashing down on you in terms of taxation and GST

03:19:41.600 --> 03:19:48.880
[Guest 1]: and wiretaps and raids, then you are in trouble because it means that regular people cannot enter

03:19:48.880 --> 03:19:55.760
[Guest 1]: the zone of private enterprise and make money off of it. And only privileged people, you know,

03:19:55.760 --> 03:20:01.280
[Guest 1]: kids from business families or even large business houses are the only people who can, you know,

03:20:01.280 --> 03:20:06.400
[Guest 1]: partake in this kind of economic activity and actually make money. That kind of inequality

03:20:06.400 --> 03:20:12.480
[Guest 1]: really bothers me. The other thing which I have worried about a lot during the pandemic is

03:20:14.880 --> 03:20:19.920
[Guest 1]: when we say we lifted 270 million people out of poverty, it's not like overnight they became rich.

03:20:19.920 --> 03:20:23.440
[Guest 1]: It's that, you know, we've eliminated some extreme levels of poverty. We've increased

03:20:23.440 --> 03:20:27.840
[Guest 1]: the number of job opportunities and so on. But what we've realized during the pandemic is you

03:20:27.840 --> 03:20:33.440
[Guest 1]: have this kind of lockdown or your city stopped functioning or, you know, the top 20 percent of

03:20:33.440 --> 03:20:38.400
[Guest 1]: income earners who are responsible for the, you know, top 45 to 50 percent of consumer spending,

03:20:38.400 --> 03:20:42.880
[Guest 1]: they stopped spending money. And now everything has come to a grinding halt and all these people

03:20:42.880 --> 03:20:49.440
[Guest 1]: have slipped back into poverty. I believe about 60 to 70 million people have slipped back into

03:20:50.000 --> 03:20:55.520
[Guest 1]: some kind of poverty over nine, 10 months of sustained, you know, lack of employment and,

03:20:55.520 --> 03:21:02.000
[Guest 1]: you know, lack of social protection and so on. I think on those margins, some attention does need

03:21:02.000 --> 03:21:09.760
[Guest 1]: to be paid to how we think about inequality, how we think about barriers to entry and any system

03:21:09.760 --> 03:21:15.440
[Guest 1]: where a very small group of elite people are responsible for consumption and like kind of

03:21:15.440 --> 03:21:20.560
[Guest 1]: act as the engines of growth in the economy is not very sustainable. Right. And we've sort of

03:21:20.560 --> 03:21:24.880
[Amit Varma]: seen that through the pandemic. Yeah, it's fascinating. And both the kinds of inequality

03:21:24.880 --> 03:21:29.920
[Amit Varma]: you speak of are actually inequalities that I agree are problematic and that are a result of

03:21:29.920 --> 03:21:35.360
[Amit Varma]: not enough reforms of liberalization, really not going far enough. And, you know, it's still

03:21:35.360 --> 03:21:39.840
[Amit Varma]: treating sort of citizens as subjects. Only some are privileged subjects. You know, some

03:21:39.840 --> 03:21:44.400
[Amit Varma]: pigs are more equal than others, as the case may be. And even when we speak of rich people

03:21:44.400 --> 03:21:48.400
[Amit Varma]: benefiting, one of the trends that we've seen in the last few years is rich people actually

03:21:48.400 --> 03:21:52.880
[Amit Varma]: leaving the country en masse, which tells you that there is still a lot of work to be done.

03:21:52.880 --> 03:21:59.760
[Guest 2]: So I have a perspective on this problem. I think that every business has a certain fixed cost

03:22:00.560 --> 03:22:08.080
[Guest 2]: of lawyers and accountants and political protection. And the fixed cost is so high

03:22:08.080 --> 03:22:15.440
[Guest 2]: in the modern environment of ever more harsh rules and criminal clauses and electronic surveillance

03:22:15.440 --> 03:22:23.600
[Guest 2]: and dystopian data world that you've got to literally be hundreds of crore to pay for that

03:22:23.600 --> 03:22:28.240
[Guest 2]: minimum bar of protection. So conceptually, what has happened is that there was an older,

03:22:28.240 --> 03:22:34.960
[Guest 2]: kinder, gentler India where it was meaningful to be a one crore business, a five crore business,

03:22:34.960 --> 03:22:40.000
[Guest 2]: a 10 crore business. It's become harder and harder to do that because the machinery of the state is

03:22:40.000 --> 03:22:47.760
[Guest 2]: now deeply in the claws of each firm. And then there is a fixed cost of protection. So you've

03:22:47.760 --> 03:22:52.400
[Guest 2]: got to be a certain size, then you can pay for that protection. Or it's like a Chinese Communist

03:22:52.400 --> 03:22:59.200
[Guest 2]: Party situation that you've got to co-opt the ruling party and get that protection. But beyond

03:22:59.200 --> 03:23:03.840
[Guest 2]: that, you've got to be very big to pay for those fixed costs. So there's a hollowing out of the

03:23:03.840 --> 03:23:08.480
[Guest 2]: middle. And that also links to the phenomenon of the rich leaving. Because if you are in the zone

03:23:08.480 --> 03:23:13.280
[Guest 2]: of, you know, running a hundred crore business, then you might feel that I'm better off doing

03:23:13.280 --> 03:23:17.280
[Amit Varma]: this in London. Fair point. Shruti, my next question is to you. And it's about something

03:23:17.280 --> 03:23:22.080
[Amit Varma]: interesting you pointed out, which gives me an opportunity to talk about what might be a

03:23:22.080 --> 03:23:27.040
[Amit Varma]: distinction that people need to make. Where at one point in your fabulous opening essay of the

03:23:27.040 --> 03:23:32.800
[Amit Varma]: 1991 project, you write, quote, since 1991, the union government revenue has increased 25 times

03:23:32.800 --> 03:23:36.560
[Amit Varma]: and state government revenue has increased 28 times in nominal terms and about four times in

03:23:36.560 --> 03:23:42.640
[Amit Varma]: real terms. Embracing markets allowed the Indian government to increase its welfare spending,

03:23:42.640 --> 03:23:46.720
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And many people who make simplistic arguments of market versus state,

03:23:46.720 --> 03:23:52.320
[Amit Varma]: just assume that you are sort of talking about, you know, one extreme, that if you want markets

03:23:52.320 --> 03:23:56.240
[Amit Varma]: to flourish, you don't want the state at all. Whereas my point as far as the Indian state has

03:23:56.240 --> 03:24:00.160
[Amit Varma]: been concerned is that listen, the Indian state can carry out whatever welfare activities it wants

03:24:00.160 --> 03:24:05.840
[Amit Varma]: to just get out of the way of private enterprise, just let private enterprise function. And the

03:24:05.840 --> 03:24:11.440
[Amit Varma]: figures that you came up with seems to indicate that the two can happen together, that the welfare

03:24:11.440 --> 03:24:17.120
[Amit Varma]: state will actually be a better funded, and therefore, hopefully, you know, a more inclusive

03:24:17.120 --> 03:24:21.760
[Amit Varma]: welfare state, if there is growth in the economy, if private enterprises are allowed to flourish,

03:24:21.760 --> 03:24:27.680
[Guest 1]: because that's where the money comes from. So, you know, this is fundamental Adam Smith

03:24:27.680 --> 03:24:33.280
[Guest 1]: kind of business, right? I mean, the size of your pie has to grow. Otherwise, what you're

03:24:33.280 --> 03:24:37.440
[Guest 1]: going to get into is if the pie doesn't grow, and you keep talking about how we split it and

03:24:37.440 --> 03:24:41.680
[Guest 1]: redistribute it, there are going to be more and more people who spend a lot of money, you know,

03:24:41.680 --> 03:24:48.480
[Guest 1]: classic rent seeking literature on how to redistribute this pie. And the smaller the pie,

03:24:48.480 --> 03:24:53.680
[Guest 1]: or the less the pie grows, the more conflict you're going to have in society on how we split

03:24:53.680 --> 03:24:59.920
[Guest 1]: this pie, right? If the pie keeps growing, right? Yes, it's true that every group may not get the

03:24:59.920 --> 03:25:05.200
[Guest 1]: exact same share of the pie may not always get the you know, may not always partake in the same way

03:25:05.200 --> 03:25:10.720
[Guest 1]: in the gains from trade, but everyone will benefit. So that's number one. The second is,

03:25:10.720 --> 03:25:15.920
[Guest 1]: I think it's very important, the kinds of things that Ajay and I have talked about so far,

03:25:15.920 --> 03:25:21.120
[Guest 1]: we're talking about some fundamental structural changes in the economy, right? And structural

03:25:21.120 --> 03:25:25.200
[Guest 1]: changes in the economy are never painless. I mean, they're painful at the highest levels of

03:25:25.200 --> 03:25:30.880
[Guest 1]: privilege to the lowest levels of, you know, privilege. So you can be the controller of

03:25:30.880 --> 03:25:35.360
[Guest 1]: cement or sugar prices, and the next day, suddenly your position goes away, and you don't have a job

03:25:35.360 --> 03:25:39.360
[Guest 1]: anymore. And of course, your job is secure, but you have to do something else, which is not as

03:25:39.360 --> 03:25:44.480
[Guest 1]: status, high status or powerful. Or you could be a poor guy who just loses his job, because now

03:25:44.480 --> 03:25:49.200
[Guest 1]: there's a pandemic or something else has happened, or now there are no more STD boots, you know,

03:25:49.200 --> 03:25:52.720
[Guest 1]: for instance, with the telecom revolution. So if you were someone who was running an STD booth,

03:25:52.720 --> 03:25:55.440
[Guest 1]: now you suddenly find yourself out of a job, or you're someone who's a typist.

03:25:57.200 --> 03:26:04.320
[Guest 1]: We do need to think when we are people who are talking about large structural changes in society,

03:26:04.320 --> 03:26:11.360
[Guest 1]: we do genuinely need to think about how do we manage the structural change socially?

03:26:11.920 --> 03:26:16.400
[Guest 1]: What do we do when firms go bankrupt? What do we do when entire sectors become

03:26:16.400 --> 03:26:21.920
[Guest 1]: obsolete or irrelevant? What happens when masses of people come out of agriculture

03:26:21.920 --> 03:26:27.440
[Guest 1]: and move to cities with no social protection whatsoever? So of course, in the longer run,

03:26:27.440 --> 03:26:31.600
[Guest 1]: we need to make sure that our cities are well equipped with jobs and housing and everything.

03:26:31.600 --> 03:26:35.360
[Guest 1]: But in the very short run, what are we supposed to do with these people? And these are hundreds

03:26:35.360 --> 03:26:40.320
[Guest 1]: of millions of people, it's not a small number. When I say that Nehru didn't make investments in

03:26:40.320 --> 03:26:45.040
[Guest 1]: health and primary education, and we need a massive investment, that's going to cost money.

03:26:46.320 --> 03:26:49.840
[Guest 1]: If you're going to spend in a big way on health in India, post pandemic,

03:26:49.840 --> 03:26:53.840
[Guest 1]: 2-3% of the GDP, that's money that the government simply doesn't have.

03:26:54.480 --> 03:26:59.040
[Guest 1]: So in some sense, everybody, whether you're a statist or not a statist,

03:26:59.040 --> 03:27:05.600
[Guest 1]: has to have a commitment to economic growth, right? You want to have good measures to

03:27:05.600 --> 03:27:10.720
[Guest 1]: battle climate change, right? Or you want to do greater amounts of mining, it doesn't matter,

03:27:10.720 --> 03:27:16.480
[Guest 1]: you could be on ideological ends of every spectrum, but on whatever you are, greater

03:27:16.480 --> 03:27:21.440
[Guest 1]: economic growth is probably going to be able to make one or both possible, right? So that

03:27:21.440 --> 03:27:26.960
[Guest 1]: is something I want to put out there. We genuinely lack a commitment to economic growth in India,

03:27:26.960 --> 03:27:32.080
[Guest 1]: it's become very partisan and tribal. The opportunity cost is just enormous. I mean,

03:27:32.080 --> 03:27:37.440
[Guest 1]: the whole every, you know, 1% increase in GDP per capita lives 3 million people out of poverty,

03:27:37.440 --> 03:27:42.560
[Guest 1]: you know, per year and so on. So in about 10 to 15 years, you can eliminate extreme poverty in

03:27:42.560 --> 03:27:49.600
[Guest 1]: India, right? So the opportunity cost of not conducting reforms of not creating the kind of

03:27:49.600 --> 03:27:55.120
[Guest 1]: institutional infrastructure that you need for economic growth in India, is that you are now

03:27:55.120 --> 03:28:00.480
[Guest 1]: leaving behind 2-300 million people in extreme poverty that you could have avoided. So this is

03:28:00.480 --> 03:28:05.760
[Guest 1]: something that is, it's so difficult to explain to ordinary people who are not economists,

03:28:05.760 --> 03:28:10.400
[Guest 1]: what is at stake? Because what is at stake is invisible, right? Those people were poor before

03:28:10.400 --> 03:28:14.160
[Guest 1]: they continue to be poor. So people don't realize that there was an opportunity to actually lift

03:28:14.160 --> 03:28:19.360
[Guest 1]: them out of poverty. So I think that is the big thing when we talk about any kinds of reforms.

03:28:19.360 --> 03:28:24.880
[Guest 1]: Everything else is detail, right? And even Ajay and I disagree on a lot of these things. If Ajay

03:28:24.880 --> 03:28:29.360
[Guest 1]: and I sat down to talk about bankruptcy or SEBI, I'm sure we would like have lots of different

03:28:29.360 --> 03:28:37.920
[Guest 1]: ideas. But the commitment remains that economic growth is the base idea on which everything else

03:28:37.920 --> 03:28:43.120
[Guest 1]: must follow. And if you don't have a commitment to economic growth and increasing the size of the pie,

03:28:43.120 --> 03:28:48.320
[Guest 1]: which by the way, can only be done by greater trade, division of labor and specialization,

03:28:48.320 --> 03:28:53.280
[Guest 1]: right? That's the fundamentals. If you don't have that, if you don't get rid of permits and

03:28:53.280 --> 03:28:58.960
[Guest 1]: institutions, which will allow for greater trade and the size of the pie to grow, if that commitment

03:28:58.960 --> 03:29:03.920
[Guest 1]: is missing, India is just in deep trouble. And that commitment is missing. And we are in deep

03:29:03.920 --> 03:29:11.440
[Guest 1]: trouble. Sorry, I'm just very upset about this. I have a twist on what Shruti just said,

03:29:12.480 --> 03:29:16.640
[Guest 2]: which is the same idea, but it's worth reinforcing from a slightly different angle.

03:29:16.640 --> 03:29:20.400
[Guest 2]: In the field of public finance, there is a lot of discussion around the tax GDP ratio.

03:29:20.960 --> 03:29:26.640
[Guest 2]: Okay, so everybody universally believes that higher tax GDP ratios are better.

03:29:26.640 --> 03:29:34.240
[Guest 2]: Okay, Ila Patnaik has a bracing insight on this subject. She says, suppose you had

03:29:35.600 --> 03:29:44.240
[Guest 2]: 14 rupees of taxation on a 100 rupee GDP versus 14 rupees of taxation on a 200 GDP,

03:29:45.360 --> 03:29:52.560
[Guest 2]: i.e. that the tax GDP ratio went down by half. The second case is Pareto superior to the first case.

03:29:52.560 --> 03:29:59.520
[Guest 2]: In the second case, the people had 200 rupees of GDP, okay, and the state had only 14. So,

03:30:00.080 --> 03:30:08.800
[Guest 2]: 14,100 versus 14,200. 14,200 is always better. It is a very twisted kind of

03:30:09.360 --> 03:30:14.400
[Guest 2]: development-ish discourse to think that the tax GDP ratio should be always raised.

03:30:14.400 --> 03:30:20.960
[Guest 2]: And in fact, there are many, many, many aspects in which tax policy and tax administration today

03:30:20.960 --> 03:30:26.080
[Guest 2]: are designed in a hostile way, in a way that favors the arbitrary power of tax inspectors

03:30:26.080 --> 03:30:32.160
[Guest 2]: and officials, and that precisely expresses this kind of tension, that you're better off

03:30:33.200 --> 03:30:38.320
[Guest 2]: letting it go. You're better off letting a private economy thrive and staying at 14

03:30:38.320 --> 03:30:43.920
[Guest 2]: rupees of government revenue. If GDP will go from 100 to 200, we should be delighted,

03:30:43.920 --> 03:30:49.840
[Guest 2]: we should be exuberant. So, we shouldn't obsess on the tax GDP ratio, we should obsess on GDP,

03:30:49.840 --> 03:30:56.160
[Guest 2]: the greatest good of economics is to get GDP up. And arguably, in a large part of the Indian state

03:30:56.160 --> 03:31:00.240
[Guest 2]: today, the way forward is to get the tax GDP down, not up.

03:31:00.960 --> 03:31:06.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's, again, a fantastic point. And, you know, it's this sort of reflexive acceptance of

03:31:06.640 --> 03:31:10.880
[Amit Varma]: a metric without even really thinking about it. You know, whenever somebody speaks about tax

03:31:10.880 --> 03:31:14.160
[Amit Varma]: collections of the government going up, I'm like, why is that a good thing? You have more

03:31:14.160 --> 03:31:18.320
[Amit Varma]: money in the hands of the predatory state instead of in the hands of the people where I would

03:31:18.320 --> 03:31:21.760
[Amit Varma]: rather have it. But that's a separate point. You weren't really making that and I completely agree

03:31:21.760 --> 03:31:26.400
[Amit Varma]: with both of you that economic growth is the thing and the way to get there is through economic

03:31:26.400 --> 03:31:32.000
[Amit Varma]: freedom. And the point is, people miss the humanitarian consequences. Like I have tremendous

03:31:32.000 --> 03:31:36.560
[Amit Varma]: anger for the policies of the past and the policymakers of the past in past decades,

03:31:36.560 --> 03:31:42.480
[Amit Varma]: which kept people poor for decades, literally. And that's an unseen effect. You don't see that

03:31:42.480 --> 03:31:46.720
[Amit Varma]: if you're poor today, you don't see the counterfactual of how things might have been

03:31:46.720 --> 03:31:51.680
[Amit Varma]: had things spanned out differently, which is why it's not about numbers. People think of GDP. Oh,

03:31:51.680 --> 03:31:57.440
[Amit Varma]: it's a number, a percent or percent. It has a real human cost on real human lives. And that's

03:31:57.440 --> 03:32:00.560
[Amit Varma]: something we need to consider. We're kind of running out of time. So I'll end with a final

03:32:00.560 --> 03:32:05.600
[Amit Varma]: question for both of you that, you know, we can look at the 1991 reforms either as a beacon of

03:32:05.600 --> 03:32:10.320
[Amit Varma]: hope that it lifted a quarter of a billion people out of poverty, which itself just for that

03:32:10.320 --> 03:32:15.360
[Amit Varma]: humanitarian reason is incredible. It empowered so many people with all the knock on effects of

03:32:15.360 --> 03:32:19.680
[Amit Varma]: that. Or we can look at everything that has happened since and that has happened in our

03:32:19.680 --> 03:32:24.960
[Amit Varma]: politics and the fact that the momentum has slowed and all of that as a cautionary tale,

03:32:24.960 --> 03:32:30.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, you can see the events of the past 25 years in both these ways. And you know,

03:32:30.480 --> 03:32:34.720
[Amit Varma]: one view would be that, hey, okay, 91 was a good moment, but look at what's happened since and we

03:32:34.720 --> 03:32:39.520
[Amit Varma]: are sliding backwards. Another way of looking at it could be that there was a process, there was

03:32:39.520 --> 03:32:45.680
[Amit Varma]: a movement towards freedom, the arc of history was bending one way, and we've got to work for that to

03:32:45.680 --> 03:32:52.400
[Amit Varma]: continue. So, you know, are you more hopeful or more despairing when you look at what might lie

03:32:52.400 --> 03:33:00.480
[Guest 2]: ahead of us, say in the next 15 years? I feel that the most important thing that changed

03:33:00.480 --> 03:33:08.400
[Guest 2]: out of the outcomes of 1991 to 2011 is that there was a certain despondence and pessimism

03:33:08.400 --> 03:33:17.520
[Guest 2]: about India. So, you know, we had a fabulous freedom movement. It was really a historic

03:33:17.520 --> 03:33:23.920
[Guest 2]: moment in India's history in terms of the decency and the moral qualities of the people who led the

03:33:23.920 --> 03:33:29.920
[Guest 2]: freedom movement. And then after that, while there was a bit of a spurt in Nehru's years of GDP

03:33:29.920 --> 03:33:36.000
[Guest 2]: growth, it didn't work out great after that. And then we had this long period 1962 to 77,

03:33:36.000 --> 03:33:44.480
[Guest 2]: which was truly gloomy. Standing in 1977, the Indian elite had run out of the skip in its step.

03:33:44.480 --> 03:33:50.240
[Guest 2]: So, this was no longer the country of Gandhiji and Nehru and Ramanujan and Tagore. This was the

03:33:50.240 --> 03:33:55.840
[Guest 2]: country that was battered and bruised and starting to question itself that, is there something wrong

03:33:55.840 --> 03:34:01.520
[Guest 2]: with us? You know, so that's why the biting phrase, the Hindu rate of growth, that is there something

03:34:01.520 --> 03:34:08.320
[Guest 2]: about being Hindu that messes with us and that damages our ability to do well and to be as great

03:34:08.320 --> 03:34:15.760
[Guest 2]: and as cool a country as anything else that the world can do. I'm thrilled to bits that the 1991

03:34:15.760 --> 03:34:23.600
[Guest 2]: to 2011 period proves that we in India have the creativity, the energy, the intellectual capacity,

03:34:23.600 --> 03:34:28.320
[Guest 2]: the emotional capacity to really do amazing things. The kind of things that got done in

03:34:28.320 --> 03:34:34.880
[Guest 2]: India in that period, I think have forever settled that question that there is nothing wrong here.

03:34:34.880 --> 03:34:40.000
[Guest 2]: There's nothing wrong with us. We are every bit as good as anybody else in the world. And we just

03:34:40.000 --> 03:34:45.600
[Guest 2]: got to get our shift together. So, yes, we've had a difficult time after that. And we need to

03:34:45.600 --> 03:34:52.160
[Guest 2]: work hard on figuring out how to put this engine back on the road. But I feel it was just one of

03:34:52.160 --> 03:34:59.120
[Guest 2]: the most important episodes in India's history. And it pours concrete on the idea of India.

03:34:59.120 --> 03:35:04.560
[Guest 2]: It teaches us that the basic machinery of the idea of India can be made to work

03:35:04.560 --> 03:35:08.000
[Guest 2]: and it can deliver growth and prosperity and decency.

03:35:09.840 --> 03:35:15.840
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I mean, I of course agree with everything Ajay said. I would say what gives me hope is

03:35:15.840 --> 03:35:21.600
[Guest 1]: one, of course, India fundamentally changed. But to me, the hopeful thing is it gives power back to

03:35:21.600 --> 03:35:28.160
[Guest 1]: the people, right? There is something very basic and happy about that. The idea that my grandmother

03:35:28.160 --> 03:35:34.560
[Guest 1]: doesn't have to separate like, you know, kankar from rice, right? Or, you know, anybody who wishes

03:35:34.560 --> 03:35:39.680
[Guest 1]: to get a CD of Pink Floyd, you know, should they be able to afford one? All these sound like first

03:35:39.680 --> 03:35:44.240
[Guest 1]: world problems. But you can imagine this at every level, right? Like a schoolgirl wanting to get

03:35:44.240 --> 03:35:50.800
[Guest 1]: like a schoolgirl wanting to buy a bicycle, right? Or her father wanting to make his own bicycle and

03:35:50.800 --> 03:35:58.720
[Guest 1]: sell it or repair it. These are just things that are magical to me, okay? That this transformation

03:35:58.720 --> 03:36:04.720
[Guest 1]: happened, that regular folks just had so much more control over what they wore, what they bought,

03:36:04.720 --> 03:36:10.720
[Guest 1]: what they sold, how they consumed, right? That they could buy a packet of atta or sugar in a

03:36:10.720 --> 03:36:16.400
[Guest 1]: shop without being worried about it, right? Or they didn't have to stand in line for hours to get

03:36:16.400 --> 03:36:22.960
[Guest 1]: milk to feed their baby. These are things that one should not take for granted, given that not

03:36:22.960 --> 03:36:27.040
[Guest 1]: too long ago in Indian history, these were just not things that were possible. And they were not

03:36:27.040 --> 03:36:32.000
[Guest 1]: possible for a very long time and people were very despondent. So that gives me great hope that,

03:36:32.000 --> 03:36:36.960
[Guest 1]: you know, imagine if we managed to conduct land reforms and agricultural reforms and labor reforms,

03:36:36.960 --> 03:36:42.640
[Guest 1]: like the sky's the limit on when you give people control back over their economic choice and

03:36:42.640 --> 03:36:49.280
[Guest 1]: destinies. That I think is a very hopeful message. There are two things that make me very despondent.

03:36:49.280 --> 03:36:55.600
[Guest 1]: One is just the missed opportunity that we talked about. Every year that we kind of linger on and

03:36:55.600 --> 03:37:00.560
[Guest 1]: hang around and have these petty conversations about partisan politics and don't make these

03:37:00.560 --> 03:37:06.880
[Guest 1]: big bang, you know, economic changes happen is longer that people kind of, you know,

03:37:06.880 --> 03:37:12.160
[Guest 1]: hang around in poverty and lose life. And they live a few years too less and women don't get

